<FIRST>u i AM-GermanRefugees     08-08 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-German Refugees,0493</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bonn Closes Its East Berlin Mission Due To Refugee Overflow</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West German officials said the Bonn
government closed its East Berlin mission to the public Tuesday
because its capacities were ``completely exhausted.''
   The West German government accused East Germany of being
responsible for a wave of refugees seeking to leave their communist
homeland.
   Scores of East Germans have fled to West German diplomatic
missions in East Berlin; the Hungarian capital of Budapest and
Prague, Czechoslovakia.
   Bonn officials said 130 East German citizens are in the West
German mission in East Berlin and are refusing to leave, demanding
that East Germany allow them to emigrate.
   Claus Duisberg, an aide to Chancellor Helmut Kohl, called on
East Germany to ``create conditions ... that would give people
reason for staying.''
   A leading West German parliamentarian, Eduard Lintner, said East
German leader Erich Honecker should either initiate political
reforms or resign, a newspaper reported.
   ``Erich Honecker and his old men should finally leave,'' the
Cologne Express newspaper quoted Lintner as saying.
   East German officials have refused to adopt political reforms
like those under way in the Soviet Union, Poland and Hungary.
   Hundreds of East Germans have been trying to leave through
Hungary, which has been dismantling border barriers along its
frontier with Austria.
   Seventy-two East Germans who fled through Hungary arrived at a
temporary housing center in Giessen, West Germany, on Tuesday after
traveling by train from Vienna.
   News reports say about 200 East Germans are inside the West
German Embassy in Budapest, demanding that their government let
them move to the West.
   West German news reports say about 20 East Germans are inside
the West German mission in Prague.
   East Germany's state-run news agency ADN on Monday accused the
West German Embassy in Budapest of ``gross interference'' in East
German's internal affairs.
   West Germany summoned Lothar Glienke, head of the East German
diplomatic mission in Bonn, to the chancellery to protest the
statement, said West German government spokesman Herbert
Schmuelling.
   Schmuelling said West German officials also discussed the
situation at the East Berlin mission with Glienke and appealed to
the East German government to ``contribute to the solution of these
matters.''
   ``The federal government wants to continue its constructive
cooperation with the German Democratic Republic (East Germany)
despite this situation,'' Schmuelling said.
   West German officials said East Germany agreed not to arrest
refuge-seekers inside the East Berlin mission if they leave the
complex, but refused to guarantee they would be permitted to leave
the country.
   The West German newspaper Bild Zeitung reported the number of
East Germans who moved to West Germany _ both legally and illegally
_ increased dramatically since last year. It said the figure for
the first seven months of this year was 55,970 compared with 39,832
for all of last year.
</TEXT>
