<FIRST>u w AM-Obit-Mladek     08-08 0228</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Mladek,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Czech, IMF Official Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jan Victor Mladek, a member of
Czechoslovakia's last non-communist government and a retired
International Monetary Fund official, died of cancer at George
Washington University Hospital.
   Mladek, who was 77, died Monday.
   Mladek was also a founder of the Central and East European Art
Foundation, which promoted East European artists.
   Trained as an economist, he served in the anti-Nazi Czech army
in France and England before becoming head of the exile
Czechoslovakian government's monetary department in the Ministry of
Finance.
   He was vice chairman of the Czech delegation to the 1944 Bretton
Woods Conference, which planned Europe's postwar economy and where
the IMF, the worldwide lending agency, was created.
   An official in the finance ministry in the government of
Persident Eduard Benes after the war, Mladek represented
Czechoslovakia on the IMF executive board. He became the IMF's
deputy director of operations at its Washington headquarters after
the communists took power in Prague in 1948.
   He was head of the fund's central banking service for 14 years
before retiring in 1977.
   Mladek and his wife, Meda, established the art foundation in
Washington and helped mount shows of East and Central European art
at the city's Hirschorn and Corcoran art galleries.
   Born in Bochnia, Poland, in what was then the Austro-Hungarian
Empire, Mladek became a naturalized American citizen in 1960.
</TEXT>
