<FIRST>r a AM-PublisherQuits     08-08 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Publisher Quits,0328</SECOND>
<HEAD>Publisher Of Arizona Republic and Phoenix Gazette Steps Down</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY LOPEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pat Murphy, publisher of The Arizona Republic and
The Phoenix Gazette, resigned Tuesday, saying he felt it was time
to move on.
   ``I just turned 60 last week, and sometimes you ask yourself how
much time do you have left to do things you want to do?'' he said.
``I've had 3{ years as publisher and brought some terrific people _
managing editors and assistant managing editors _ on board.''
   ``I've gotten as much satisfaction as a publisher could have,''
he said in an interview, adding that it was time ``to take a
breather.''
   Murphy said he didn't know what he'd do next but was stepping
down immediately, trying to sell a screenplay and might write a
novel.
   Frank E. Russell, president of Central Newspapers Inc., the
Indianapolis company that controls the newspapers, said a search
would begin for a successor to Murphy, ``a person with a proven
track record as a publisher of a major metropolitan newspaper.''
   Central Newspapers is owned by the Pulliam family and includes
Vice President Dan Quayle as one of its owners. It owns Phoenix
Newspapers Inc., which was headed by Murphy and which publishes the
weekly Arizona Business Gazette as well as the daily Republic and
Gazette.
   Editors of the Republic, Gazette and Business Gazette will
report directly to Eugene S. Pulliam, publisher of The Indianapolis
Star and The Indianapolis News, until Murphy's successor is named,
said Bill Shover, director of public affairs for the Phoenix
newspapers.
   Murphy, a former columnist, took over the Phoenix newspapers on
March 11, 1986. He took an active role as publisher, describing
maverick Republican Gov. Evan Mecham as a ideological juggernaut
even as Mecham attacked the newspapers and their reporting.
   Mecham was ousted by a Senate Court of Impeachment last year but
found innocent on criminal charges.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
