<FIRST>r w PM-TreasuryBills     08-08 0165</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Treasury Bills,150</SECOND>
<HEAD>Treasury Rates Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates on short-term Treasury
securities are at their highest level in two weeks.
   The Treasury Department on Monday sold $6.6 billion in
three-month bills at an average discount rate of 7.94 percent, up
from 7.65 percent last week. Another $6.6 billion was sold in
six-month bills at an average discount rate of 7.70 percent, up
from 7.35 percent last week.
   The rates were the highest since July 24 when three-month bills
sold for 8.09 percent and six-month bills averaged 7.73 percent.
   The discount rates understate the actual return to investors _
8.21 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling for
$9,799.30 and 8.12 percent for a six-month bill selling for
$9,610.70.
   In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said Monday that the
average yield for one-year Treasury bills, the most popular index
for making changes in adjustable rate mortgages, fell to 7.73
percent last week, down from 7.86 percent the previous week.
</TEXT>
