<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-89 0302EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-RivkindResigns     08-08 0308</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rivkind Resigns,0316</SECOND>
<HEAD>Miami INS Director Rivkind Resigns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Perry Rivkind, the volatile Florida immigration
chief who ignored orders to deport Nicaraguans but sent home
Haitian boat people, announced his resignation.
   Rivkind, district INS director since 1983, said Monday he would
resign Aug. 21 to teach criminal justice at a small college in
Virginia.
   Three years ago Rivkind refused to send back a group of
Nicaraguan refugees and announed he was flouting U.S. policies that
treated the Nicaraguans the same as other Central Americans, who
have no special immigration status.
   The more than 800,000 Cubans in South Florida _ the largest
Cuban community anywhere except the city of Havana _ admired
Rivkind's anti-communism and enforcement of an open-door policy for
Cuban refugees. Thousands of Nicaraguan refugees also live in the
region.
   Rivkind said the criticism that hurt him most were claims by
Haitians in Miami that his adherence to the federal order to send
Haitian boat people back home _ while allowing Nicaraguans to stay
_ was racist.
   He said it was ``simply not true'' that under his term Haitians
were discriminated against. ``I think it's dangerous and
irresponsible to make statements about discrimination in a
community as volatile as this.''
   ``It's true that my relationship with Mr. Rivkind has been up
and down some days. Sometimes we are friends, another time we are
enemies,'' said the Rev. Gerard Jean-Juste, a leader of the
100,000-member Haitian community here. ``I hope that the next
district director to come will provide equal justice, equal
treatment to the Haitian refugees as is given to the Cubans.''
   Rivkind said he tired of being held to official government
positions.
   ``I am one who likes to speak out on social issues, and
government sometimes says don't speak out,'' said Rivkind, who will
teach at Patrick Henry Community College in Martinsville, Va.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
