<FIRST>u i BC-Ireland-U2     08-08 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Ireland-U2,0244</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guitarist Adam Clayton of U2 Rock Group Bailed on Drug Charge</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LON5 of Aug. 7</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Adam Clayton of the Irish rock group U2
has been charged with possession of marijuana.
   The 29-year-old bass guitarist, dressed all in black, appeared
briefly in Dublin's District Court on Monday but under Irish law
was not required to enter a plea.
   Clayton was arrested near his Dublin home Sunday night and
charged with possessing marijuana and with having the drug with the
intent to supply someone else, police told the court.
   Judge Desmond Windle ordered Clayton to post bail of $710 and to
return to court on Sept. 1.
   If convicted of possession of marijuana, Clayton faces a maximum
fine of $1,420. Police said there is no fixed penalty for a
conviction for possession of the drug with intent to supply, and
the judge usually takes into account the circumstances of the
arrest and the amount of drug involved.
   Det. Michael Moody of the Garda Siochana, Ireland's police
force, told the court that when the first charge was read to him,
Clayton replied: ``There was nothing found in my possession.''
Clayton made no comment when the second charge was put to him,
Moody said.
   The musician stood with his hands clasped behind his back facing
the judge as the detective gave his evidence.
   The British-born musician became an Irish citizen earlier this
year.
</TEXT>
