<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-89 0359EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-CubaArrests     08-08 0332</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cuba Arrests,0341</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wife Of Jailed Cuban Human Rights Activist Working For His Release</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GLORIA GOMEZ-CANTENS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department condemned the arrest of three
Cuban human rights activists, and a rights group said the
detentions confirmed Cuba's status as one of the world's ``most
rigidly totalitarian states.''
   Elizardo Sanchez, head of the Cuban Commission of Human Rights
and National Conciliation, was arrested early Sunday when about 20
security policemen showed up at his home soon after 5 a.m., his
wife Margarita said Monday.
   Hiram Abi Cobas, acting head of the Human Rights Party of Cuba,
and Hubert Jerez, president of the Jose Marti Commission on Human
rights, also were arrested, according to Ramon Cernuda, a Cuban
exile and book publisher here.
   There was no word on why authorities had detained the men.
   Mrs. Sanchez said friends are helping her work for her husband's
release.
   ``I haven't spoken to him yet,'' Mrs. Sanchez told The
Associated Press in a phone interview Monday. ``I spoke to my
brother-in-law this morning and he told me he was still in jail. My
mother-in-law is going to Villa Marista, where we think he is being
held.''
   Meanwhile, the State Department released a statement condemning
the arrest as a ``flagarant human rights violation.''
   ``We hope concerned members of the international community,
including the United Nations, will join us in condemning not only
Sanchez' arrest, but also the continued imprisonment of other
prominent human rights leaders,'' said Richard Boucher, a State
Department spokesman.
   Members of Sanchez' organization said he had spoken to American
reporters about human rights on the island a few days before his
arrest.
   Cernuda said Americas Watch, a New York-based human rights
organization, and Amnesty International, were already working for
the release of the workers.
   ``In jailing Sanchez, Cobas and Jerez, the Cuban government has
demonstrated that it deserves its reputation as one of the world's
most rigidly totalitarian states,'' a statement released Monday by
Americas Watch said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
