<DOCNO> AP890808-0030 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-89 0321EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-NewZealand     08-08 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-New Zealand,0524</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Prime Minister-Designate says Anti-Nuclear Policy to Continue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WELLINGTON, New Zealand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man elected today to succeed
outgoing Prime Minister David Lange said he intends to maintain a
tough anti-nuclear decree that bans U.S. warships from New Zealand
ports.
   ``Our nuclear policy won't be changed,'' Deputy Prime Minister
Geoffrey Palmer told a news conference after being named head of
the governing Labor Party today. Lange, 47, resigned Monday amid
party wrangling over economic policy, citing health reasons.
   ``We want to have dialogue with the Americans, we want to have
discussions, but I wouldn't want to suggest that there is going to
be any prospect of immediate change in that respect at all,''
Palmer said.
   The U.S. State Department said Monday that it hoped the next
prime minister would reassess the policy that led to the the
collapse of the ANZUS military alliance with America and Australia.
   Lange arranged to visit Gov.-General Sir Paul Reeves today to
formally submit his resignation. Upon acceptance of the
resignation, Palmer was to formally become prime minister.
   Helen Clark, 40, who was health minister, will become deputy
prime minister.
   Palmer, 47, former attorney-general and justice minister, was
elected leader of the traditionally left-leaning Labor Party at a
meeting of the party's caucus following Lange's sudden announcement
that he was resigning after five years.
   Lange said he wanted to step down while he was still on top. He
suffered a heart attack a year ago.
   He noted recent opinion polls show his personal popularity and
that of his Labor Party government are increasing.
   But observers pointed to party infighting over the economy and
last week's reappointment to the Cabinet of Roger Douglas, a
conservative archrival of Lange who Lange dismissed as finance
minister last year.
   Lange's government denied permission for U.S. warships to enter
New Zealand ports in 1984 because Washington refused to confirm or
deny whether specific ships carried atomic weapons.
   The United States in 1986 retaliated by suspending all military
cooperation with the government in Wellington, making it impossible
to operate the Australian-New Zealand-U.S. (ANZUS) defense alliance.
   State Department spokesman Richard Boucher said Monday: ``We are
hopeful ... that Prime Minister Lange's successor will reassess New
Zealand's anti-nuclear policy.
   ``We hope he will address with us the differences between our
two countries on security-related issues,'' he said.
   There was no immediate reaction to Lange's resignation from
France, which was embroiled in a major diplomatic row with New
Zealand after French agents in 1985 bombed the environmentalist
ship Rainbow Warrior in Wellington harbor, causing the death of a
Dutch photographer.
   Last year Lange allowed Douglas to deregulate industries, remove
subsidies and privatize government departments. But he opposed
Douglas' proposed flat tax among other ideas, saying it would hit
the poor hardest.
   ``There is no place in New Zealand for deregulated labor
markets. There is no place in New Zealand for doing away with a
minimum wage,'' Lange said. ``There is no place in New Zealand for
policies which would reduce women to some convenient chattels of
the marketplace.''
</TEXT>
