<FIRST>r a PM-DayCareDeath     08-08 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Day Care Death,0354</SECOND>
<HEAD>Child Left By Day Care Service In Locked Car Dies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEAN GOLEMBESKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BLOOMFIELD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities shut down a day care
service while they investigate the death of a 3-year-old girl who
was left in a closed car for more than three hours on a sweltering
afternoon.
   Ebony Skinner was left alone in a late-model Cadillac with its
windows rolled up from 12:30 p.m. to 4 p.m. Friday, police Capt.
Richard Mulhall said. The car was parked in the driveway of the day
care operator's home, which is where the business is located.
   The girl was one of seven children between the ages of 3 and 6
who had returned from a brief shopping trip with the day care
operator, Carrie Allison.
   ``It's possible she fell asleep and was quiet in the back,''
Mulhall said. The other children and their parents were being
questioned.
   Temperatures were as high as 94 on Friday, while the humidity
was oppressive. Medical experts said under those conditions a child
can begin dehydrating in 30 minutes.
   The state medical examiner's office said Ebony died of
hyperthermia, a condition in which a person loses the ability to
sweat and thereby control body temperature.
   Mulhall said the car's windows were closed because its air
conditioning had been used during the trip to a nearby shopping
plaza.
   No charges had been filed against Allison, 57, who runs a
state-licensed day care business from her home. Mulhall said he
expected charges to be filed once the police investigation was
completed.
   Mulhall said Allison was ``very emotional and in a state of
shock'' on Monday.
   Allison didn't return a telephone call to her home Monday.
   Donna Jolly, a spokeswoman for the Department of Human
Resources, said the state temporarily suspended the license of the
day care service pending the investigation. No decision had been
made on whether to permanently close the business.
   The girl's mother, Melanise Hughes, and father, David Skinner,
weren't listed in local telephone directories and couldn't be
reached for comment.
</TEXT>
