<FIRST>r a PM-Leland     08-08 0462</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Leland,0481</SECOND>
<HEAD>Family of Texas Congressman Awaits Word on His Fate</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Leland-Search, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL GRACZYK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Family and friends of U.S. Rep. Mickey Leland
awaited word today on the fate of the congressman, who was on a
plane that failed to arrive as expected at a refugee camp near the
Ethiopian-Sudanese border.
   ``I think that he's going to be all right. Really, I do,''
Leland's mother, Alice Rains said Monday night. ``And I know I have
to have courage, because I want to give courage to the children.''
   The plane carried nine Americans and five Ethiopians. The
Americans included members of Leland's staff and U.S. Embassy
personnel.
   Alma Newsom, a spokeswoman in Leland's Washington office, said
Monday it was ``too early to raise alarms'' despite information
from the State Department that the plane was reported overdue on a
flight from the Ethiopian capitol of Addis Ababa to the refugee
camp, Fugnido, about 300 miles to the southwest.
   State Department spokesman Adam Shub said, however, ``We are
concerned about the welfare of Mr. Leland and his group.''
   Ms. Newsom said she is not overly concerned because
communications are poor and the travelers would not be able to
notify anyone of a change in plans.
   ``My guess is once en route, the camp that was the original
destination was too far and they opted to go to a different camp,''
Ms. Newsom said.
   She said the plane was late in departing Monday from Addis Ababa
because of bad weather.
   Ms. Newsom said pilots were strict about adhering to a 5 p.m.
curfew to return to Addis Ababa.
   ``If they feel they can't get back by that time, then you stay
where you are overnight,'' she said.
   The 44-year-old Leland is chairman of the House Select Committee
on Hunger. He has taken a strong interest in Africa's refugees and
visited the same area in March, officials said.
   The six-term congressman is married and has a son.
   Leland, who also serves on the House Committee on Energy and
Commerce and the Committee on Post Office and Civil Service and was
twice chairman of the Congressional Black Caucus, often has served
as a mediator in matters of international or interracial
consequence.
   For 10 years, he has overseen a program in which black youths
from his urban district were sent to Israel for six-week stays.
   He joined two other congressmen last October in a trip to Cuba
in efforts to negotiate the release of five political prisoners and
their families.
   When members of the Veterans' Peace Convoy to Nicaragua were
stopped at their approach to the International Bridge in Laredo in
June 1988, Leland negotiated with U.S. Treasury officials in an
effort to allow the group's passage across the border.
</TEXT>
