<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     08-08 0427</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0441</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tokyo Stocks Up, Dollar Off Slightly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index rebounded
today after four days of decline, while the U.S. dollar edged down
against the Japanese yen after a three-day climb.
   The dollar closed at 139.25 yen, down 0.53 yen from Monday's
139.78-yen finish. It opened at 139.55 yen and moved between 138.95
yen and 139.65 yen.
   The dollar had gained 3.58 yen in three trading days before
today's decline.
   Currency trading today was marked mainly by participants'
position adjustments, said Shinzo Yamamoto, a trader with Daiwa
Bank in Tokyo.
   News last Friday of a lower-than-expected U.S. jobless rate in
July had contributed to the dollar's rise.
   But Yamamoto said most market players were wary about buying too
many dollars because ``the jobless rate, which is only one of many
indicators, is not enough to determine the U.S. economy has started
to grow again.''
   A trader with the Bank of Tokyo said the dollar edged down
against the yen as the U.S. currrency was sold in dealings between
the dollar and the West German mark.
   Most of today's dealings were among banks, with individual
investors remaining on the sidelines, said the trader, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   On the stock exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average
climbed 129.10 points, or 0.37 percent, and closed at 34,759.48.
The index had lost 111.61 points the previous day.
   Genjiro Sasaki, a dealer with New Japan Securities Co., said
that after losing nearly 270 points since last Thursday, the Nikkei
rebounded because of speculative investors' buying spot issues and
selling futures issues to make profits from price gaps between the
two markets.
   ``The new prime minister was finally chosen, and it reassured
the market that there is less political uncertainty,'' he added.
   Today, the governing Liberal Democratic Party chose Toshiki
Kaifu, a former education minister, as the party's new president.
He thus will become prime minister, succeeding Sousuke Uno, who
resigned to take responsibility for the party's losses in the July
23 parliamentary election.
   ``Many participants were still reluctant to buy because they
don't want to lose money in case the index plunges due to a
possible major political change,'' Sasaki said.
   He noted first section volume was still small, estimated at 450
million shares, up from the previous day's 300 million.
   Traders reported many buy orders for Nintendo stock, which
closed at a limit high of 16,400 yen ($118) after the company
announced a gratis share offering today.
   The interest in Nintendo also triggered buying of Fanac and Sony
issues, Sasaki added.
</TEXT>
