<DOCNO> AP890808-0041 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-89 0600EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-FamilyReuinted     08-08 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Family Reuinted,0406</SECOND>
<HEAD>Couple Plans to Renew Wedding Vows After 14 Year Separation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT McKNIGHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who fled Vietnam hours before the fall
of Saigon gave his wife a dozen red roses as he was reunited with
his family after 14 years.
   Anthony Tran was the chief engineer aboard an army tugboat that
pulled out of the Gulf of Tonkin on April 29, 1975, about 12 hours
before South Vietnam's government surrendered.
   His wife, Dao, and five of their seven children rejoined him
Monday night at New Orleans International Airport, where they
arrived from Vietnam via San Francisco.
   ``I'm still very nervous and excited,'' Tran said.
   He translated his wife as saying, ``She can't speak, she is too
nervous.''
   Tran took a two-week vacation from his job as a refrigeration
technician to have time to spend with his family. He said he would
concentrate on teaching them about living in the United States.
   ``I have to teach them about freedom and the difference between
communism and freedom. Right now, I don't understand them and they
don't understand me,'' Tran said.
   Language may be a problem, he said.
   ``The first thing I have to know is how good they speak English.
In this country, they can't work without speaking English,'' Tran
said.
   He said he will not be able to support all his children _ his
oldest son is 32 _ on his salary.
   Tran has held numerous jobs since coming to this country. He
currently is working for a maintenance contractor at New Orleans
International Airport.
   Tran said before he left Vietnam, he had a friend spread the
word that he was dead, fearing the North Vietnamese would harm his
wife and children if they learned he had fled.
   Three years later, he got word to his family that he was alive
and he began sending money to his wife _ between $3,000 and $6,000
each year, he estimated _ so she could buy her family's way out of
the country.
   Two of Tran's daughters weren't part of the reunion plans. Their
oldest daughter drowned in 1980 with 37 other refugees when their
boat sank at sea.
   Their second oldest daughter, he said, is remaining in Vietnam
until the family can get enough money for her husband and their two
children to emigrate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
