<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     08-08 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Eases, Gold Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar eased in calm European trading
this morning and currency dealers said they expected it to settle
into a narrow trading range and wait for clues about the direction
of U.S. interest rates.
   Gold prices rose.
   Traders in Milan, Italy, said the dollar is coming back down
``to reality'' after rising on Friday's better-than-expected U.S.
employment figures.
   They said the dollar's rise had been magnified by the thin
August holiday market.
   ``The dollar wouldn't have reacted as much in a normal market,''
one trader said. ``It's a very sensitive market that tends to
accentuate even the slightest impulses.''
   Added a trader at a commercial bank in Frankfurt: ``What goes up
must come down. Nobody knows what they should think. People are
changing opinions faster than they're changing clothes.''
   Others predicted dollar activity might pick up later this week
with the release of the July U.S. producer price index and retail
sales figures.
   ``By now we've seen this market is almost exclusively interest
rate oriented,'' one trader said. ``It is hungry for news that can
confirm what the employment data suggested.''
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell 0.53 yen to a closing 139.25 yen. Later, in
London, it was also quoted at 139.25 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Monday:
   _1.9035 West German marks, down from 1.9055
   _1.6375 Swiss francs, down from 1.6380
   _6.4403 French francs, down from 6.4470
   _2.1493 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1502
   _1,369.50 Italian lire, down from 1,373.50
   _1.1722 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1745
   In London, the dollar fell 1 cent against the British pound. It
cost $1.6175 to buy one pound, compared with $1.6075 late Monday.
   Gold opened in London at $366.10 a troy ounce, compared with
late Monday's $365.75. At midmorning, the city's five major bullion
dealers fixed a recommended price of $366.20.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $366.10 compared with $365.40 late
Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $1.18 to close at $367.28.
   Silver was quoted in London at $5.16 a troy ounce, down from
Monday's $5.18.
</TEXT>
