<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     08-08 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0508</SECOND>
<HEAD>Canadian Air Brings Chill from Plains to Appalachians</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A Canadian air mass chilled much of the nation's midsection this
morning, pushing temperatures to record lows from the southern
Plains to the Appalachians.
   Elsewhere this morning, showers and thunderstorms continued over
south-central Texas, across the central Gulf Coast and over
portions of Florida. Showers also were over eastern North Carolina
and rain was falling over much of New England.
   Thunderstorms dissipated over the Rockies but continued late
Monday evening across Nevada and portions of the Desert Southwest.
Strong winds caused dust storms in Arizona, reducing visibility to
a quarter of a mile in the Salt River Valley, and heavy rain slowed
traffic near Parker.
   A high pressure area extending from southern Canada to central
Kansas sent early morning temperatures plunging into the 40s in
parts of Michigan and the central Appalachians and into the 50s in
parts of the southern Plains and Southeast states.
   By early morning, at least 15 cities had set new record lows for
the date. They included Columbus, Ohio, where a reading of 51
degrees broke by one degree a mark set in 1886; Grand Rapids,
Mich., where the thermometer hit 46 degrees; Huntsville, Ala., with
58 degrees; and Dallas-Fort Worth, with 66 degrees.
   More than three dozen cities set record lows on Monday.
   Today's forecast called for scattered showers and thunderstorms
from south-central Texas across the Gulf Coast to Florida, and some
scattered thunderstorms over the Desert Southwest, the Rockies, and
the Plateau region west of the Rockies. A few showers also were
predicted for western New York state and northern New England.
   Highs were expected to be in the 60s over Michigan and western
Pennsylvania; the 90s from southern South Carolina into Florida, in
south-central and southwest Texas, and across much of the
intermountain region; between 100 and 108 degrees in the Desert
Southwest; and in the 70s and 80s elsewhere.
   Temperatures at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 44 degrees at Lansing,
Mich., to 92 degrees at Blythe and Thermal, Calif.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 65 partly cloudy; Boston 64 showery; Buffalo 50
fair; Charleston, S.C. 76 fair; Cincinnati 54 partly cloudy;
Cleveland 58 partly cloudy; Detroit 50 fair; Miami 80 partly
cloudy; New York 62 fair; Philadelphia 58 fair; Pittsburgh 50 fair;
Portland, Maine 64 showery; Washington, D.C. 60 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 51 fair; Denver 58 fair; Des Moines 55 fair;
Fort Worth 65 fair; Indianapolis 50 fair; Kansas City 56 fair;
Nashville 55 fair; New Orleans 78 cloudy; Oklahoma City 58 fair;
St. Louis 61 fair; Minneapolis@St. Paul 58 cloudy; San Antonio 76
cloudy.
   _West: Albuquerque 66 windy; Anchorage 60 partly cloudy; Boise
80 partly cloudy; Honolulu 79 fair; Las Vegas 92 partly cloudy; Los
Angeles 65 partly cloudy; Phoenix 87 cloudy; Salt Lake City 69
fair; San Diego 68 partly cloudy; San Francisco 57 partly cloudy;
Seattle 65 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 52 fair; Toronto 46 partly cloudy.
</TEXT>
