<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-89 0703EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Christina     08-08 0618</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Christina,0641</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oregon Mental Patient Has Run Away Before, Posing as Other People</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. JOHN'S, Newfoundland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Oregon mental patient found
outside a church in this eastern Canadian city has wandered off
before, acting as another person, and her father says it is her way
of dealing with mental anguish.
   The woman, who called herself Christina, has been identified as
Rochelle Scholl of Portland, Ore., Ed Hallett, a spokesman for
Newfoundland Premier Clyde Wells, said Monday.
   Hallet said the brown-haired woman, about 19, was identified by
Portland psychologist Susan Beattie, who arrived Monday in St.
John's, where Ms. Scholl has been hospitalized for treatment.
   Officials said Ms. Scholl on Monday night insisted she was
Christina.
   Her positive identification came one month after she was found
wrapped in a blanket at a church, clinging to a doll. Doctors in
the Newfoundland capital said the woman indicated she was a
severely handicapped 14-year-old with a life-threatening muscle
disease that left her unable to walk or talk, though she could
communicate through sign language.
   Rochelle has misled authorities on at least two other occasions,
officials said. Although seemingly mute and handicapped, Scholl was
later found to be able-bodied and able to speak.
   Her father, Rodney Scholl, said Monday in a telephone interview
from his home in Selma, Ore., that he is sure his daughter left
Oregon as Rochelle Scholl but in her own mind she isn't Rochelle
now.
   ``She has a mental diagnosis of a hysterical disassociation with
regression and amnesia,'' he said. ``My intentions are to bring her
home.''
   Scholl said he believes his daughter's adopting the persona of
Christina was her way of dealing with mental anguish. He said the
episodes are brought on by stress, but he could not think of any
specific incidents other than the stress of adolescence.
   ``She disassociates from it. She thinks she is who she is,'' he
said.
   Rochelle was living on her own in a low-income housing project
after being discharged from a mental hospital last spring, he said.
   ``She was being seen on an outpatient basis and did a lot of
volunteer work with nursing homes and with handicapped people,'' he
said.
   The father said Ms. Scholl left July 2, telling a neighbor she
was heading for California or Arizona with $1,000 in her pocket.
   Ms. Scholl had been living in Mesa, Ariz., with her mother and
stepfather from the age of five, Scholl said. At 18, she moved to
Oregon to be with her father.
   The discovery of Ms. Scholl on July 7 triggered an intense
investigation that involved Canadian police, social and medical
workers, customs officials, Scotland Yard and Interpol.
   She used sign language to tell doctors she came to Canada on a
yacht with her mother, three men and a nanny. She was thought to
understand English, German and a Yugoslavian dialect.
   News reports from January 1988 said she turned up at an airport
in Des Moines, Iowa, clutching a baby bottle and a handwritten
letter authorities originally believed was written by her mother,
said Len Power of the Royal Newfoundland Constabulary.
   Three months earlier she was found in an airport bathroom in
Springfield, Mo., with a baby bottle and a similar letter that
quoted from the Bible and blamed her apparent disabilities on
falling short of the ``Lord's blessing.''
   Lt. Freeman Twine of the Royal Newfoundland Constabulary said
police are satisfied Christina is Rochelle Scholl but she had not
admitted her identity Monday night. Nor had she started to walk or
talk.
   ``She just doesn't indicate anything,'' Twine said.
   Scholl has been committed to the Waterford mental hospital in
St. John's. A lawyer has been appointed by the provincial Justice
Department to represent her.
</TEXT>
