<FIRST>r i PM-China-Jiang     08-08 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Jiang,0596</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Party Chief Portrayed as Man of the People</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The official media is portraying China's new
Communist Party chief, Jiang Zemin, as a man of the people who does
not fear getting his hands dirty and is comfortable preaching
homely socialist virtues.
   ``Let's sing a song together,'' he reportedly told workers at a
Shanghai steelworks. ``We'll sing: `We Workers Have Strength,' OK?``
   ``Under Comrade Jiang Zemin's direction, the song rose loud and
clear,'' the party newspaper, the People's Daily, reported today in
a front-page article titled ``General Secretary Among the People of
Shanghai.''
   Jiang returned Sunday from a five-day visit to the city where he
was local party secretary until his June 24 appointment to the
national post. He succeeded Zhao Ziyang.
   Early in his two-year tenure, Zhao also was portrayed as a warm
and personable man who enjoyed visits outside the capital to mingle
with ordinary people. But since his ouster for allegedly supporting
student pro-democracy protesters, the media has printed only harsh
criticism of him and blamed him for virtually every problem China
faces, from an unbalanced budget to corruption to poor worker
morale.
   Jiang, on the other hand, ``repeatedly stressed that we must
rely entirely on the working class,'' Shanghai's Xinmen Evening
News said in a report on the party leader's visit.
   It said that while touring the No. 2 Textile Equipment Factory,
Jiang stopped to ask a young worker his age and what school he had
attended. He then stuck out his hand, causing the youth to blush
and try to wipe off his oil-covered hand.
   ``Never mind,'' Jiang said, grabbing the hand and pumping it.
``From now on we must rely on you'' workers.
   ``These words sank into people's ears,'' the report said. ``For
a while people had become hazy about the leading role of the
workers and the idea of the worker-peasant alliance as an
ideological foundation.''
   At the steelworks, the People's Daily said Jiang noticed that
some workers did not know all the words to the song that begins:
``We workers have strength, we workers have strength. Every day we
are busy at work.''
   ``We should sing this kind of song often,'' he admonished them.
The paper added: ``Watching the scene, some comrades said, `We
haven't seen a scene like this for many years.' ``
   Jiang also called for large and medium-sized businesses to take
the lead in economic development, giving implicit support to the
new post-Zhao emphasis on state ownership rather than
privatization. Those sized companies tend to be state-owned, and
most have large work forces with low productivity but guaranteed
lifetime employment.
   China's most efficient and fast-growing sector is its tiny
private sector, but most of these companies are small.
   The reports said Jiang rode about in a van on his tour, drank
only tea and insisted on eating at home _ all in keeping with the
government's current campaign to save money and encourage simple
living.
   They also said he listened closely to the problems of local
officials and often took notes. His only advice, however, appears
to have been ideological. After listening to reports by officials
in villages around Shanghai regarding export production, collective
enterprises and population control, the People's Daily said Jiang
``jotted down a plan for Shanghai and its suburbs.''
   His plan: ``Grasp well the building of party spirit, develop
education in socialism, patriotism and hard work, and strengthen
education in the national planning mentality.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
