<FIRST>r i PM-SriLanka     08-08 0467</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sri Lanka,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Demands India Finish Pullout Next Month</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said today it wants
India to withdraw all its troops by next month but that the New
Delhi government is offering a phased pullout that would finish in
February.
   Foreign Minister Ranjan Wijeratne, briefing Parliament today on
talks he had last week with Indian leaders in New Delhi, said an
end to Indian military operations should be ``immediate and
unqualified.''
   Indian troops began arriving two years ago to enforce a New
Delhi-brokered peace plan aimed at ending an insurgency by minority
Tamils fighting for autonomy in the north and east. About 43,000
are now stationed on the Indian Ocean island.
   ``The Indian position on withdrawal, on the basis of three
shiploads per week of 1,500 to 1,600 personnel, including a three
week preparatory period, will take 28 to 30 weeks and will end in
February 1990,'' Wijeratne, who is also the deputy defense
minister, told Parliament.
   Wijeratne led a six-member delegation to New Delhi on July 29 to
discuss a time frame for the pullout. India has already withdrawn
2,220 troops in phases since July 29, the date initially set by
President Ranasinghe Premadasa for completion of the pullout.
   Sinhalese radicals have stirred up an anti-Indian campaign to
protest the presence of Indian soldiers deployed in the
Tamil-dominated north and east.
   The July 29, 1987, peace accord, which granted limited autonomy
to those areas failed when the dominant Tamil group, the Liberation
Tigers of Tamil Eelam, rejected it, saying it did not meet their
aspirations for a homeland.
   On Indian troops halting military operations in the north and
east, Wijeratne said the Indians wanted the Tamil Tigers to first
unilaterally suspend military offensives for a 15-day period.
   India has linked the troop withdrawal with the devolution of
powers to the Northeastern Council, formed under the peace accord,
which gave Tamils limited autonomy in exchange for an arms
surrender.
   ``Our position is the implementation of the agreement was not
connected with the Indian troop withdrawal,'' Wijeratne said.
   Wijeratne's statement will be debated in Parliament and
Premadasa is expected to chair a meeting of his Cabinet Friday to
announce Sri Lankan position on the issues. There will be no voting.
   Sinhalese extremists claiming the presence of Indian troops
compromised the country's independence, have launched a vicious
campaign against the government. At least 4,000 people, mainly
government officials and supporters, have been killed in the
two-year Sinhalese uprising. The Tamil insurgency has claimed
11,000 lives.
   Tamils form 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people, and
Sinhalese make up 75 percent. Tamils accuse the Sinhalese of
discriminating against them in jobs, education and use of the
Sinhalese language.
   About 60 million Tamils live in southern India.
</TEXT>
