<FIRST>r a PM-VideoConvention     08-08 0512</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Video Convention,0527</SECOND>
<HEAD>Video Retailers Brace for Censorship Battle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Video store owners say they are being unfairly
singled out by legislators who want to curb the rental of violent
films such as ``Ninja Brothers of Blood'' and ``Night of the
Demons.''
   Video retailers attending the eighth annual Video Software
Dealers Association convention, which entered its third day today,
expressed concern that they soon might be prosecuted if they rent
violence-filled features, even those rated PG-13, to children.
   The booming home video market is dominated by mass-appeal
blockbusters like ``E.T. The Extra-Terrestial'' and how-to tapes.
   But the strong presence of low-budget, violence-filled features
in thousands of rental stores has led to a number of bills aimed at
limiting the availability of such cassettes to minors.
   A Missouri bill that becomes law on Aug. 28, in fact, prohibits
the rental to minors of tapes that have either a tendency to appeal
to morbid interests or depict violence in a patently offensive way
as judged by local community standards.
   ``We think it has a lot to do with the Meese Commission,'' said
Pam Horovitz, executive vice president of the video association,
referring to the President Reagan-appointed commission on
pornography and violence.
   ``We really believe that it is the fundamental responsibility of
the parent to decide what their children can and cannot watch.
That's the only place where the decision can be made in the best
interests of the child,'' she said.
   Horovitz said some of the films that could be covered by the
Missouri bill are available to children on television or in
theaters.
   A Paramount Home Video spokesman said the marketplace _ not the
government _should decide what's acceptable.
   ``We are committed to making the highest quality motion pictures
and television shows that audiences want,'' said Deborah Rosen.
``The audience should decide what they want and what they don't
want.''
   ``We believe self-regulation is the best idea,'' said Ron
Castell, senior vice president of Blockbuster Video, the nation's
largest chain with more than 820 stores. ``We are concerned,
however, about box art. As an industry, we have to police ourselves
on that.''
   Program suppliers frequently redesign movie package art to boost
sales. A number of the so-called B titles are driven by lurid
packaging _ the more graphic the cassette cover design, the better
the cassette is expected to sell.
   But video retailers now find themselves under increased pressure
to submit new art to the Motion Picture Association of America. The
MPAA, which hands out movie ratings, demands that illustrations for
MPAA-rated films be approved separately.
   Home video sales are expected to hit $10 billion this year.
   ``This is not a hard business. All you do is rent movies.
Americans love movies,'' Kastell said. ``And they have an
insatiable demand.''
   A record 14,000 video retailers, distributors, producers and
tape manufacturers have come to the convention to check out videos
ranging from ``Who Framed Roger Rabbit'' to ``Balloonacy,'' a
how-to video complete with 50 balloons and tips to create more than
30 inflated animals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
