<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-89 0935EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Iran-Iraq 1stLd-Writethru a0477 08-08 0608</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran-Iraq, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0477,0624</SECOND>
<HEAD>Year After Cease-fire, Iraq Calls for Peace Treaty with Iran</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 3rd pvs, ```The cease-fire...' to ADD
that today official holiday, color. Pickup 4th pvs, `On Aug....' Edits
thereafter to TRIM.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALAH NASRAWI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraqi President Saddam Hussein called on
Iranian leaders today to sign a peace treaty to end the eght-year
Persian Gulf war, halted nearly a year ago by a U.N.-brokered
cease-fire.
   In a television message marking the anniversary of the day Iraq
accepted the U.N. cease-fire resolution, Saddam said a treaty would
guarantee ``both countries' legitimate rights.''
   ``The cease-fire agreement should not be taken as a talisman for
peace ... we are after a comprehensive, total and lasting peace
treaty,'' he said.
   Today was an official Iraqi holiday to mark the anniversary. On
Monday night, thousands of people poured into a central Baghdad
park for a fireworks display and traditional singing and dancing in
a government-organized celebration.
   Crowds of teen-agers, some wearing traditional Arab robes, waved
flags and portraits of Saddam labeled ``the maker of peace and
victory.''
   On Aug. 8, 1988, U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
announced the cease-fire would take effect Aug. 20, following
Iraq's decision to drop a demand for direct talks before
hostilities were suspended.
   Both sides accepted U.N. Security Council Resolution 598,
calling for immediate withdrawals to pre-war borders, exchange of
prisoners, formal peace talks and a panel to determine
responsibility for the conflict that killed an estimated 1 million
people.
   U.N.-sponsored talks on a peace treaty started Aug. 25 in Geneva
but deadlocked immediately. Three further rounds of discussions
failed to make any progress.
   Saddam noted in his speech that Iran has made no public
declaration of its desire for peace, saying, ``The Iranian leaders
have been far away from peace in their deeds and maybe in their
intentions as well.''
   He said the ``no peace-no war'' situation with Iran created
instability and ``countries in the region, fearing the worst, will
remain on guard against Iran.''
   The talks stalled over Iranian insistence that the next step in
the peace process should be Iraq's withdrawal from about 380 square
miles of Iranian territory it occupies.
   The Iraqis, however, say they do not recognize a 1975 treaty
drawing part of the Iran-Iraq border down the middle of the
Shatt-Al-Arab waterway, their only outlet to the sea.
   Baghdad maintains the border should be redrawn to include all
the waterway as Iraqi, and that Iraq should have the sole right to
dredge it of mines and other war debris.
   He called for an immediate start to a full exchange of nearly
100,000 prisoners of war, saying ``it's a patriotic and
humanitarian responsibility that these prisoners should be
repatriated without delay.''
   Saddam added that Iran should avoid ``cheap bargaining'' on the
POW issue in order to gain leverage at the peace talks.
   Iraq has proposed that the POWs be swapped under an agreement
separate from the U.N. resolution, but Iran says they can only be
freed as part of an overall settlement of the conflict.
   So far, only 2,360 ailing and disabled prisoners have been
repatriated under exchanges arranged by the International Committee
for the Red Cross.
   Saddam said Iraq has demonstrated its wish for peace by
demobilizing about 200,000 soldiers, almost one-quarter of its
army, and freezing its paramilitary forces.
   The Iraqi leader said that government projects for swift
reconstruction of the war-damaged southern city of Basra and the
port of Faw is a further sign that Iraq is seeking lasting peace.
   The war began in September 1980 when Iraq invaded Iran after
border skirmishes.
</TEXT>
