<FIRST>u w PM-UrbanLeagueReport 1stLd-Writethru a0434 08-08 0868</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Urban League Report, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0434,850</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kemp Pledges to Rid HUD of GOP Influence Peddlers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 10 grafs with speech, picks up pvs 4th graf, Blacks are</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Housing and Urban Development Secretary Jack
Kemp pledged today to get ``the Republican influence peddlers'' out
of his troubled department and work for imrpoved opportunities for
poor people to own their own homes.
   Kemp addressed the annual conference of the National Urban
League a day after the civil rights organization issued a report
saying that at the present rate of progress it would take black
Americans 1,163 years to catch up with whites in home ownership.
   Before Kemp spoke, delegates observed a moment of silence to
express concern for Rep. Mickey Leland, D-Texas, a member of the
Congressional Black Caucus missing on an airplane flight in Africa.
   ``It is typical of Mickey that if a plane were missing and
Mickey was on it, it would be on its way to northern Africa to help
the poor and those who have been left out,'' Kemp said.
   Turning to the investigations of questionable practices and
insider profiteering during the Reagan administration in the
department he now heads, Kemp said: ``We're going to take the
greedy and the consultants and the Republican influence peddlers
out of HUD.''
   ``I don't want it to work for the Democratic National Committee;
it shouldn't work for the Republican National Committee; it's got
to work for the people,'' he said.
   ``We want to take publicly assisted housing and publicly owned
housing and, if it's possible and if there's some sweat equity
involved and if people can homestead in this century as we should
have done more of in the last century, we should give people a
chance to own a home,'' Kemp said.
   ``We are going to do our very best to end the disgrace of
redlining (refusal of lenders to provide mortgages in certain
areas) in America, to make sure that seed capital is flowing into
low-income housing and low-income commmunities,'' he said.
   In its report Monday on the economic status of blacks, the Urban
League called for new efforts to ``overhaul the stalled engine of
racial progress.''
   ``The impressive long-term progress of African-Americans has in
more recent years stalled and, in some cases, even reversed,'' it
said.
   Blacks are gaining on whites so slowly in employment and
economic development that there appears little chance they will
catch up before the middle of the next century, said the report by
the league's research department.
   ``There is a commanding need to overhaul the stalled engine of
racial progress,'' it said.
   One of the bleakest parts of the report was on housing, where
the researchers reported that the black home ownership rate
increased only from 64.6 percent of the 1970 rate for whites to
65.1 percent in 1985 _ a gain of half a percentage point in 15
years.
   As a result, the report said, it would take until the year 3152
for blacks to catch up with whites.
   ``The impact of legal discrimination was perhaps most
dramatically manifest in the residential separation of the races,''
the report said. ``Institutional racism, as revealed in the racist
policies and practices of mortgage lenders, housing developers, and
real estate agents, has been equally consequential.
   ``Combined with the aversion whites have exhibited toward living
in areas in which African-Americans exceed or might exceed a
certain number, these factors have generated and sustained telling
levels of residential segregation,'' it said.
   In education and health the prospects are a little better, said
the report.
   But in some economic and health areas, including infant
mortality, the researchers said gains are being made so slowly that
they are unable to estimate when parity might be reached.
   By contrast, the number of blacks completing high school
compared with whites increased so dramatically, from 55 percent in
1967 to 79 percent in 1985, that the league estimated parity should
be reached in 16 years.
   The report said 43.7 percent as many whites as blacks were
unemployed in 1985, compared with 45.9 percent in 1967.
   ``Major initiatives are necessary if this trend is to be
checked,'' the league said.
   The report estimated it would take 54 years for blacks to reach
parity with whites in managerial and professional occupations, 73
years in median earnings for full-time workers and an undetermined
amount of time in family income.
   It estimated it will be 159 years, if present trends continue,
before black poverty rates shrink to equal those of whites.
   One area where blacks lost ground was in earnings of their
businesses, as a share of the earnings of all American companies.
In 1972, this figure was nearly 20 percent. In 1982, it had shrunk
to less than 7 percent.
   The report estimated it will take 55 years for black college
enrollment to reach parity with white enrollment, 40 years for life
expectancy, three years for voter registration and nine years for
voting rates in congressional elections.
   In its bleak report on infant mortality, it said the white rate,
as a percentage of the black rate, has declined from 54.6 percent
in 1970 to just over 51 percent in 1985.
</TEXT>
