<SECOND>PM-Lynn Fire, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0531,0465</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire Sweeps Massachusetts Tenement; 3 Dead</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 13 grafs to UPDATE with tenant saying some rooms
had ropes in place of fire escape, landlord charged with failing to install
sprinklers, owner refusing to comment; PICKS UP penultimate graf, `Police
Capt. ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN GALVIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LYNN, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire early today destroyed a rooming house
whose landlord had been cited for failing to install sprinklers,
killing at least three people, injuring 11 and leaving 13
unaccounted for, authorities said.
   Several people escaped the 12:30 a.m. blaze in the four-story
brick tenement by jumping onto lower roofs. Others lowered
themselves on ropes that tenants said had been supplied in rooms in
place of a fire escape.
   It was not immediately clear whether local ordinances required
fire escapes.
   One victim was believed to have been shinnying down a rope when
he fell to the street, authorities said. Police said two more
bodies were spotted in the ruins. Firefighters awaited the arrival
of a crane to clear the debris.
   Early today 22 of the 35 residents believed to live in the house
were accounted for, authorities said.
   ``We've got a grisly task ahead of us,'' said Fire Chief Kurt
Numberg.
   The house had no sprinkler system, authorities said. Mike Barry,
an attorney for the city, said the owner, Leo Allard, was charged
in January with failing to install sprinklers as required under a
1987 city ordinance.
   Last month, Allard was charged with operating a woodworking shop
in the basement, a zoning violation, Barry said.
   Allard was at the scene this morning and refused to answer
reporters' questions.
   The cause of the fire was under investigation.
   ``People were jumping out of windows, hanging on mattresses and
climbing on ropes that knotted up and never reached bottom,''
Numberg said.
   One tenant who escaped said he had to drop about a story to the
street when the rope in his room proved too short to reach from the
window to the ground. Louis Clough, 43, another tenant, said ropes
were a fixture in some rooms.
   Michael Whalen, 40, said he woke up when he smelled smoke, then
broke a window and lowered himself to safety with a rope. He said
there were smoke detectors in the building, but he didn't hear any
go off.
   Lynn, a depressed working-class coastal town of about 79,000, is
15 miles north of Boston.
   Police Capt. Fred McGovern identified one of the dead as
Benjamin Amiro, 50. He was believed to have fallen while shinnying
down a rope.
   McGovern said seven other tenants were injured, along with two
police officers and two firefighters. The police and fire injuries
were not considered serious.
</TEXT>
