<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-89 1222EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Crystal     08-08 0565</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Crystal,0581</SECOND>
<HEAD>Billy Crystal Looking `Mahvelous' in Moscow</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviets don't have much to laugh about these days,
but American comedian Billy Crystal had them in stitches with
slapstick and stand-up routines poking fun at long lines and
superpower politics.
   ``I was raised thinking you were the enemy. You were raised
thinking I was the enemy,'' Crystal told an invitation-only
audience of 600 people, about half foreigners and half Soviets.
``We were both wrong: It's the French.''
   The 41-year-old native New Yorker, whose grandmother emigrated
from Russia, brought his irreverent humor to the communist
heartland to tape ``On Location: Midnight Train to Moscow'' for
broadcast in October on Home Box Office.
   He spent a few days taping skits for the special around town,
then put on a 50-minute show Monday night at Moscow's Pushkin
Theater.
   With staples such as meat, sugar and toothpaste in short supply,
and ethnic violence, strikes and crime on the rise, Soviets need
some comic relief. A few, at least, got it from Crystal.
   A Soviet woman who spoke English said she had never heard of him
but decided to attend the show ``because we need positive
emotions.'' She roared throughout but admitted afterward the
``dialogue was hard to understand.''
   In an interview on Red Square, Crystal agreed comedy was sorely
needed in the Soviet Union.
   ``Here, there is a desperate need to be more open and have more
fun,'' he said.
   The comedian, known for his imitations of Sammy Davis Jr. and
other celebrities, studied with a language coach and opened his
show with a few minutes in Russian.
   ``I wanted to perform in the U.S. Embassy because it has the
best microphones,'' he said, referring to the new office building
the Americans say they can't occupy because of KGB bugs.
   During the rest of the show, Crystal did his best to help the
Soviets bridge the language gap and was most successful with
slapstick and mime. His impersonation of Jack Nicholson reciting a
Russian tongue-twister was a big hit with Soviets, who are familiar
with Nicholson's soft-spoken manner from movies available on
bootleg videotapes.
   Crystal, wearing a gray shirt and white pants that stood out
against a huge red backdrop of a man and woman holding a hammer and
sickle, also portrayed Charlie Chaplin scrounging for food in
Moscow. When he got some, it tasted terrible.
   About a dozen of his relatives in the Soviet Union attended
Monday's show. One called Crystal's comedy ``a new genre for us,
but very interesting.''
   In an interview, Crystal said he had a tough time preparing for
the special because ``there's no place to break the show in like
Impravda or Catch a Rising Tsar.'' The Improv and Catch a Rising
Star are comedy clubs in the United States.
   Standing outside Lenin's Mausoleum on Red Square, Crystal
compared the resting place of the founder of the Soviet state to
Graceland, the home of the late Elvis Presley that has become a
shrine for fans.
   Crystal, who first visited the Soviet Union in April, was asked
if he had any advice for tourists. ``If you bring laxatives, it's a
great place to be,'' he quipped.
   The funniest thing he saw during his visit, he said, was the
shower curtain in his hotel room. ``It's this big,'' he said,
making a tiny square with his hands.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890808-0064 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-89 1225EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SAfrica-Strikes     08-08 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SAfrica-Strikes,0282</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lockouts, Strikes Disrupt South Africa's Auto Industry</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Goodyear tire company
Tuesday threatened to fire 1,200 striking black workers as strikes
and lockouts crippled South Africa's motor vehicle industry.
   In all, 13,000 members of the National Union of Metalworkers of
South Africa at four automobile plants and two vehicle component
factories are not working due to strikes or lockouts. Industry
officials say the closed plants produce about two-thirds of South
Africa's motor vehicles.
   About 5,000 workers are on strike at Volkswagen's plant in
Uitenhage, about 3,600 workers from the Toyota plant near Durban
have been locked out and fired, and about 3,000 workers are on
strike at two plants of the South African Motor Corp., which
produces Fords and Mazdas.
   On Monday, British-owned Eveready locked out 800 workers at its
Uitenhage plant because of a wage dispute. Goodyear followed suit
on Tuesday, saying the 1,200 workers who have been on strike for
five weeks at its factory in Port Elizabeth would be fired unless
they signed an undertaking by Friday that they would accept
employment conditions proposed by the South African management in
the wake of disinvestment by the U.S. parent company.
   The strikes against the three auto manufacturers, which began
last week, are linked to the union's ongoing efforts to negotiate a
wage agreement on a nationwide basis with all major auto companies.
Toyota has been the most adamant in resisting such negotiations,
and says its dismissed workers will lose all chance to reclaim
their jobs unless they reapply by Monday.
   Auto manufacturers not yet affected by the current wave of labor
disputes include Nissan, BMW and Mercedes-Benz.
</TEXT>
