<FIRST>u a PM-FiresRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0491 08-08 0581</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fires Rdp, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0491,0596</SECOND>
<HEAD>Residents Return in Idaho; California Firefighters Make Progress</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with evacuated residents returning home in
Idaho, Utah and California fires contained, increase acreage of Idaho to
43,000, new warning on lightning danger. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Firefighters in California contained two large blazes and dozens
of Idaho residents returned home today a week after fires forced
them out. But a ``red flag'' went up for the third straight day,
warning of lightning strikes.
   Spotter planes cruised over Western forests in a search for
lightning-sparked fires after thousands of storm bolts struck the
region. Fire bosses said they saw no immediate evidence of a new
round of major blazes.
   ``The next two days should tell,'' said Ron Smith, spokesman for
the Boise Interagency Fire Center, the federal fire command post.
``There have been some strikes, but it takes time until we'll spot
whether they've touched off new fires.''
   Fire center officials today posted a ``red-flag'' warning of dry
thunderstorms and gusting wind.
   About 23,000 firefighters on Monday fought the worst of blazes
on 182,000 acres, primarily in Idaho, Oregon and California,
according to the fire center.
   The fire battles have cost more than $27 million, with the bill
rising sharply each day, the center said. More than 220,000 acres
have been charred in a bout of mostly lightning-caused fires that
began July 26.
   In Idaho, the most heavily burned state, more than 9,000 people
were committed to extinguishing to the blazes, including a
43,000-acre series of fires that destroyed a small resort town 70
miles northeast of Boise.
   Early today, dozens of residents who fled their homes more than
a week ago because of those fires were allowed back ``on the
condition they be prepared to leave immediately again,'' Boise
National Forest spokesman Rick Perkins said.
   ``A big wind could change the picture real fast,'' he said.
   About 25 people in the Long Creek summer home area remained
evacuated because of the fire danger.
   Nearly 5,000 firefighters in southern and central California
contained two blazes that blackened thousands of acres of forest
and wilderness for more than a week.
   Firefighters were mopping up a 7,550-acre fire in the Sierra
foothills east of Fresno and a 15,300-acre blaze in the Cleveland
National Forest east of San Diego, which was ignited by a target
shooter's bullet nine days ago. It torched a house and trailer and
neared the historic Mount Palomar Observatory earlier in the week.
   Lightning struck about 700 times Monday in six Western states.
   Most of the new fires were small. The largest had burned five to
seven acres in the Ochoco National Forest in central Oregon.
   Hundreds of federal troops moved through the Boise fire center
for training and eventual deployment. But land managers continued
pressing for more manpower.
   Before the lightning, firefighters in Oregon and Idaho had
consolidated gains made during cool weather last week and predicted
that many of the 100 fires that had burned nearly 89,000 acres
would be contained by midweek.
   Airplanes sent over national forests Monday in Washington to
look for smoke found dozens of lightning-caused fires, most of
which were quickly contained.
   Near Coalville, Utah, about 45 miles east of Salt Lake City,
firefighters finished digging a circle around a 1,700-acre blaze,
and authorities hoped to bring it under control tonight.
   In northwestern Nebraska, a fir that blackened 3,000 acres of
brush and timber in canyon country near Belmont was largely
contained.
</TEXT>
