<FIRST>u a PM-Prayer-Hail 1stLd-Writethru a0538 08-08 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Prayer-Hail, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0538,0422</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rain, Hail Rout Thousands From Ampitheater; 130 Treated</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with conditions of two admitted to hospital,
ADD details on 20-degree temperature drop, number of teen-agers, how they
were dressed, the altitude. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MORRISON, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A storm during a packed prayer service at
a 10,000-seat amphitheater pelted participants with hail and cold
rain and sent people scrambling for cover. At least 130 people were
taken to hospitals.
   Two of the injured were taken to a coronary intensive care unit,
while the rest were treated and released Monday night, said Pat
Conroy, medical coordinator for the five-day Lutheran national
youth conference.
   Most were treated for dizziness and hypothermia, or low body
temperature, from getting soaked by the rain, which dropped the
temperature 20 degrees to about 45.
   About 9,000 teen-agers from across the United States were
participating in the service, dubbed Fire Power, when the storm
broke, said Gary Lane, Denver director of parks and arenas. The
arena is in a park belonging to the city of Denver but is outside
the city limits.
   ``When you have youths dressed in T-shirts and shorts and a
storm can kick up and drop temperatures 20 degrees, you get some
borderline hypothermia cases,'' Lane said.
   Four helicopters and 35 ambulances were brought in to treat the
crowd.
   ``The crowd had to leave the amphitheater, and there was some
panic as people were leaving. Some suffered hyperventilation and
some had hypothermia as they were getting wet,'' said Carolyn
Etter, a parks department director.
   Etter said Lee Gilling, superintendent of Denver's mountain
parks system, went to investigate. ``As far as Lee can tell, there
was no functional problem (with the amphitheater) but a storm and
crowd problem,'' she said.
   Mark Wagner, who led a group of 26 students from Houston,
attributed much of the panic to altitude sickness. Red Rocks, the
Denver park where the amphitheater is situated, is at 6,400 feet,
Lane said.
   ``As it started to rain, there was no covering, so people went
to the wall for cover,'' Wagner said. ``The people never had time
to get rested from the long walk up to Red Rocks.''
   Phyllis Westerman, 32, and David Jones, 40, remained today at
St. Anthony's Central for treatment of chest pains, said hospital
spokeswoman Bev Lilly. They were listed in good and stable
condition respectively. Their hometowns were not immediately known.
   The event was part of the five-day national youth conference
that began Saturday.
</TEXT>
