<FIRST>r i AM-Korea     08-08 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0495</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Korea Urges United Nations to Open Border for Radical Student</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY TUNNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANMUNJOM, Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   North Korea stepped up demands Tuesday
for the United Nations to let a South Korean student who visited
the communist nation return home via the border at Panmunjom.
   The United States accused North Korea of increasing tensions by
turning the truce village of Panmunjom into a ``political carnval''
with groups from North Korea shouting ``Yankee go home!'' and
making obscene gestures at U.S. guards.
   Officials in Seoul said the communist government in Pyongyang
sent two telephone messages to the South Korean government Tuesday
asking for meetings at Panmunjom to discuss the return of
20-year-old radical student Im Su-kyong.
   South Korea, which has said it will arrest Ms. Im when she
returns, did not reply immediately.
   At the 450th meeting of the Military Armistice Commission held
Tuesday in Panmunjom, North Korea demanded the U.S.-led United
Nations Command reconsider its refusal to allow Ms. Im to cross the
border.
   Maj. Gen. Choe Ui Ung, the chief North Korean delegate, said it
was ``quite natural and proper'' for Ms. Im to return home through
the border and ``there is no need for her to make the long way
around'' and travel through third countries.
   U.S. Rear Adm. Larry G. Vogt, leader of the U.N. delegation,
responded that Ms. Im's crossing concerns the two Koreas and ``is
not armistice business.''
   Vogt said North Korea has used Ms. Im and her supporters to
create a ``political carnival'' at the border with demonstrations,
banners, and protesters shouting ``Yankee go home.''
   He said groups visiting the North Korean side of the
Demilitarized Zone around Panmunjom in July shouted slogans, and
swore at and made obscene gestures toward those on the other side
of the border.
   Choe said, ``Even the U.S. youths and other Americans who
visited Panmunjom shouted with indignation towards your GIs, `Why
have the Americans came to another's country to serve as watchmen
of division?'''
   Observers said the demonstrations often included Ms. Im and
foreigners attending the 13th World Festival of Youth and Students
July 1-8 in Pyongyang.
   The student has said she will cross the border on Aug. 15, the
anniversary of Korea's liberation from Japanese colonial rule in
1945, in a demonstration for unification of the countries divided
after World War II. Seoul says her illegal visit is a breach of
national security.
   Ms. Im has become a celebrity in Pyongyang, according to North
Korean military observer Lt. Col. Yun Ki Oon. He told the meeting
she is called the ``flower of unification'' and is mobbed wherever
she goes.
   North Korea's Central News Agency, monitored in Tokyo, said Ms.
Im has received many visitors and gifts at the hospital where she
is recovering from a six-day hunger strike, started after she was
refused permission to cross the border July 27.
</TEXT>
