<FIRST>r i PM-Afghanistan     08-08 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghanistan,0287</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rocket Hits Kabul Ammunition Depot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rocket slammed into a large military
depot for ammunition today, setting off a chain reaction of
explosions that rocked the capital.
   There were no immediate reports of casualties from the attack at
dusk. Ambulances rushed to the scene.
   As the blasts echoed across the city, an electrical outage
plunged Kabul into darkess for about 20 minutes. Black smoke,
meanwhile, billowed over northwest Kabul where the depot was on
fire.
   The depot is about a half mile from a large residential
neighborhood.
   The almost nonstop wave of explosions was continuing two hours
after rocket hit. It was one of about six rockets fired late today.
   They followed a lull in such attacks earlier in the day.
However, more than 115 rockets have crashed into the city during
the past four days.
   No group claimed responsibility for today's attack, but
U.S.-backed guerrillas fighting to oust the Soviet-allied
government have tried repeatedly to hit military targets in Kabul,
with little success.
   Since late June, Kabul has been hit by almost daily rocket
attacks, but most have struck civilian areas. At least 281 people
have been killed and 745 injured in the rocket attacks and a car
bombing, according to U.N. sources.
   More than 40 rockets hit the capital Monday, the worst day of
the recent blitz. Eight people were reported killed.
   There were initially reports today that the depot was set on
fire by sabotage. However, U.N. sources confirmed it was hit by a
rocket.
   A well-informed military source said the Afghan army recently
moved a large amount of ammunition from the city's airport to the
depot.
</TEXT>
