<FIRST>r i AM-Asia-Refugees     08-08 0335</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Asia-Refugees,0351</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hong Kong Police Break-up Protest at Site of Refugee Camp</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police Tuesday broke up a nine-day sit-in by
residents unhappy over the influx of Vietnamese refugees.
   About 100 police carried 26 protesters from the site in a rural
park, authorities said. The demonstrators linked hands and sang
before the officers moved in.
   ``One or two of them did struggle a little bit, but none of them
very violently,'' said district police commander Richard Younge.
There were no arrests, he said.
   Up to 300 protesters had assembled at the site during the
sit-in, although only 26 were there during the early morning raid.
   The protesters said they are concerned that the construction of
a camp for Vietnamese refugees would pollute a nearby reservoir.
They also have said they are unhappy with the influx of Vietnamese
into the British colony.
   Local residents met later Tuesday in the nearby village of Sai
Kung and said they would hold a mass protest demonstration,
government-funded radio reported. No date was given.
   A Hong Kong government spokesman said construction at the site,
which was delayed by the sit-in, had resumed.
   The government is building the detention center to shelter
Vietnamese fleeing their communist homeland. More than 52,000 boat
people have taken refuge in Hong Kong.
   Also on Tuesday, Japanese officials said two wooden boats
carrying 280 Vietnamese refugees arrived in southern Japan.
   One boat with 151 Vietnamese arrived near a small island
northwest of Nagasaki, said Keisuke Sakamoto, spokesman for the
local Maritime Safety Agency, Japan's coast guard.
   The second boat, carrying 129 refugees, arrived in the same area.
   Since May, 592 boat people have come ashore in Japan.
   Kyodo News Service quoted the latest boat people as saying they
left Vietnam to escape poverty.
   Sakamoto said they were to be taken to a refugee reception
center.
   At an international conference in June, Britain and Hong Kong
called for forced repatriation of boat people not fleeing political
persecution. Vietnam refuses to accept such people.
</TEXT>
