<SECOND>PM-Obit-Wilson,0157</SECOND>
<HEAD>A.W. Wilson, Pastor Prominent in 1955 Bus Boycott, Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. A. W. Wilson, whose church
became a rallying point for the 1955 bus boycott that launched the
civil rights movement and raised Martin Luther King Jr. to national
prominence, has died at age 87.
   Funeral services for Wilson, who died at home Friday after a
long illness, will be held Wednesday at Holt Street Baptist Church,
where he was pastor for 50 years and continued preaching in recent
months despite failing health.
   The year-long Montgomery bus boycott began after Rosa Parks, a
black seamstress, refused to give up her seat on a segregated city
bus.
   Organizers held their first meeting at the Holt Street Baptist
Church, the site of mass gatherings and King oratory that are now
part of civil rights lore.
   Survivors include Wilson's wife, Annie Mae Wilson; a son and two
grandchildren.
