<FIRST>r i AM-Refugees-Pirates     08-08 0303</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Refugees-Pirates,0315</SECOND>
<HEAD>71 Feared Dead in Latest Attack by Pirates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARI S. MANIAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of pirates who stormed a
boat carrying 84 Vietnamese stole valuables, raped women and sunk
the vessel, and 71 of the refugees were feared dead, officials said
Tuesday.
   The attack brought to 271 the number of boat people missing and
believed dead as a result of piracy off the coast of this Southeast
Asian country this year, U.N. and Malaysian officials said.
   The officials, quoting the 13 survivors of the latest attack,
said the refugees left Vietnam last week. They were off the Kuala
Trengganu coast, 180 miles northeast of Kuala Lumpur, when they
were attacked Saturday night by pirates in two boats.
   The pirates took their valuables, raped some of the women, sank
the refugees' boat and fled, the officials said.
   The officials did not say how the attackers were armed.
   In the past, refugee officials have blamed most such attacks on
Thai pirates.
   Three survivors of the attack were rescued by oil rig workers
Sunday in the South China Sea, and fishermen picked up the other 10.
   Refugee officials said the survivors were being put into a
refugee camp to await screening for settlement in the United States
or elsewhere.
   In one of the worst such attacks in recent years, a Vietnamese
refugee boat with 130 people aboard was stormed by Thai pirates
April 16. One refugee survived, but the rest are believed dead.
   Officials say this year's death could actually be much higher
than 271, because some attacks leave no survivors and go unreported.
   The refugee officials say they believe most of the pirates were
Thais.
   About 23,000 Vietnamese refugees live in Malaysian camps.
Malaysia accepts them only for temporary stay before permanent
settlement elsewhere.
</TEXT>
