<FIRST>r a AM-People-Breathed     08-08 0188</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Breathed,0193</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former `Bloom County' Cartoonist Joins `Boating'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pulitzer Prize-winning cartoonist Berke Breathed,
whose last ``Bloom County'' comic strips appeared in newspapers
last weekend, will be a contributing editor at Boating magazine,
the magazine announced Tuesday.
   John Owens, editor-in-chief of Boating, said in a statement from
New York that Breathed, an avid boater who has homes in Evergreen
and Florida, will write a monthly humor column titled ``Overboard.''
   Breathed, who owns four boats, said his column will reflect his
consuming interest in the sport.
   ```Boating' looks at equipment in the way I want to look at
equipment _ what's coming out, and why we silly boaters think that
a new-style helm station is exciting,'' he said in the statement.
``The emphasis is on the engineering and the equipment, rather than
the events and personalities.''
   Breathed discontinued ``Bloom County,'' which featured Opus the
penguin, to begin work on a new strip called ``Outland'' that will
begin appearing Sept. 3. ``Outland'' features a black ghetto child
who was a ``Bloom County'' regular, with Opus possibly making
appearances.
   Breathed won the Pulitzer Prize for cartooning in 1987.
