<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-89 1329EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-Hostages     08-08 0560</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Hostages,0573</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tug of War Evident in Iranian Hostage Policy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hostages, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANWAR FARUQI</BYLINE>
<UNK>Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First, Iran's new president offered to
help solve the hostage crisis, then the interior minister renewed
threats against the United States. On Tuesday, a Tehran newspaper
was offering help again.
   The events seem to be part of a tug of war between President
Hashemi Rafsanjani and his followers _ called pragmatic by some and
opportunist by others _ and the hard-liners of Interior Minister
Ali Akbar Mohtashemi for control of Iran following the death in
June of Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini.
   Rafsanjani made the offer of help in his inaugural speech last
week. On Monday, Mohtashemi urged Shiite Moslems around the world
to continue fighting the United States, which Iran cals the ``great
Satan.''
   On Tuesday, the English-language Tehran Times quoted a source it
did not identify as saying Iran would ``definitely'' intercede to
gain the release of the hostages if Washington gave assurances it
would release frozen Iranian assets.
   Rafsanjani, allied with spiritual leader Ali Khamenei, is known
to seek better ties with the West in the effort to rebuild Iran
after eight years of war with Iraq. He appears to see freeing the
hostages as a first step to good relations.
   Mohtashemi's faction, including Premier Hussein Musavi and Ahmad
Khomeini, son of the revolutionary patriarch, wants the revolution
to keep its confrontational edge.
   For hard-liners, diplomatic reliations mean compromise with the
enemy. Many radical Shiite Moslems in Lebanon agree with them.
   Sixteen Western hostages are held in Lebanon, most by Shiite
groups sponsored by Iran. Eight are Americans.
   About $2 billion in assets, including military equipment ordered
before the revolution, were frozen after the U.S. Embassy in Tehran
was stormed in February 1979 by militant students, who held 52
Americans hostage for 444 days. Iran claims the assets now are
worth $12 billion.
   According to the source quoted in the Tehran Times, U.S.
assurances that the assets will be released ``should be concrete
and there should be convincing grounds that these proposals will be
translated into action.'' Excerpts of the report were carried by
the official Islamic Republic News Agency.
   Repeating Iran's frequently stated position, the source said:
``It's a well-known fact that we do not have any direct or indirect
hand in hostage-taking. Of course, we have spiritual influence in
Lebanon which we can use in our efforts for the release of the
hostages there.''
   Mohammad Javad Larijani, former deputy foreign minister and a
Rafsanjani ally, was quoted in a dispatch from the news agency as
saying ``it would be a great achievement for the world of Islam''
if Iran could secure the release of the hostages.
   ``It will make it clear that Iran has always been working for
the benefit of humanity,'' IRNA quoted him as saying.
   Larijani had helped improve diplomatic relations with the West,
but resigned earlier this year when a struggle over the issue began
in the leadership.
   In an editorial Tuesday, the Tehran Times called the United
States ``an oppresser'' for freezing the assets and said relations
between the two countries would be like that of ``lamb and wolf.''
   It added, however: ``As the officials of the Islamic Republic
have said repeatedly, the doors are not completely closed and the
right intentions and thoughts can help resolve the problems.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890808-0078 </DOCNO>
