<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--ManHeld     08-08 0192</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Man Held,0196</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Held in Jail for 87 Days After Complaint Dismissed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WAUKESHA, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A homeless man accused of not paying $6.51
for a meal he had eaten was mistakenly held in jail for 87 days
after the complaint filed against him was dismissed, authorities
say.
   Robert J. Mandt apparently wanted to stay in the Waukesha County
Jail to get three meals a day and a roof over his head, his
attorney, Bradley J. Bloch, said Monday.
   Records showed Mandt was held for 48 days on a misdemeanor
charge of defrauding a restaurant keeper in a March 18 incident.
   The charge was dismissed May 5, but officials did not realize
that until July 29. Mandt was taken to a Milwaukee intersection and
released two days later at his request, Jail Administrator William
H. Conine said.
   The charge was dismissed because of the ``feeling the defendant
had been freeloading on the system'' and already had served enough
time for the offense, said Assistant District Attorney Timothy
Westphal.
   ``It's very unfortunate that he was able to manipulate the
system through a snafu when the paperwork never came through,''
Westphal said.
</TEXT>
