<FIRST>u a PM-MosaicsTalks 1stLd-Writethru a0581 08-08 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mosaics Talks, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0581,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>Art Dealer Agrees to Give Cypriots Access to Mosaics</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to CLARIFY that Cyprus gets access but not
actual possession for two weeks. PICKS UP 7th graf pvs, `Today is ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JODI PERRAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. art dealer agreed today to give the
Greek Orthodox Church of Cyprus access to four sixth-century
mosaics while she decides whether to appeal a judge's order to
return them to the Cypriots.
   U.S. District Judge James E. Noland ruled Thursday that dealer
Peg Goldberg of Carmel had not obtained valid title to the mosaics
when she bought them last summer in Switzerland for $1.2 million.
   Ms. Goldberg had refused to surrender the mosaics until she
decided whether to appeal. On Friday, the Cypriots demanded
immediate release of the artworks, but an agreement was worked out
before a hearing on the request began today.
   The agreement allows the Cypriots immediate access to the
mosaics in an Indianapolis vault. The Cypriots agreed not to remove
the mosaics or do any restoration work for two weeks while Ms.
Goldberg decides whether to appeal.
   If she does not appeal, the Cypriots can take the mosaics home.
   The Republic of Cyprus and the church had sued Ms. Goldberg to
recover the works, which had been stripped from a church in
Turkish-occupied Cyprus in the late 1970s.
   ``Today is a great day for Cyprus. Fifteen years of hard work in
securing our artifacts, our cultural heritage, have not been
wasted,'' said Michael Kyprianou, senior counsel to the Republic of
Cyprus.
   Cypriot officials learned of the mosaics' whereabouts when Ms.
Goldberg offered them to the J. Paul Getty Museum in California for
$20 million in January. The Cypriots sued Ms. Goldberg in March.
   June Walton, an attorney for the Cypriots, said a local Greek
Orthodox priest had been asked to bless the church treasures, which
date to 525 A.D. and depict Christ as a boy. An art expert also was
to inspect the mosaics today.
</TEXT>
