<DOCNO> AP890808-0086 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-89 1400EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Estonia     08-08 0311</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Estonia,0320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Estonians Approve Strict Voting Law</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawmakers in the republic of Estonia on Tuesday
tightened residency requirements for voting and running for office
in a move to stem the influence of Russians.
   Ina Tamet, an editor at official Estonian Radio in Tallinn, said
the Baltic republic's Supreme Soviet approved the law by a 194-36
margin.
   Russians make up about a third of the republic's 1.6 million
people, and some Russian workers went on strike for several days in
July to protest the legislation.
   Ms. Tamet said there were reports the Russian workers would
strike again after the law was approved, but Estonian journalists
had no firm information that a strike would follow.
   The law requires that residents live in one place for two years,
or in Estonia for five years before they be permitted to vote. It
requires candidates for local offices to live in one place for five
years, or if they've moved within Estonia to be residents of the
republic for 10 years before they may run, Ms. Tamet said.
   Despite the dispute over provisions of the law, she said the
legislative debate was ``relatively quiet.''
   Estonians, who are at the forefront of the three Baltic
republics' drive for greater local control over the economy and
political system, say they are being overrun by Russians and other
Soviet ethnic groups, imported to work in the republic's factories.
   Ethnic Estonians are more stable, and therefore would gain from
the new election law.
   In July, the national legislature also gave Estonia and the two
other Baltic republics, Lithuania and Latvia, the go-ahead to begin
wide-ranging economic reforms, including the possibility of
creating their own currencies.
   Economic reformers say that is essential to help them reform the
price structure. They view the rigid Soviet system of state-control
prices as one of the biggest handicaps they must overcome.
</TEXT>
