<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Egypt     08-08 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Egypt,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Expresses Appreciation For Egypt's Efforts in Hostage Crisis</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Hostages</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush conveyed thanks Tuesday for
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak's efforts on behalf of the U.S.
hostages and asked his help in securing release of the body of
American hostage William R. Higgins.
   Bush expressed his gratitude in a meeting with Egypt's new
defense minister, Youssef Sabry Abu-Taleb.
   ``The phone calls were well received. ... He's been so helpful
to us in so many ways,'' the president said at the outset of an
Oval Office meeting.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said later the defense
minister brought a message from Mubarak ``dealing with the current
situation in the region'' and offering ``to help in any way that he
could.''
   He said Bush discussed the continuing U.S. ``concern about
regional security, including Libya,'' and, in a brief discussion of
the hostages, ``reiterated his desire for a definitive accounting
of Lt. Col. Higgins and his concern for the safety and release of
the hostages.''
   Eight Americans are being held by terrorist groups in Lebanon.
   FBI experts concluded Monday that a videotape released by one
terrorist group in Beirut last week does show Higgins dead.
   Abu-Taleb spent 15 to 20 minutes with Bush, and left the White
House without stopping to answer reporters' questions.
   Bush personally called many world leaders last week to seek
their help when terrorists were threatening to kill a second
American hostage, Joseph Cicippio. They suspended the threat on
Thursday under intense international pressure.
   Abu-Taleb is on his first visit to the United States to confer
with top U.S. officials since being named to the military post in a
surprise move by Mubarak four months ago. He replaced Field Marshal
Abdel-Halim Abu-Ghazala after eight years in the office.
</TEXT>
