<FIRST>r a AM-People     08-08 1027</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People,1068</SECOND>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SMOCK, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paul Warhola, who used to give his youngest
brother, Andy Warhol, tips on art, is trying his own hand at
painting _ a can of Heinz vegetarian baked beans and two nearly
identical Heinz ketchup bottles.
   ``I'm starting from scratch on art,'' Warhola said. ``I wouldn't
want you to see the first 10 or so paintings. It will take me a
while to get into stride.''
   Warhola, 67, lives on a farm near Pittsburgh where he grows
flowers and vegetables and keeps chickens, ducks and geese.
   ``I picked Heinz because it's here in Pittsburgh and Andy did
Campbell's,'' Warhola said.
   Warhola already has a collector, a friend in the metals
recycling business who bought the three unsigned paintings for $350
apiece.
   ``He wanted me to sign them `Paul Warhol, Andy Warhol's
brother.''' Warhola said. ``But if I sign them any way but my own
name _ Paul Warhola _ I will cheapen them. I have to be left alone
to do what I think is right.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>RADNOR, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former CBS and now ABC newswoman Diane Sawyer
was called ``indisputably terrific'' and ``extremely intelligent''
in leading the women journalists on three major networks graded by
a panel selected by TV Guide.
   Connie Chung, of CBS, who left NBC this year; Maria Shriver, of
NBC; and Mary Alice Williams, formerly of CNN and now at NBC, were
also graded by the panel in the Aug. 12 issue of the magazine.
   The panel consisted of former CBS anchor Douglas Edwards,
Washington Post TV critic Tom Shales, Barbara Matusow, author of
``The Evening Stars'' and media writer for Washingtonian Magazine;
and Elsa Klensch, style editor, writer, and anchor for CNN. They
were asked to rank each woman in order of preference and comment on
each woman's journalistic ability, on-air presence, and strength
and weaknesses.
   Klensch described Sawyer as having a fantastic presence and
packaging herself very well. But Shales disagreed.
   ``She's the biggest star in the world. But no one knows why. She
didn't have any hot pieces on `60 Minutes' and it was generally
said that she waited to have stories handed to her,'' he said.
   Chung was ranked second. Panelists praised her skill, pointing
out her work as a CBS News correspondent in Washington during the
Watergate scandal.
   ``She's a tough reporter, very formidable,'' Shales said.
   The two men on the panel commented on Chung's sense of humor,
but the women felt she needed to ``loosen up a bit.''
   Shriver, ranked third, received the most criticism by three of
the panel members, who said she did not come across as serious or
sincere.
   Edwards praised Shriver for journalistic competence: ``She does
her homework and is very good in interviews.''
   The panel focused on former CNN vice president and anchorwoman
Williams' on-air presence rather than her abilities.
   ``She's skilled in live situations and she's very comfortable on
the air,'' Matusow said. ``As good an ad-libber as Sawyer, and very
brainy,'' Edwards said.
   Sawyer and Chung reportedly are making $1.6 million each, and
Williams and Shriver are taking in $500,000 each.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: A version moved on sports wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The NFL has decided not to muffle the
Ickey Shuffle.
   The football league on Monday clarified its position on the
touchdown celebration dance made famous by Cincinnati Bengals'
fullback Ickey Woods. The league said the dance was not prohibited
under league rules governing taunting on and off the field.
   ``That brightens my day,'' Woods said Monday after practice.
   Woods traditionally performs the shuffle on the sidelines.
   On Thursday, the Bengals were informed that the Ickey Shuffle
would be banned under a new rules provision adopted in March during
a meeting of the team owners of the National Football League.
   But the NFL, upon further investigation, decided that
celebrations along the bench area were not considered off-field
celebrations, said Joe Browne, NFL director of communications.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: A longer version moved on financial wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavyweight boxing champion Mike Tyson paid
$300 in fines and agreed to conduct three youth clinics after
pleading guilty Tuesday to speeding.
   Appearing with boxing promoter Don King in Albany Traffic Court,
Tyson was fined $100 for a speeding incident on April 26 when he
raced his 1989 Lamborghini with another car. Police clocked Tyson
going 71 mph in a 30 mph zone.
   Judge Stephen Safranko also ordered Tyson to conduct two clinics
at the Arbor Hill Community Center within 60 days.
   For the second incident, which occurred in Albany nine days
later, Tyson was fined $200 and ordered to conduct a clinic for the
Albany Parks Department. Authorities said Tyson got that ticket
while going at an ``imprudent speed'' in a 30 mph zone while again
racing another vehicle.
   Asked by Safranko if the sentences were fair, Tyson mumbled,
``It's fair.'' Tyson had no other comment.
   Tyson, 23, paid the fines to the court clerk in cash.
   The youth clinics will include discussion sessions and could
involve boxing, said Gerard Maney, assistant corporation counsel
for the city.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAG HARBOR, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A planned debut exhibit of Hedda
Nussbaum's photographs has been canceled after a gallery received
threatening calls, New York Newsday reported Tuesday.
   Romany Kramoris, owner of the Kramoris Gallery, said callers had
threatened to damage her property if the Nussbaum exhibit was held,
according to Newsday. The exhibit was to open Aug. 19.
   The photographs were taken during Nussbaum's 18 months of
rehabilitation at Four Winds Hospital in Westchester. The dozen
black-and-white nature photos are titled ``Signs of Life.''
   Sag Harbor village police have stepped up patrols around the
shop, said Officer Evelyn Halliday.
   Nussbaum was the battered live-in companion of convicted killer
Joel Steinberg, who is serving 8 1-3 to 25 years for the beating
death of 6-year-old Lisa Steinberg. The couple illegally adopted
the girl.
   Some callers accused Kramoris of trying to cash in on the case's
notoriety, while one complained the exhibit would glorify Nussbaum,
Newsday said. Kramoris was not at the art gallery Tuesday, and a
person answering the phone there said she would be back Wednesday.
</TEXT>
