<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-89 1448EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-CentralAmerica 2ndLd-Writethru a0551 08-08 0963</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Central America, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0551,0987</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ortega Calls on Washington to Respect Contra `Death Sentence'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY5</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4 grafs for 3rd pvs, `In Managua...' to UPDATE with more
U.S reax; pick up 4th pvs, ``The next...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN WRIGHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TELA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five Central American leaders have signed
a plan to disband the U.S.-backed Nicaraguan rebels by December,
and President Daniel Ortega called on Washington to respect the
Contras' ``death sentence.''
   ``In this way the United States can contribute to peace in
Nicaragua and Central America,'' the Nicaraguan leader said Monday
night upon returning to Managua from a three-day summit at this
Honduran beach resort.
   The plan was a sharp rebuff to the United States.
   In Washington, White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the
United States was ``generally supportive'' of the Central American
leaders' agreement. However, he said any move to disband the
Contras ``must be accepted by them voluntarily.''
   Asked how the United States would react if Honduras tried to
drive the Nicaraguan rebels from its territory, Fitzwater replied,
``It's too early and unfair to say that the game is over.''
   In Managua, opposition leaders said today the government should
meet with the rebels to discuss how to carry out the plan. They
called for continued talks with the internal opposition on the
Sandinistas' pledge to carry out democratic reforms.
   ``The next step will be very arduous,'' said Silviano Matamoros,
leader of the opposition National Conservative Party. ``The
Sandinistas are not exactly known for fulfilling their
commitments.''
   The 120-day plan, laid out in a set of three accords signed
Monday, set a 30-day deadline for a combined U.N.-Organization of
American States observer mission to organize itself and another 90
days for the Contras to demobilize.
   About 11,000 Contras and their 12,000 dependents living in
Honduras along the Nicaraguan border are to be resettled, in
Nicaragua if they want and in other nations if not. Guatemala, El
Salvador and Costa Rica volunteered to take some in, though most
would prefer to go to the United States.
   In approving the plan, the five countries ignored U.S. lobbying
to keep the Contras intact until after February elections in
Nicaragua. Central to reaching an agreement appeared to be a
Honduran decision that, after eight years, it wanted the rebels out.
   In the past, the government had denied the rebels were in the
country, then called for them to leave but allowed them to stay.
   Ortega accused the United States of trying to block the accord,
but U.S. officials and officials of other Central American nations
denied the charge.
   Contra spokesman Bosco Matamoros blamed the outcome on
``political confusion in Washington.''
   ``This is a disaster for the State Department because it tried
to impose its policy too late,'' said Matamoros in an interview
with Costa Rica's Radio Impacto. Last-minute U.S. pressure ``had a
counterproductive effect,'' he added.
   The Bush administration had been lobbying to keep the Contras
active until February's scheduled elections in Nicaragua as a
guarantee of the ``democratization'' that Ortega's leftist
government has promised.
   In Mexico City, where he met with Mexican officials, U.S.
Secretary of State James A. Baker III said he could not comment
because he had not seen a text of the pact.
   Baker noted that the Esquipulas agreement, a Central American
accord signed two years ago, says any Contra demobilization must be
carried out under conditions of safety and democracy in Nicaragua
and must be voluntary.
   ``I don't think the Central American democracies would do
anything to change the terms of the agreement that they have put
forth,'' Baker said.
   If the full 120 days from Monday were used, Dec. 5 would be the
deadline for the new plan. The accords do not mention the
consequences of any delay, but deadlines in previous Central
American agreements have often been observed more in the breach.
   The Central American nations must ``find enough will to go along
with the accords'' if they are to stick, said Costa Rican President
Oscar Arias, who won a Nobel Peace Prize for initiating the
regional peace process more than two years ago.
   It was not immediately clear whether the Contras are willing to
surrender their arms, but assuming Honduras lives up to its word
the Contras would have no territory from which to operate.
   ``We have signed a death sentence for the Contras,'' said
Ortega. He called on the United States to support the accords,
cease ``aggression'' and lift its economic embargo on Nicaragua.
   The Contras have been reduced to making sporadic attacks since
last year, when the United States cut off military aid. Non-lethal
aid continues at a rate of $4.5 million a month, with the
stipulation that it can be used for disbanding and resettling the
Contras.
   ``This is a very difficult situation for the Nicaraguan people.
We have been fighting for 10 years to achieve peace and democracy
for our country and now we feel abandoned,'' Contra spokeswoman
Azucena Ferrey said in Miami.
   The Central American presidents agreed to ask the United Nations
to provide observers and verify the demobilization. Canada, West
Germany and Spain already have volunteered to send observers under
U.N. auspices.
   The accords also call for a cease-fire in the 9-year-old
Salvadoran civil war, but have no provisions for enforcement.
   The presidents had already agreed to dismantle the Nicaraguan
rebels at a summit in February in El Salvador, but a 90-day
deadline for working out the details passed without notice.
   In the meantime, Ortega set elections for Feb. 25 and obtained
an agreement with his domestic opposition that undermined the
Contras by calling for their dissolution.
   El Salvador's civil war has left 70,000 dead, according to
independent estimates, while the Nicaraguan government says the
conflict with the Contras has claimed at least 50,000 lives.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890808-0096 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-89 1457EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Tax-FreeWitches     08-08 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tax-Free Witches,0490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Division of Taxation Rules Witches Entitled To Exemptions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN SCHWARTZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A coven of witches has won tax exempt
status in Rhode Island as a legitimate religious group.
   ``With this ruling, we witches will definitely be able to come
out of the closet and take our place in society,'' said the coven's
high priestess, Joyce Siegrist, also known as Lady Genevieve.
   Tax Administrator R. Gary Clark said he overturned the state's
initial ruling, that the Rosegate Coven did not qualify for a sales
tax exemption, because it proved on appeal that it met the
guidelines for legitimate church groups as set out by a 1986 Rhode
Island Supreme Court ruling.
   Administrative Hearing Officer Sandra Murphy said Tuesday that
she heard about 2{ hours of testimony in May and undertook
extensive research on her own before recommending the action that
Clark took on July 28.
   ``I'm happy that anyone who is practicing a religion in earnest
is able to do so without state impediment,'' she said.
   The coven, also known as Our Lady of the Roses Wiccan Church,
has 30 to 40 members in Rhode Island and meets approximately three
times a month for rituals, said Siegrist.
   The core of the Wiccan worship is belief in a diety with male
and female attributes, whose psychic energy can be tapped. Although
the power can be used for good or ill will, witches do not use it
for destructive purposes.
   When the tax exemption was denied last fall, the division's
questions indicated tax officials were focusing on the apparent
lack of formal theology schools for training Wiccan clergy, said A.
Gregory Frazier, an American Civil Liberties Union attorney who
represented the witches in the administrative hearing in May.
   He said officials also questioned the group's willingness to
allow members to belong to other churches while claiming coven
membership.
   That argument was rebutted when the Rev. Thomas Ahlburn, senior
minister of the First Unitarian Church of Providence, testified
that his church and many Eastern religions also permit members to
belong to other faiths, Frazier said.
   Under state laws, a religion must be a nonprofit group, not set
up for the purpose of avoiding taxes. It must have a litany or
system of prayer, as well as specific doctrines and practices that
its members are expected to follow.
   Clark said the connotation of ``witches'' may have made it more
difficult for the state.
   ``If all the facts were identical and they were not called
witches but were called brothers and sisters, for example, it
probably would not have been anywhere nearly so'' controversial, he
said.
   Murphy said she didn't think the decision would set a precedent.
   ``This was very logical, very straightforward and very
unemotional,'' she said, noting the coven is empowered by the state
to officiate over marriage and burials.
</TEXT>
