<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-89 1458EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u p AM-WrightReplacement Bjt   08-08 0651</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wright Replacement, Bjt,0674</SECOND>
<HEAD>Race To Replace Wright Could Be Toss-Up</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICE GRAVINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrats had a 34-year lock on the
congressional seat held by deposed House Speaker Jim Wright, but
Saturday's special election could spell Republican.
   ``It's a race that we shouldn't lose, but we could lose,'' said
Texas Democratic Party Chairman Bob Slagle.
   Both parties call the election a toss-up. A poll published
Sunday showed the leading Republican had 16 percent, the leading
Democrat had 15 percent, with 64 percent not sure.
   Sissy Day, a Democratic political consultant and a former Wright
aide, said Democrats, angry and disillusioned about Wright's
resignation during an ethics investigation, might not vote.
   Both Slagle and Day feel voters in the district are strong
Wright supporters, and if they can't vote for Wright, they don't
want to bother to vote.
   ``The ones that are maddest about it are really disillusioned
about it,'' Slagle said. ``And they might just say to hell with
it.''
   All the better, say Republicans, who have been inching into
Texas government and now boast U.S. Sen. Phil Gramm and Gov. Bill
Clements among their ranks. But Republicans aren't exactly
predicting victory.
   ``Clearly, we have an opportunity ... but the power of
incumbency is great,'' said Fred Meyer, state Republican Party
chairman. ``Whoever turns out their vote on election day is going
to win.''
   Texas now is represented by nine Republicans and 20 Democrats in
Congress. Four Democrats, three Republicans and a Libertarian have
filed for Wright's District 12 seat.
   The Democrats are Pete Geren, Jim Lane, George Petrovich Jr. and
Bill Turner. Laraine Bethke, Jim Hunter and Bob Lanier are the
Republicans. Robert Buckingham Jr., is the Libertarian.
   Because one candidate must get 51 percent of the vote to win, a
runoff is expected. Lanier, a physician who is host of the
nationally syndicated television show ``60 Second Housecall,'' and
Geren, a Fort Worth attorney, are considered the frontrunners, and
were the two leaders in the recent poll results. Each has his
party's endorsement, although Lane has important endorsements from
labor and police.
   Wright, who stepped down as speaker in May and later resigned
his House seat in the face of an ethics investigation that turned
up 69 instances of alleged rules violations, has not endorsed
anyone.
   The district, which includes most of Fort Worth, went for Ronald
Reagan in 1980 and 1984 and George Bush in 1988.
   But Democrats say the district's traditional blue collar,
conservative, voters who first sent Wright to Washington in 1955
will continue to support their party. They are also counting on a
backlash against the Republicans for the ouster of Wright, the
third-most powerful politician on Capitol Hill.
   Geren has been blasting Georgia Republican U.S. Rep. Newt
Gingrich ``and his Washington gang,'' as the group responsible for
Wright's political demise. Gingrich initiated the probe against
Wright.
   But Steve Hollern, the Tarrant County GOP party leader has said,
``It was the Democrats who threw Jim Wright out of Congress. If
they had been willing to put their neck on the line to save him,
they could have kept him, but the Democratic Congress was not
willing to do that.''
   Lane, considered a distant second as a Democratic contender in
the race, calls himself a ``Jim Wright Democrat,'' and is appearing
with Wright's son on campaign stops.
   Petrovich is putting up billboards with the slogan ``To Protect
Us,'' aimed at a city that fears losing everything it gained under
Wright's considerable influence.
   Republican Chairman Meyer played down the possible effects of
Wright's resignation on Republican candidates.
   ``People are going to vote for the candidate that will represent
them the best in the future,'' Meyer said. ``The rest is history.''
   On the other hand, Republican Lanier has said in the campaign:
``If anyone did a good job, Jim Wright did ... We should all strive
to emulate him.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
