<FIRST>r a AM-BearAttacks 1stLd-Writethru a0607 08-08 0601</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bear Attacks, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0607,0612</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Men Survive Separate Bear Attacks</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 3rd graf to UPDATE with Tuesday's condition, amount of
surgery.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A hunter mauled and chewed by a wounded black bear managed to
walk out of a forest and drive to a town for help, and a man who
waded a river to safety after being attacked by a grizzly bear
asked rescuers if his ears were still on.
   ``I could just hear his teeth grinding against my skull,'' Steve
Nordness, 39, said at Everett General Hospital in Washington state.
He was released Sunday after being treated for wounds on his head,
hands and buttocks that required more than 100 stitches.
   In Alaska, Donald Covertson, 32, was in stable condition Tuesday
at Fairbanks Memorial Hospital with 1,000 stitches piecing together
his ripped scalp, face, neck and ankle. He underwent more than nine
hours of surgery.
   Both men were attacked Saturday.
   Covertson's family said he was attacked by a grizzly on his way
out from checking on land he owns and was not armed. He told a
paramedic that he did not hear the bear before it grabbed him.
   ``The bear had his head in its mouth and shook him,'' said Marge
Nord of the Cantwell Volunteer Ambulance. ``It left and came back
and shook him again. ... He said he could hear the bones
crunching.''
   Covertson, of Palmer, waded the icy, swift Chulitna River and
fought his way through woods to the Parks Highway between Anchorage
and Fairbanks. He collapsed in view of passing motorists, Steven
and Betty Ballek of North Pole, who took him to a gas station for
help.
   ``He asked them whether his ears were still on,'' said the
Balleks' daughter-in-law, Nena Ballek. They were still attached.
   Gordon Waterman, who helps operate the station, said Covertson
was conscious and coherent. He said the bear opened up Covertson's
scalp above his left eye and tore it around the back of his head,
in addition to several puncture wounds.
   ``I don't know how the guy made it, except he had to be in
exceptionally good condition and have exceptional intestinal
fortitude,'' Waterman said.
   Nordness, of Clearview, Wash., said he shot a black bear in the
Beckler River Valley near Skykomish, but the animal, which he
estimated at 400 pounds, ran off into trees and thick brush. The
state's bear season opened Aug. 1.
   Nordness, who was alone, went to a nearby campground to get help
before going after the wounded animal. A young man he remembered
only as Kelly agreed to go with him.
   About an hour later, Nordness, carrying a .30-06 caliber rifle,
spotted the bear charging only a few feet to his left. He fired
point-blank into the bear's chest, but it kept coming and knocked
him down.
   ``Oh God, make him stop, make him stop,'' Nordness said he
thought as the bear stood on his back, tearing into him.
   Then Kelly ran up, scaring the bear off. Despite his wounds,
Nordness walked with Kelly a quarter-mile to his car and drove
himself to Skykomish for help.
   ``I wish I could find the bear that got me. I'd like to have
that carcass for a rug,'' he said.
   ``It could be dead or it could be alive,'' said William Sarvey
of the state Department of Wildlife. He said hunters with dogs were
not immediately able to find the bear.
   Campers were notified of the wounded animal and some decided to
leave, Sarvey said. ``With the high brush, it would be foolish just
to walk in there,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890808-0100 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-89 1508EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Poland     08-08 0830</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland,0857</SECOND>
<HEAD>Minor Parties Say They'll Consider Walesa Offer to Join Coalition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two parties linked to the ruling
communists since the 1940s said Tuesday they will consider an
invitation from Solidarity leader Lech Walesa to join a coalition
government that would exclude the Communist Party.
   But communist leaders, in their first comment on the Walesa
proposal, said it could lead to destabilizing the country.
   Walesa, taking the political offensive Monday four days after
the election of a communist premier, expressed opposition to any
government formed by Prime Minister Czeslaw Kiszczak and said it
would extend the party's 45-year monopoly on power.
   Instead, Walesa said, he would work for a coalition of
Solidarity, the Democratic Party and the Peasant Party, putting the
Communist Party in the position of becoming a parliamentary
opposition.
   In separate statements Tuesday, the United Peasant Party and the
Democratic Party said their leaders would take the proposal under
advisement.
   The communist Politburo, discussing the offer at its weekly
meeting Tuesday, sharply criticized the proposal, according to
state TV.
   Politburo members said it was aimed at breaking the traditional
links between the communists and the Peasant and Democratic
parties, and could undo the agreements reached between authorities
and the opposition at talks in April, an announcer said on the main
evening news program.
   ``It's another impediment by the opposition,'' according to the
report of the Politburo discussion.
   ``The initiative showed by Lech Walesa creates the danger of
opening up a government crisis, which certainly does not serve the
stabilization of the situation in this country.''
   Politburo members also ``pointed out that it complicates the
quick formation'' of a government ``which the country needs so
badly,'' state TV said.
   Walesa press aides in Gdansk said behind-the-scenes negotiations
on forming a joint government have been going on since Thursday
between Solidarity lawmakers and members of the Peasant and
Democratic parties.
   The statement was an apparent rebuttal to Peasant Party leader
Roman Malinowski, who Monday had criticized Walesa as publicizing
his coalition proposal before presenting it to the involved parties.
   Kiszczak, candidate of the communist Polish United Workers
Party, was elected Aug. 3 by the Sejm, or parliament, to form the
next government. Members of the Democratic and Peasant parties
added their votes to the communists' to give him a 237-173 majority.
   Kiszczak, a general who was interior minister for eight years,
said it would take up to two weeks to assemble a Cabinet, which
must be approved by the Sejm.
   Walesa's proposal appears to have opened the road to an
alternative scenario.
   ``The proposal put forward by ... Walesa requires serious
examination and decisions by appropriate statutory bodies of the
Democratic Party. It will be taken into account if the good of the
national and the state requires this,'' the Democratic Party said
in a statement carried on the official PAP news agency.
   The statement, issued by party spokeswoman Elzbieta Otffinowska,
mildly criticized Walesa's offer, saying: ``It is a pity that the
proposal was not presented earlier.''
   The proposal will be taken up Wednesday at a meeting of the
party leadership and its 27 parliament deputies, it said.
   The Peasant Party said in a statement that it has stressed
``numerous times that only a grand coalition government can be an
effective government, gain social credibility and carry the burden
of leading the country out of the deep economic crisis.''
   The phrase ``grand coalition'' has come to mean a coalition of
Solidarity with the communists, something that Walesa has rejected.
   But the Peasant Party's statement said, ``Lech Walesa's
statement published in the mass media shall be considered by the
(party) presidium.''
   There has been no public response by Kiszczak or the Communist
Party so far to the Walesa proposition.
   Kiszczak has been rebuffed so far in trying to enlist Solidarity
members in his Cabinet, and there is fear among authorities that a
government formed with no Solidarity representation will lack
public support.
   The concern has grown because of sharp increases in food prices
last week and a series of wage disputes, mainly involving rail, bus
and postal workers.
   ``Prospects are uncertain for creating a government capable,
through its political and social influence, of effectively
counteracting the dissolution of the economy,'' said a commentary
Monday in the communist daily Trybuna Ludu.
   ``Neither a government only of Solidarity or only of the party
and the ruling coalition will fulful this requirement,'' it said.
   As a result of partially democratic elections in June, the
communists hold 173 seats in the 460-member Sejm, Solidarity 161,
the Peasants 76, the Democrats 27 and the remainder are held by
pro-communist Christian organizations. A 231-vote majority is
needed to form a government.
   The Peasant and Democratic parties used to be rubber stamps for
the Communist Party. In the changing political environment in
Poland, in which all parties expect to compete in four years in
promised fully free elections, the allied parties have started to
demonstrate greater independence.
</TEXT>
