<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-89 1553EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Helms-Art     08-08 0511</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Helms-Art,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Helms Sends `Obscene' Photos to Colleagues</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: Contents of 5th graf may be objectionable to some readers.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Jesse Helms, trying to bolster his
campaign against the use of federal money for offensive art, has
sent fellow lawmakers four photographs that he considers obscene.
   ``I suggest you take a look at the enclosed materials,'' Helms
said in the one-paragraph letter accompanying photographs from a
current art exhibit in Washington. ``It's your call as to whether
the taxpayers' money should be used to fund this sort of thing.''
   The photos were taken by the late Robert Mapplethorpe, whose
work is on display at the Washington Project for the Arts, which
decided to show the exhibition after it was canceled by the
Corcoran Gallery of Art.
   The Corcoran wanted to avoid becoming involved in a political
battle over congressional financing of the National Endowment for
the Arts. The NEA provided one of the grants to underwrite a
national tour of ``Robert Mapplethorpe: The Perfect Moment,'' which
included homoerotic and sadomasochistic pictures.
   The photographs mailed by Helms, from the Mapplethorpe exhibit,
include ``Man in a Polyester Suit, 1980'' and ``Mark Stevens, Mr.
10 1@2, 1976,'' which both show male genitals, one of a young girl
who is partially exposed and one of a young boy standing naked on a
chair.
   The direct object of Helms' wrath is the National Endowment,
which provided $30,000 to underwrite part of the Mapplethorpe
exhibition and tour.
   The Senate recently approved a Helms amendment that bans using
federal funds for material that is considered ``obscene or
indecent'' or ``denigrates, debases or reviles'' beliefs or people
on the basis of religion, race, creed, sex, handicap, age or
national origin.
   Members of the House and Senate Appropriations subcommittees on
the interior will meet in September on the $170 million NEA budget.
In advance of that conference, Helms sent the photographs and
letter.
   A random check with congressional staff found that although the
Washington offices had received the letter and photographs from
Helms, most of the senators and members of the House had not seen
them.
   The letter was marked ``for member's eyes only,'' and during the
monthlong August recess many lawmakers are in their home states.
Although personal and urgent mail is forwarded to members, most
congressional aides said the Helms package would likely remain on
their bosses' desks until they return.
   Helms' recent actions are not new. In April 1988, the North
Carolina senator introduced an amendment to the AIDS research and
education bill renewing an expiring 1987 ban on federal money for
educational materials that promote or encourage homosexual activity.
   Helms' amendment was prompted by a gay-oriented AIDS education
videotape that he screened for several senators.
   ``There's something wrong when federal tax dollars are used for
this garbage,'' Helms said at the time.
   The amendment passed 94-2, but later senators approved a measure
saying that nothing in the bill should prevent dissemination of
accurate information to people at risk. The later amendment
effectively superseded the Helms' measure.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
