<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-89 1904EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Politics     08-08 0629</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Politics,0648</SECOND>
<HEAD>Labor Decides to Stay in Cabinet, Adopts Land for Peace</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The governing body of the left-leaning
Labor Party on Tuesday decided to stay in Israel's ruling coalition
and adopted the principle of trading land for peace to guide peace
talks with Palestinians.
   The massive show of hands that concluded the meeting of the
party's 1,350-member Central Committee put an end to the government
crisis that erupted July 5 over hard-line conditions for peace
talks adopted by the rival right-wing Likud bloc.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's party decided on that day the
government's program for Palestinian elections in the occupied
territories could only be implemented on condition the 20-month
Palestinian uprising ends.
   The plan calls for negotiating an interim self-rule period with
elected representatives of the 1.7 million Palestinians in the West
Bank and the Gaza Strip.
   Likud also demanded continuation of Jewish settlement in the
occupied territories and said no land would be traded for peace. It
said 140,000 Arabs living in the annexed east Jerusalem would not
be allowed to vote, Likud decided.
   On July 10, Labor's leadership bureau voted in favor of leaving
the government. But on July 23, the Cabinet reaffirmed the Israeli
peace plan without the Likud-adopted principles, turning Tuesday's
pre-scheduled Labor meeting into a largely ceremonial event.
   Labor leader and Finance Minister Shimon Peres, however, told
the delegates the party would leave the governing coalition if the
peace process stops.
   ``I'm convinced that we are taking the right path to stay in the
government as long as the peace process continues and to leave it
if it ends,'' Peres said.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin, an architect of the peace
initiative, said it was important to prove to the Palestinians the
Labor Party ``is not accepting silently'' Likud's conditions.
   But others, known as Labor doves, opposed the decision, urging
the hawks such as Rabin to reconsider it.
   ``The only thing (Labor) is doing is being a moderate mask for
the government,'' said legislator Chaim Ramon.
   In what appeared to be a compromise between the Labor hawks and
doves and a move to counter the Likud ``principles,'' the party
adopted 12 points to guide the peace process, including willingness
to trade territory for peace.
   The guiding points also said Israel will not annex the lands it
has occupied since the 1967 Middle East war but would not agree to
the establishment of a Palestinian state there either.
   ``We do not want to annex the territories. That would mean to
live with perpetual uprising, who knows for how many generations,''
Peres said.
   The Labor plan said east Jerusalem Arabs would be allowed to
vote, but outside Jerusalem, and stressed that Jerusalem would stay
``undivided and united under Israeli sovereignty.''
   Another point called for suspension of Jewish settlements once
talks aimed at elections start and said the issue would become part
of subsequent negotiations.
   Responding to another Likud demand, Labor said elections should
start ``without preconditions.'' Negotiations for elections would
run parallel with efforts to quell the uprising, which has claimed
at least 530 Palestinian and 38 Israeli lives.
   Labor also appeared to open a door for some PLO participation by
saying that ``Palestinians from outside'' can participate in the
talks on the final status of the occupied lands on condition their
candidacy is agreed upon by Israel, Egypt and local Palestinians.
   Other Labor points seemed aimed at answering some PLO demands.
They guaranteed free and democratic elections monitored by foreign
observers and said that after the balloting, Palestinians would
receive political rights.
   The Palestine Liberation Organization has rejected the Israeli
program, saying free elections were impossible under occupation and
demanding that elections lead to an independent Palestinian state
with Jerusalem as its capital.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
