<SECOND>AM-Daughter Burned,0250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Pleads Innocent in Burning of Daughter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AKRON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man pleaded innocent Tuesday to charges he
set fire to his pregnant 17-year-old daughter, who delivered a
healthy baby hours later despite having burns over most of her body.
   Joseph Richmond, 41, was indicted by a Summit County grand jury
last week on charges of felonious assault, child endangering and
aggravated arson. He remained in the county jail Tuesday in lieu of
a $10,000 cash bond.
   A pretrial hearing was scheduled Aug. 15.
   His attorney, Charles Houston, will not comment on pending
cases, a secretary in his office said. George Pappas, assistant
county prosecutor, did not return a telephone call Tuesday
afternoon.
   Richmond is accused of dousing his daughter with brake fluid
during an argument July 24 and then throwing a lighted match at
her. He told police he was only joking or trying to scare her.
   Witnesses told police the father and daughter had argued over
whether she should be allowed to go out with friends. Authorities
said Kimberly Richmond is single and lives with her parents.
   Ms. Richmond remained in serious condition in the regional burn
unit at Children's Hospital Medical Center of Akron. Her baby, born
a month prematurely, is in good condition, the hospital said.
   Doctors said Ms. Richmond has third-degree burns over 70 percent
of her body. Last week, she regained consciousness and was taken
off a respirator, said hospital spokeswoman Carol Wallace.
</TEXT>
