<DOCNO> AP890808-0115 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-89 1917EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Dole-Hostages     08-08 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dole-Hostages,0248</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dole Praises President Bush for Handling of Hostage Crisis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Minority Leader Robert Dole said
Tuesday he thinks President Bush is doing a better job than his two
predecessors of dealing with a Mideast hostage crisis.
   But the Kansas Republican also warned that if terrorists carry
out their threat to murder hostage Joseph Cicippio, the United
States will use military retaliation.
   If Cicippio is murdered, ``All bets are off,'' Dole said. ``Then
you would see a military response.''
   Dole, at a news conference, praised Bush for using intensive
diplomatic pressures from at least 12 nations in an attempt to
resolve the situation that led to the apparent murder of hostage
Marine Lt. Col. William Higgins by Muslim extremists in Lebanon.
   The president ``is using every channel,'' said Dole, who said he
was briefed last week by the CIA. Among nations applying diplomatic
pressure are Algeria, the Soviet Union, Iran and Israel, he said.
   ``I really believe there is some optimism,'' Dole said. ``I've
talked to the president about this a number of times.''
   He attributed his optimism to Bush's steady approach and the
more moderate tone adopted by Iran's new president.
   Dole earlier had criticized Israel for not notifying the United
States that it planned to abduct a Shiite Muslim cleric from his
home in South Lebanon. He didn't repeat that criticism Tuesday,
saying instead he thinks ``the Israelis are under some pressure.''
</TEXT>
