<HEAD>As Trial Opens, Prosecutor Says Officials Used Fake Vouchers, Bonus
Checks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Female companionship and winks and nods were used
by a defunct savings and loan to curry favor with regulatory
officials, a federal prosecutor said Tuesday at the fraud trial of
a president of the association.
   Officials at Vernon Savings &amp; Loan Association made thousands of
dollars in political contributions and payments for prostitutes and
then were reimbursed with phony bonus checks and false business
vouchers, said U.S Attorney Robert Hauberg.
   Haugberg said Vernon President Patrick G. King took part in the
scheme by approving expenditures of more than $55,000 from thrift
funds.
   King is charged in a 37-count indictment with conspiring to
defraud the government and misapply Vernon funds. The indictment
alleges that he used thrift money to make illegal political
contributions to several congressmen, including former House
Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, and U.S. Rep. Jack Kemp, R-N.Y.
   As opening statements began Tuesday in King's trial, his
attorney, Emmett Colvin, said King was a victim of government
prosecutors and said they had harassed witnesses into implicating
King.
   Prosecutors said they will call several Vernon officials who
already have pleaded guilty to various charges. Colvin said he will
show during the trial that Vernon owner Don R. Dixon took pain to
ensure that King did not know about the illegal payments. No
criminal charges have been filed against Dixon.
   Vernon Savings was closed by federal regulators in November
1987, with losses totaling more than $1.3 billion.
   King was deputy commissioner with the state thrift regulatory
agency before joining Vernon.
   The witnesses will describe the ``nuts and bolts and also the
winks and nods, the tacit understandings'' of the transactions,
Haugberg said.
