<FIRST>r w AM-Justice-Foreign     08-08 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Justice-Foreign,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justice Department Plans for International Affairs Office</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh, responding
to the increasingly international nature of crime, announced plans
Tuesday to create an Office Of International Affairs in the Justice
Department.
   ``Often more than 50 percent of my day is devoted to some matter
related to our international involvement in fighting drug
trafficking, money laundering, international organized crime and
business fraud, environmental depredations, terrorism or
espionage,'' the attorney general said in remarks prepared for
delivery in Honolulu to the American Bar Association.
   Thornburgh said he would ask permission from Congress to create
the office to coordinate the department's dealings with foreign
governments on law enforcement issues.
   The attorney general said the plan was based on dramatic
increase in international law enforcement activities since he
headed the Justice Department's criminal division in during the
Ford administration.
   ``Upon my return to the department, the biggest single change
that I noticed was the vast increase in the amount of international
activiity in which we are now engaged,'' Thornburgh said.
   The office will report directly to the attorney general.
   Thornburgh has long said he wanted to make the Justice
Department more responsive to the increasing international nature
of crime.
   ``This is an area, I believe, where we have not kept up with the
times,'' Thornburgh said.
   ``Crime is no longer limited by the distance one pony can cover
in a day's time, and a businessman's primary market is no longer
that which is within a wagon's ride,'' Thornburgh said.
</TEXT>
