<FIRST>r a AM-RescueTrial     08-08 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rescue Trial,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>No `Greater Evil' Defense in Operation Rescue Trespassing Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Operation Rescue leader Randall Terry and
four other anti-abortionists cannot argue during their trespassing
trial that they were trying to prevent the greater evil of murder
when they blockaded a clinic, a judge ruled Tuesday.
   ``There cannot be any way in which it can be shown that the
abortions were stopped that day. This is going to be a case of
trespassing, conspiracy to trespass and obstruction of a
business,'' Municipal Judge Richard Paez said.
   Defense attorney Cyrus Zal had asked Paez to allow him to use
the ``necessity defense,'' arguing a law was broken during the
March 25 blockade in order to prevent greater harm.
   ``There are hearts that are still beating today because of the
actions my client took,'' Zal said Monday.
   But the judge said Tuesday he wouldn't allow expert testimony on
the viability of a fetus, saying that question was left to the
Legislature.
   ``I think the law at the time and now is that a woman has the
right to an abortion up to ... 24 weeks,'' Paez said.
   Terry, 29, and Michael McMonagle, 36, both from Pennsylvania;
Don Bennette, 35, of Mission Viejo; Andy Eppink, 41, of Lake Los
Angeles; and Jeff White, 31, of Santa Cruz are each charged with
two counts of conspiracy and one count each of resisting arrest,
blocking an entrance, failing to disperse and violating a court
order.
   Terry, McMonagle and White are acting as their own attorneys.
   ``Can any pro-lifer in this country get a fair trial? Our
defense is gutted right in the forefront. Our defense of why we
were there is that we were saving human lives,'' Terry said.
   The decision allows jury selection to go forward in what is
expected to be a month-long trial.
   The five defendants were among 771 demonstrators arrested last
spring for blocking the entrances of Los Angeles-area women's
clinics as part of a crusade against abortion.
   The city attorney's office says it is prepared to prosecute 539
other anti-abortion demonstrators, trying them in groups of 15 to
20. The remaining 232 originally arrested pleaded guilty and were
sentenced to probation.
