<FIRST>r i AM-Czechoslovakia     08-08 0603</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovakia,0623</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official Meets Cardinal After His Offer to Mediate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The deputy premier met with
Cardinal Frantisek Tomasek, who offered to mediate between
communist authorities and activists seeking political reform, it
was reported Tuesday.
   The Communist Party daily Rude Pravo reported the meeting Monday
between Tomasek and Deputy Premier Matej Lucan. It did not,
however, mention Tomasek's open letter expressing support for a
petition for democratic reforms or his offer to mediate amid
increasing attacks by the authorities on the opposition.
   Prague officials lashed out again Tuesday at activists who
circulated a petition for democratic reform, alleging they are
trying to stir up unrest.
   Tomasek, 90, made his offer to mediate in an open letter Aug. 4,
in an apparent attempt to defuse tension over the forthcoming 21st
anniversary of the Soviet-led invasion of Czechoslovakia, emigre
sources said Monday.
   ``Today, an increasing number of citizens are demanding a share
in the domestic responsibility for the state of society by signing
the petition `Several Sentences' and, to this end, are even
prepared to pay the price of personal sacrifice,'' the cardinal's
letter said.
   The petition has been signed by 15,000 people, including some
Communist Party members.
   Sources close to the cardinal who insisted on anonymity said the
meeting with Lucan ``took place in a very noble and smooth
atmosphere,'' but declined to say whether the meeting produced any
concrete agreements or give other details.
   Rude Pravo said only that Lucan ``appreciated the cardinal's
interest in current developments in our society and the solution of
open questions.''
   In a separate article, the daily quoted officials as criticizing
the petition and its authors. A co-sponsor of the petition,
Stanislav Devaty, was arrested Monday at his home in Gottwaldov,
Moravia. He was arrested twice earlier this year on charges of
anti-state activity, but released both times after staging hunger
strikes.
   Communist Party ideologist Jan Fojtik called the petition ``a
flop,'' Rude Pravo reported.
   The Prague leadership repeatedly has denounced the petition and
said those signing it face fines or imprisonment.
   The criticism is part of a barrage of propaganda against
opposition groups prior to the Aug. 21 anniversary of the 1968
invasion, when renewed anti-government protests are expected.
   Six of the activists who sponsored the petition have been told
they are under investigation and police have searched houses and
done repeated document checks on dissidents in recent days.
   In an interview with Rude Pravo and the official news agency
CTK, the chief investigator of the national security corps,
Jaroslav Spura, said he had proof the petition aimed ``to stir up
unrest, provoke acts of pressure and violate public order.''
   Spura said his investigation was not finished but it already was
clear the petition's supporters sought ``to overthrow the socialist
system in Czechoslovakia.''
   He quoted from a letter allegedly written by veteran activist
Petr Uhl to banned playwright Vaclav Havel. It was not clear how
authorities obtained the letter, and its authenticity could not be
confirmed.
   Uhl's telephone has been cut off by police and Havel has been
ordered by authorities to stay out of Prague.
   Havel was detained twice last week, once for three hours and the
second time for 11 hours.
   About 10,000 people took part in unofficial demonstrations last
year to mark the 20th anniversary of the invasion. Other
anti-government protests took place in October, January and May
when police used force to disperse crowds.
   Tomasek voiced his concern about further violence in his letter.
   ``As a herald of peace I have the duty to warn against
violence,'' he said. He also called on authorities and the
opposition to meet.
</TEXT>
