<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-UrbanLeague 1stLd-Writethru a0659 08-08 0820</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Urban League, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0659,810</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Tells Urban League: `We Will Not Tolerate Discrimination'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS Gray's state to Pennsylvania, updates with reaction
to speech, subbing 3 grafs for 9th graf, Commenting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, sidestepping disputes with
civil rights advocates, pledged Tuesday to work with them to halt
the decline of inner cities and to remove barriers for minorities.
He vowed, ``We will make America open and equal to all.''
   ``My administration is committed to reaching out to minorities,
to striking down barriers to free and open access,'' Bush told
delegates to the 79th annual conference of the National Urban
League.
   ``We will not tolerate discrimination, bigotry or bias of any
kind _ period,'' he said.
   The president got a cordial reception, interrupted by applause
10 times from a mostly black audience of several thousand people.
   He did not unveil any initiatives. Nor did he address several
areas where his administration has alienated civil rights groups,
such accepting without complaint Supreme Court rulings limiting
affirmative action, vetoing minimum wage legislation and nominating
William Lucas to be the Justice Department's top civil rights
enforcer.
   The Detroit lawyer's nomination was rejected by a Senate
committee after criticism by black leaders that Lucas, who also is
black, lacked experience in discrimination cases.
   Bush told the Urban League that ``in many respects, urban
America offers a bleak picture, an inner city in crisis,'' with
problems of crime, drugs, school dropouts, and limited economic
opportunities.
   ``Your problems are my problems,'' Bush said. ``Today, I offer
you my hand, I offer you my word. Together we will make America
open and equal to all. Together, we will find a way to stop the
decline in our inner cities _ to restore hope, and make the '90s a
decade of urban renaissance.''
   Commenting afterward on the speech, Rep. William Gray, D-Pa.,
the majority whip of the House, said, ``I think what we've got here
is a president who's got the right tone. He's given us some
criteria to judge him by but we haven't seen the specifics, the
means for fighting that war on drugs, the means of investing in
education. Education is key but where is the money going to come
from?''
   Urban League President John E. Jacob said that in evaluating
Bush's administration, ``I am willing to concede that the first six
to eight months is the rhetoric period. We will use the next 12
months to determine how well he does in carrying that out.
   ``His rhetoric is right,'' Jacob said. ``He is saying the right
things. Now we have to find out whether he is going to do the right
things.''
   Bush told the audience, ``Now, I'm not afraid to say we've got
hard work ahead of us. We've got to wage war on poverty and wage
war on despair, wage war on the hopelessness that robs us of our
future.
   ``I want to tell all of you here, I'm not going to relax in this
job or rest until I know that I have done everything in my power to
assure that we succeed _ that every child in our inner cities has a
shot at a good job, that every kid stays in school and gets a
quality education, yes, lives in decent housing in a neighborhood
free of drugs, fear and violence.''
   Bush, accused by some civil rights leaders of failing to match
his words with actions, said that ``we've all spent a lot of time
over the past two decades debating the best means of ending unequal
treatment ... about affirmative action, about quotas, about goals
and timetables.''
   However, Bush said that with America's population growing older,
there will be an abundance of job opportunities in the 1990s. ``For
every child growing up today _ black or white, urban or rural _
there will be a job waiting.''
   Bush noted that he has proposed a $250 million dollar increase
in Head Start funds and had included in a $441 million education
package some money for grants to schools hit hardest by drugs.
   He called anew for approval of a program of enterprise zones
giving tax breaks to inner-city businesses, and said that a
six-year-old job training program has been helping disadvantaged
youths enter the workforce.
   There was no mention in the speech of a rumored trip by Bush to
central Africa later this year. White House aides said the
possibility of such a trip is not being widely discussed in the
administration.
   Meanwhile, White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said
Bush has not decided whether to resubmit Lucas' name during the
current congressional recess, which would temporarily avoid the
confirmation process.
   Likewise, Fitzwater indicated Bush was not about to change his
view that no new laws are needed to modify the Supreme Court
rulings. ``That's a decision that's already been made by the
Justice Department,'' Fitzwater said.
</TEXT>
