<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-JewishLeaders     08-08 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Jewish Leaders,290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jewish-American Leaders Meet With President</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jewish-American leaders, concerned about
possible strains in U.S.-Israeli relations over the hostage crisis,
said President Bush ``reaffirmed the close and strong
relationship'' in a meeting with them Tuesday.
   Bush, Vice President Dan Quayle and other administration
officials met with a half-dozen leaders from Jewish-American
organizations at the White House.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said afterwards the
Jewish leaders, who requested the meeting, were ``concerned about
Israel in this process and any general public attitudes that might
develop.''
   He said they expressed support ``for the president and for the
peace process in the Middle East (and indicated) they shared our
anguish over the hostage situation.''
   ``Essentially, it was a discussion of the peace process ... how
that could be helped,'' he said.
   Seymour D. Reich, chairman of the Conference of Presidents of
Major Jewish Organizations, issued a statement later saying: ``The
meeting was positive and productive. The president reaffirmed the
strong and close relationship that binds the United States and
Israel.''
   The terrorists who claim to have hanged Marine Lt. Col. William
R. Higgins in Lebanon on July 31 were demanding that Israel release
the Moslem cleric its commandos abducted on July 28.
   Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole, R-Kan., accused Israel last
week of acting irresponsibly, and Fitzwater said then that some
administration officials shared those sentiments.
   Other Jewish leaders at the meeting were: Edward Levy Jr.,
president of the American Israel Political Action Committee and a
Detroit businessman; Max M. Fisher of Detroit, honorary chairman of
the Republican National Jewish Coalition; Gerry Klein of New York
and Dick Fox of Philadelphia, co-chairman of that coalition; and
Malcolm Hoenleina, executive director of the Conference of
Presidents of Major Jewish Organizations. Reich is a New York
lawyer.
</TEXT>
