<FIRST>u w AM-US-CentralAmerica     08-08 0651</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Central America,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Sees Contras Remaining if Unsatisfied by Peace Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   WASHINGTON _ The Bush administration said Tuesday that the
Nicaraguan Contra rebels can remain together as a fighting force if
they don't like the plan by Central American presidents to disband
them.
   White House Press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater said the
administration is ``generally supportive'' of the pact agreed to by
the presidents of Costa Rica, Nicaragua, Honduras, El Salvador and
Guatemala. But he said ``we're skeptical'' of Nicaragua's
commitment to democratic reforms.
   The agreement calls for the rebels to voluntarily disband by
Dec. 5 and be peacefully repatriated, so long as the Nicaraguan
government moves toward democratic elections.
   But the Bush administration said the pact is far from the
``death sentence'' for the Contras described by Nicaraguan Daniel
Ortega.
   ``We're clearly moving toward demobilization and repatriation
...,'' said Fitzwater. ``We're moving in that direction but I think
it's too early to say that the game's over.''
   ``Our policy is ... we would not like to see demobilization
before the election,'' set for Feb. 25, he told reporters.
   The 120-day plan set out in accords signed by the presidents
Monday set a 30-day deadline for a joint U.N.-Organization of
American States observer mission to be organized and another 90
days for the Contras to demobilize.
   The Contras, whose 10,000 troops are encamped in Honduras along
the Nicaraguan border, are to be part of negotiations with the
commission and the Sandinistas to work out details of the
demobilization, U.S. officials said.
   But Fitzwater emphasized that if the Contras don't like the
conditions developed by the commission, ``The issue then is,
they're still there. If they don't agree to it, they're not
demobilized.''
   U.S. officials would not discuss what stand the Bush
administration would then take on renewed funding for the rebels.
The current aid package calls for $49.8 million in food, clothes
and other non-lethal aid to last through Feb. 28 next year.
   State Department officials refused to confirm reports that the
administration had lobbied the Central American leaders to keep the
Contras intact until the election.
   ``The timetables and the issue of before and after the elections
... is not something that we focus on specifically,'' said Richard
Boucher, spokesman for the State Department. ``What we focus on is
the process and the steps needed to make the process work.''
   The Center for Democracy, a private, non-partisan U.S. group
picked to monitor the Nicaraguan election next February, said the
pact's success depend on how the provisions of a political accord
last week between the Sandinistas and opposition parties are
implemented.
   ``We are at the moment of truth with regard to Nicaragua,'' said
Allen Weinstein, the center's president, ``one that can lead toward
genuine democratization ... or away from those goals.''
   Weinstein, whose organization also monitored the 1986 Philippine
and the 1988 Panamanian elections for the Senate, said the OAS and
U.N. should also seek an immediate start to the promised amnesty
for political prisoners and a plan to let the Contras vote in the
election without having to return to Nicaragua.
   U.S. officials said they were pleased with the parts of the
Central American pact that call for an end to the nine-year-old
Salvadoran civil war being waged by Marxist rebels, the voluntary
nature of the demobilization, and the requirement for verifiable
conditions that will allow peaceful and secure repatriation of the
Contras.
   They also said Nicaragua's recent concessions, announced on the
eve of the Central American presidents' meeting, to ease
restrictions on the media coverage and allow voting by soldiers
were a positive sign.
   Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., chairman of the Foreign
Relations Western hemisphere affairs subcommittee, called for U.S.
cooperation with the accord.
   ``It is our role, as friends of democracy and as neighbors with
a profound interest in the stability of the region, to support this
process,'' Dodd said Tuesday.
</TEXT>
