<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-89 2021EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-MemorialProtests     08-08 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Memorial Protests,0496</SECOND>
<HEAD>Proposal: No Politics, Speeches, Picnics, Bikes at Viet Monument</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group that built a memorial to honor the
city's Vietnam War dead wants to ban political activity, pets,
bicycles and radios at the site to preserve a dignified atmosphere.
   The Philadelphia Vietnam Veterans Memorial Fund also wants to
ban sports and picnics.
   ``It's not just here in Philly, but across the nation, these
memorials have taken on the sanctity of a burial ground,'' said
District Attorney Ron Castille, the group's vice president.
   The American Civil Liberties Union called the proposal
``blatantly unconstitutional.''
   ``The streets and parks belong to the people and are free and
open to them to communicate messages,'' said Stefan Presser, legal
director of the ACLU of Pennsylvania. ``If the Fairmount Park
Commission approves this, there is no doubt in my mind it will be
challenged out of this office.''
   The granite monument is inscribed with the names of 641 people
killed in Vietnam.
   The memorial group said the proposed regulations are not a
response to any specific activities, but are intended to dignify
the memorial.
   The veterans fund wants to allow only memorial services or
ceremonies honoring Philadelphians who died or were listed as
missing in action.
   City officials and the memorial fund officers are negotiating
for a ``deed of gift,'' a document transferring control of the
monument from the non-profit memorial fund to the city. It would
then come under the park commission's jurisdiction.
   Under the proposal, ``Partisan'' activities would be banned,
including demonstrations for or against federal, state or local
governments or their policies.
   Also banned would be any activity by a political party or a
group seeking publicity, speechmaking of a partisan nature and
picketing, sign-waving or leaflet distribution.
   The memorial fund further wants to ban non-political activities
like soliciting, sports, picnics, walking pets, bicycling, roller
skating, littering, spitting, and playing radios or other audio and
video equipment.
   William Mifflin, executive director of the park commission, said
the proposed regulations were unprecedented for his organization.
   ``To my knowledge, we've never had a regulation of this sort,''
he said.
   The commission will consider the fund's proposal in October,
Mifflin said.
   Lloyd Ziff, counsel to the memorial fund, said the proposal was
patterned after rules adopted by the National Park Service for the
Vietnam Veterans Memorial in Washington, D.C., and Arlington
National Cemetery.
   The memorial was dedicated in October 1987 after the memorial
fund raised $1.2 million to build it.
   On Memorial Day, vandals splashed white paint on four parts of
the wall listing the names of the dead. Veterans believed the
desecration was the work of youths they had chased away about 3 a.m.
   Firefighters flushed water over the paint, washing most of it
away, and crews of veterans spent hours before and after a Memorial
Day ceremony scraping and cleaning away what was left.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
