<DOCNO> AP890808-0137 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-89 1818EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Canada-Abortion     08-08 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canada-Abortion,0508</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawyer Tells Court that Quebec Woman Proceeded with Abortion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Quebec woman barred from an abortion by an
injunction obtained by her former boyfriend went ahead with the
procedure, her lawyer told the Supreme Court on Tuesday.
   The court's nine justices had convened in emergency session in
Ottawa to hear the case of Chantal Daigle, a Quebec secretary, who
was believed to have just entered her 23rd week of pregnancy.
   Her lawyer, Daniel Bedard, did not say when or where Ms. Daigle,
21, had the abortion. He apologized to the court but asked for
permission to proceed with the case because Ms. Daigle faces
contempt of court.
   With the urgency removed from the need to proceed before an
abortion would become increasing dangerous, any decision on the
injunction could now be days or weeks away.
   Ms. Daigle's case had focused attention nationwide on abortion
and the lack of a national abortion law. It was the latest in a
series of cases in provincial courts this summer.
   Canada has been without an abortion law since the Supreme Court
in January 1988 ruled that the existing law's stringent
requirements for approval infringed on a woman's rights. The House
of Commons failed to approve any of six proposals in July 1988.
   The outcome was that abortion was a matter between a woman and
her doctor until the provincial court cases emerged.
   The Quebec Court of Appeal last month upheld an injunction
obtained by former nightclub bouncer Jean-Guy Tremblay, 25, Ms.
Daigle's ex-boyfriend.
   She faced a two-year prison sentence and a $42,500 fine if she
proceeded with the abortion.
   But there has not been a warrant for her arrest, said John
Tymchyk, prosecutor in Val d'Or, Quebec, where the injunction was
granted.
   ``We're not the ones who would bring it,'' he said. ``It's a
civil injunction so it would have to be a private individual who
brings contempt charges against her.''
   Both Tremblay and his lawyer, Henri Kelada, said in Ottawa they
did not want to take action for contempt against Ms. Daigle.
   In Toronto, Robin Rowe, national co-ordinator for the Canadian
Abortion Rights Action League, said it was Ms. Daigle's personal
decision.
   ``It shows that women who want and need an abortion will get one
_ no matter what the courts say,'' Ms. Rowe said.
   Prime Minister Brian Mulroney has said Parliament will consider
the abortion issue this fall on return from recess.
   The federal government has argued in the Supreme Court that
abortion is ``within the exclusive legislative authority of the
Parliament of Canada'' and should not be a matter for provincial
courts to decide.
   Quebec's Court of Appeal was divided 3-2 in upholding the
injunction, basing the decision on the provincial Charter of Human
Rights. Justice Yves Bernier wrote in the majority position that
``the child that has been conceived but not born is a reality that
must be taken into account.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
