<FIRST>u i AM-Israel-Attack 1stLd-Writethru a0646 08-08 0826</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Attack, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0646,0845</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jordanian Wounds American, Holds Israeli Hostage Before Being Killed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to include claim of responsibility, more
quotes from Shomron, Rosen. Pickup 9th `She said'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KIBBUTZ LOTAN, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Jordanian soldier crossed the
border Tuesday, shot and wounded an American and held an off-duty
Israel soldier hostage for nearly four hours before a sharpshooter
killed him, officials said.
   His victims said the man told them he was avenging a brother or
sister killed by Jews. Military officials said he was deranged and
acted on his own.
   The siege ended when Israeli troops stormed a tool shed where
the attacker held the hostage in a date grove near the Kibbutz
Lotan, a collective farm 12 miles north of the Red Sea resort of
Eilat and a few miles from the rugged mountains of Jordan.
   ``A sniper very cleanly picked him off,'' said Wendy Maayan, the
kibbutz secretary, who immigrated from Minneapolis.
   Lt. Gen. Dan Shomron, armed forces chief of staff, told army
radio: ``I'm convinced that Jordan still continues to be
responsible so that terrorism would not infiltrate from its borders
into Israel, in spite of such insane soldiers.
   ``In spite of this being a quiet border, both the army and the
civilians are trained to respond quickly to an infiltration. ...
Jordan is doing its best to prevent infiltrations, but sometimes
it's not successful.''
   Israel television said Fatah Uprising claimed responsibility for
the attack, but it did not say where the claim was issued. The
Syrian-backed group is an offshoot of Yasser Arafat's mainstream
Fatah branch of the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   The wounded woman, Lauren Rosen of Englewood, N.J., said on army
radio she was walking with the soldier and another woman when
``this man in military uniform came out quickly from (behind) a
tree, about three trees ahead of us, with a gun, speaking in
English, something about a brother. He fired one shot and I went to
the ground.''
   Officials at Eilat's Yosef Tal Hospital said she was slightly
wounded by a bullet that passed through her neck.
   The attack occurred on her 25th birthday, she said, and ``I was
very, very lucky. I feel just fine.''
   She said it would not frighten her away from the kibbutz, an
assortment of brown stucco buildings that was founded by American
Reform Jews in 1983 and has about 80 residents, a third of them
U.S. immmigrants. It grows vegetables and dates.
   A Jordanian statement identified the attacker as Farid Ali
Mustafa and said he abandoned a border observation post.
   Armed with a U.S.-made M-16, the man attacked at 11:30 a.m. just
outside the fenced kibbutz.
   The army said hostage soldier Osnat Lev, who is in an army unit
that lives and works on collective farms, was rescued after 3 p.m.
by a special anti-terrorist unit.
   Ms. Maayan said an Israeli soldier fired one shot as other
troops shouted and the attacker came into view through a door of
the corrugated steel shed.
   Ms. Lev said on the radio her attacker kept mentioning a dead
sister and asked the location of Israeli army bases he could attack.
   ``He said all the time that his sister was killed, and why was
she killed, and why I killed her. So I said I did not kill her at
all. He said that the Jews killed her and now he comes to kill
everybody,'' the soldier said.
   The sharpshooter fired into the shed about 500 yards from the
kibbutz fence after soldiers attempted to negotiate with the
attacker for hours, radio reports said.
   Shlomo Tushinsky, a member of the kibbutz council, said the
gunman asked for a Koran, the Moslem holy book, and set a deadline.
   ``A copy of Koran was brought and several minutes after that the
story was over,'' he said. Other kibbutz residents said the Arab
was shot when he bent down to pick up the Koran, borrowed from some
Arab workers.
   Israel radio said there were unconfirmed reports the man asked
for the release of Sheik Abdul Karim Obeid, the Lebanese Shiite
clergyman whose kidnapping by Israel on July 27 has triggered a
crisis over foreign hostages in Lebanon. Deputy Army Spokesman Col.
Renaan Gissin said there was no connection.
   In Tel Aviv, Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin said the incident
illustrates that Israel faces a more immediate threat from terror
than many other countries.
   ``For us fighting terrorism is a matter of ... life and death,''
he said.
   Two other border incidents this year involved Jordan.
   In May, a Jordanian soldier opened fire on an Israeli patrol,
wounding two Israeli soldiers before he was killed. Jordan later
said he acted on his own. In March, two gunmen crossed the border
and killed an Israeli soldier. A Palestinian guerrilla group
claimed the attack, and Jordan later announced that it had arrested
several men in connection with the incident.

</TEXT>
