<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaping lizards were everywhere after a curious
employee at a Dallas museum opened a box of 130 chameleons.
   ``They went all over the place,'' said Amy Jumper, a spokeswoman
for The Science Place. ``Their little sticky feet went up the walls
and on people's arms.''
   The tiny, color-changing reptiles were being kept for children
taking a class on reptiles.
   The reptile roundup went on for days and was not without some
casualties.
   ``Unfortunately,'' Jumper said, ``if you pick them up by their
tails, their tails fall off.''
   The recaptured lizards are regrowing their tails, and some have
gone home to live with young museum patrons.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>POCATELLO, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   You're barking up the wrong tree if you
treat Sheriff Bill Lynn's new officer any differently from his
co-workers. He gets to enjoy all the same job benefits, including
life insurance.
   Patrolman First Class Xavier, a 1{-year-old German Shepherd, was
recently added to the policy.
   ``When I first talked to personnel director Lillie Flowers about
adding Xavier to the plan, she thought I was kidding,'' Lynn said.
``But our carrier said as long as the dog is working for the
department, he can be insured.''
   Lynn guarantees Xavier will be a fulltime member of Bannock
County's force. The dog, obtained for the county by a local civic
group, will be used to sniff out drugs, conduct building searches
and as a public relations mascot for the department.
