<FIRST>u i AM-Israel-Uprising     08-08 0430</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Uprising,0442</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Palestinians Killed, Jewish Settler and Two Sons Mistakenly Shot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 20-year-old Palestinian was shot and killed
Tuesday after he threw a concrete building block at soldiers making
arrests in his village in the occupied West Bank, the army said.
   Also Tuesday, Israeli soldiers shot and wounded a Jewish settler
and his two sons during an accidental exchange of fire in the
occupied West Bank, the army said.
   In the Gaza Strip, soldiers found the body of a Palestinian. He
apparently was stabbed to death by fellow Arabs who suspected him
of collaborating with Israel, Arab reporters said.
   Four Palestinians were wounded in clashes with Israeli troops in
the occupied territories, according to hospital officials. They
said the victims included an 11-year-old in critical condition at a
Nablus hospital with a bullet wound in the chest.
   Meanwhile, an underground Palestinian group said in a leaflet
distributed in the West Bank that funds intended to support the
20-month uprising in the occupied territories were being
``plundered.''
   The leaflet named nine Palestinians who it claimed had misused
up to $5 million in uprising funds and urged the leadership of the
PLO's main Fatah faction to penalize them.
   The leaflet, and other pamphlets circulated recently, reflects
growing factional rivalry in the Arab community as the uprising
continues.
   The uprising's underground leadership called for a strike
Wednesday to mark the 20 months of revolt against Israeli
occupation of the West Bank and Gaza Strip. The territories were
captured from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967 Middle East war.
   The victim of Tuesday's clash with the army was identified as
Mohammed Mahmoud Jaber of the West Bank village of Burkin.
   Jaber's death raised to 530 the number of Palestinians killed by
Israeli soldiers and settlers since the uprising began.
Thirty-eight Israelis also have died in the violence.
   Ninety-one Palestinians have been killed by fellow Arabs, most
after they were accused of collaborating. The latest victim was
identified as Suleiman Brak Abu Hamad, 45, of Rafah.
   The shooting of the Jewish settler and his sons occurred when
the settler stopped his car near the West Bank village of Bidya and
fired several shots into a grove patrolled by an army unit.
According to military sources, he mistook the troops for
Palestinians about to attack his car.
   The unit responded with fire, wounding the settler who the army
identified as Daniel Hamtzani. The army said Hamtzani was in fair
condition, his 3-year-old son was in serious condition with a
gunshot wound to the head, and an older son suffered light injuries.
</TEXT>
