<FIRST>r w AM-HealthyAmericans     08-08 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Healthy Americans,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Amputee Vet, Others Honored</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Vietnam veteran double amputee who is
pedaling a bicycle with his arms across the country was named along
with nine other people as 10 Healthy American Fitness Leaders.
   A doctor who developed fitness programs for the mentally and
physically handicapped and a man who helped create Nautilus
excercise equipment were among the others recognized by the U.S.
Jaycees for their roles in promoting better health.
   Bob Wieland, who lost both his legs to a land mine in Vietnam,
said he was trying to inspire others with handicaps by bicycling
from Los Angeles to New York.
   ``I do things like this bicycle trip to give other disabled
people like myself hope,'' said Wieland, who has gotten to
Amarillo, Texas. ``No one has ever pedaled a bike across the
country using their arms.''
   Others named in the annual awards were:
   _Sen. Jeff Bingaman, D-N.M., for founding the Healthnet New
Mexico program.
   _Jack Benedick, also a Vietnam veteran double amputee who has
become a skier.
   _Richard Cendali, founder and director of the International Rope
Skipping Organization.
   _Ellington Darden, described in a press release as an
instrumental figure in the development of Nautilus weightlifting
equipment.
   _Gina Oliva, who created aerobic dance programs for the deaf.
   _Susan Moucha, a leader in physical education for victims of
cerebral palsy.
   _Dr. Julien Stein, who has put together health programs for the
mentally and physically handicapped.
   _Dennis Van der Meer, who introduced a widely-used method of
tennis instruction.
   _and Guy Reiff, who has created a fitness program for children.
</TEXT>
