<FIRST>r i AM-UN-Panama     08-08 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Panama,0296</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panama Asks Urgent Security Council Meeting on `US Interference'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Panama's U.N. ambassador asked Tuesday for
an urgent meeting of the Security Council to consider ``the policy
of destabilization and coercion pursued by the United States
against Panama.''
   No date was set, but requests for a council meeting usually are
honored within a week or so.
   Ambassador Leonardo A. Kam said in his letter that he sought a
continuation of the council debate held April 28.
   He requested the meeting ``in view of the fact that the United
States troops in Panamanian territory have continued the dangerous
escalation of their acts of intimidation, provocation and
aggression against Panama.''
   Panama's government, controlled by Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega,
the commander of the Defense Forces, accuses U.S. troops stationed
there of instigating civil unrest as a pretext for U.S. military
intervention.
   Noriega was indicted on federal drug charges in Florida in
February 1988. The United States has imposed economic and other
sanctions in an attempt to remove him.
   Panama claims the United States wants to retain control of the
Panama Canal, which is to be turned over to Panama in the year 2000
under treaties signed in 1977.
   In the April debate, Panamanian Foreign Minister Jorge Ritter
claimed the United States was trying to provoke chaos and disorder
in his country to justify military intervention.
   U.S. Ambassador Thomas Pickering replied that Panama was
concocting claims of U.S. interference to conceal ``its lack of
freedom and its apparent intention to conduct fraudulent
elections'' that were held May 7.
   Panama's opposition, the Roman Catholic Church and international
observers said the opposition apparently won the election. The
government voided the results.
  
</TEXT>
