<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     08-08 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0433</SECOND>
<HEAD>Showers And Thunderstorms In The West</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain was scattered over the West and parts of the South on
Tuesday, dampening some areas that have suffered forest fires, and
temperatures dropped to record lows across the eastern two-thirds
of the nation.
   Showers and thunderstorms extended from southwestern Washington
across northern California, northwestern Nevada and northwestern
Utah.
   Hail fell at higher elevations near Lake Tahoe on the
California-Nevada border, along with locally heavy rain.
   Southern Nevada also had thunderstorms, and 0.35 of an inch of
rain in a short time at Las Vegas caused some street flooding. The
rainfall raised the city's total for the year to 1.66 inches, about
0.8 of an inch below normal for Aug. 8.
   Lightning striking utility poles throughout the Las Vegas Valley
knocked out power for 40,000 customers. Nevada Power Co. spokesman
Murray Westgate said most areas were restored before dawn, but
hundreds of customers remained without power for several hours.
   Showers and thunderstorms also spread across southern Texas,
along the Gulf of Mexico coast and southern Alabama, and from
Florida across Georgia and the South Carolina coast.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours up to 2 p.m. EDT included
1.37 inches at Tallahassee, Fla.
   Elsewhere, showers were scattered over Lower Michigan and
western New York state.
   Temperatures plunged to record or record-tying lows, mostly in
the 40s and 50s, at more than 90 cities across the eastern
two-thirds of the nation, from Texas to the East Coast and from
North Dakota to Florida.
   The low at the top of Mount Mitchell, N.C., was 35.
   Tuesday's official low for the Lower 48 states was 38 at
Houghton Lake, Mich.
   But at the other extreme, Daytona Beach, Fla., hit a record 97
degrees.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 52
degrees at Johnstown, Pa., to 102 at Gila Bend, Ariz.
   For Wednesday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast
along the coast of North Carolina, from southern Georgia across
Florida and the Alabama coast, as well as over Nevada, Utah,
western Wyoming, Idaho, western Montana, eastern Washington and
eastern Oregon.
   High in the 70s were predicted along much of the Pacific Coast,
over south-central Colorado, the Great Lakes, New England, the
northern half of the Appalachians and the central Atlantic Coast;
in the 90s over southern Florida, southern and southwestern Texas,
eastern Montana, western Dakotas and eastern California; near 110
over the desert Southwest; and generally in the 80s over the
remainder of the nation.
</TEXT>
