<FIRST>u a AM-InterstateFire     08-08 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Interstate Fire,0395</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Closes Rubbish Site; Firefighters Put Out Interstate Fire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HELEN J. SIMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Firefighters Tuesday doused a rubbish fire
that had buckled a section of a major highway, while a judge
ordered the dump where the waste was found to remove garbage piled
beneath two busy roadways.
   A two-judge appeals panel ordered Hub Recycling and Scrap Metals
Co. to refuse any more construction waste until a lower court can
decide whether the facility poses a threat to the community.
   The judges also told Hub Recycling to clean out materials that
lie beneath the highways _ Interstate 78 and U.S. Route 22 _ and
not place new waste under the roads.
   Flames and heat from a pile of debris Monday buckled an elevated
portion of Interstate 78, a critical east-west link with New York
in one of the nation's busiest highway interchanges. State
officials say repairs could take a year.
   Gov. Thomas Kean lauded the decision by the Appellate Division
of Superior Court, saying it would pave the way for a cleanup at
the site, which state officials say is an illegal landfill.
   ``With our hands no longer tied, we can begin to clean up this
mess and make sure the disaster doesn't get worse,'' he said.
   Kean declared an emergency, allowing New Jersey to ask for
federal help in paying for the repairs to the highway.
   Fire officials, using bulldozers to reach buried pockets of
flame, said they had extinguished the blaze, which on Monday
threatened to spread toward Route 22, now the main alternate to
motorists using Interstate 78.
   ``Basically, the fire is out, but there's always the possibility
of something being buried that wasn't knocked out,'' said Larry
Krieger, a fire department spokesman.
   Fire officials are investigating arson, and the state attorney
general's office has opened a criminal investigation.
   State officials allege Hub was dumping materials illegally, and
said they have been trying for months to halt the piling up of
waste at the four-acre site.
   ``The events of the last 36 hours demonstrate that the existence
of this facility poses an imminent threat to the area,'' said
Assistant Attorney General Michael S. Caro. He added that piles of
garbage at the site hindered firefighters' and emergency workers'
access to the dump.
</TEXT>
