<FIRST>r i AM-PLO-Fatah     08-08 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-PLO-Fatah,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fatah Congress Calls For More Military Action Against Israel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUNIS, Tunisia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The fifth congress of Fatah, the main
group in the Palestine Liberation Organization, closed Tuesday with
a call for increased military action to end Israeli occupation of
the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   More than 1,000 members of Fatah rejected Israeli Prime Minister
Yitzhak Shamir's plan for elections in the occupied territories.
Fatah is led by PLO chairman Yasser Arafat.
   The delegates approved a resolution calling for
``intensification of the armed struggle and all other forms of
battle to put an end to the Israeli occupation of Palestinian
territories.''
   Hard-liners had pressed the congress to recommend extending the
armed struggle beyond the West Bank and Gaza. Arafat's recent
declaration that military action would be confined to the occupied
territories helped the PLO open a dialogue with the United States,
Israel's chief supporter.
   The Fatah resolution, distributed by the Palestinian news agency
WAFA, did not say what kind of military operations might be
conducted outside the occupied lands or define ``all other forms of
battle.''
   Under Shamir's election plan, Palestinian delegates would be
chosen to negotiate with Israel.
   Fatah said elections must be held in ``a democratic atmosphere
under international supervision after the withdrawal of Israeli
forces ... as part of a global plan for a definitive solution to
the Israeli-Arab conflict.''
   The congress repeated its call for an international conference
on Middle East peace, continuing dialogue with the United States
and talks with ``democratic Israeli forces'' who oppose the
occupation and ``support the inalienable rights of the Palestinian
people.''
</TEXT>
