<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-89 2010EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Baird-Clinic     08-08 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baird-Clinic,0440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bill Baird Closes Pioneering Boston Abortion Referral Clinic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A longtime abortion rights activist said Tuesday
he has closed his abortion referral clinic because he can't afford
to keep it open, and claimed he has been pushed aside by some
feminist groups and Planned Parenthood.
   Bill Baird, 57, who has lobbied for abortion rights for almost
27 years, said he is bitter about the circumstances surrounding his
departure from Boston, where he established his clinic in 1967.
   He retains abortion referral clinics in Hempstead and Hauppage
on New York state's Long Island. Like Planned Parenthood, the
clinics perform pregnancy tests and refer patients to doctors who
perform abortions.
   ``I emptied everything out Saturday,'' said Baird. ``We wept and
hugged each other and I put a sign out front saying `We Shall
Return.' I think there's something immoral about the original
pioneer being forced out because he can't come up with the rent.''
   Baird said his main source of revenue, college campus lectures,
has been effectively cut off by anti-abortion activists.
   ``I've been very badly hurt by a successful campaign by
anti-abortion forces who threatened to picket or bomb colleges or
universities where I appeared,'' he said.
   Baird also said women's rights groups have resented his work on
their behalf.
   He recounted his appearance onstage at a women's rights rally
when he was asked to leave because he was a man.
   Baird also accused Planned Parenthood and its president, Faye
Wattleton, of attempting to freeze him out of the abortion rights
movement.
   Wattleton did not return calls by The Associated Press to her
New York office Tuesday.
   Baird said he was recently heartened when he was asked to be the
keynote speaker at the New England Collegiate Conference on Nov. 2.
He hopes to tour college campuses again this winter and revive his
crusade.
   He said he and his staff plan to work for a national right to
privacy amendment and want to pressure U.S. marshals into escorting
women to abortion clinics to prevent harassment by anti-abortion
activists.
   Baird began his crusade in the early 1960s, inspired, he said,
by a woman who died in his arms after a self-inflicted abortion
attempt with an coat hanger.
   Baird served three months in prison for distributing
contraceptives. His Hempstead clinic was firebombed in 1979. In
1971, he was arrested on a charge of corrupting a minor for giving
a lecture on birth control before an audience that included a woman
who had brought along her 14-month-old child.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
