<FIRST>r a AM-Bush-Gunman     08-08 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Gunman,0330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Held in Bank Robberies Says He Stalked Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRETEL WIKLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A suspect in eight bank robberies around the
country has told investigators he plotted to kill President Bush
and attended several of his appearances, including one in Michigan,
authorities said Tuesday.
   John Spencer Daughetee, 34, was arrested Friday in Oakland,
Calif., during a bank robbery. He told investigators he had robbed
at least seven other banks and plotted to assassinate Bush, said
Sgt. Sam Maddux, an Oakland robbery investigator.
   ``He admitted that at some point he started hearing voices and
that he has been following the president around the U.S. in an
effort to get close enough to kill him,'' Maddux said Tuesday. ``He
admits carrying guns on his person, a .22-caliber automatic handgun
and a .380-caliber automatic handgun.''
   Maddux said Daughetee, believed to be from Flora, Ind., said
during interviews with Oakland police and FBI agents that he was in
a crowd of about 4,000 people who attended Bush's speech in the
Detroit enclave of Hamtramck on April 17.
   ``I think there was some indication that he was close to the
president in Detroit,'' Maddux said. ``But security was very tight.
... Because of the need for some type of ID, he wasn't allowed in.''
   WXYZ-TV in Detroit reported that Daughetee had staked out a
position the night before Bush's speech, but couldn't get to it
because he would have had to pass through a metal detector.
   The station also said Daughetee found a spot in a house with a
line of sight but couldn't get positioned before the president
finished his speech.
   Maddux said Daughetee confessed to a bank robbery spree dating
back to November 1986, beginning with a bank in Sacramento, Calif.
Maddux said the other banks Daughetee admitted to robbing were in
Miami; Charlotte, N.C.; Baltimore; Portland, Ore.; San Francisco,
where he hit two on Friday, and Oakland.
</TEXT>
