<FIRST>u i AM-Salvador     08-08 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador,0476</SECOND>
<HEAD>Summit Accords Seen as Propitious for Salvador Peace</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Central America</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Both sides in El Salvador's
10-year-old civil war on Tuesday praised the peace accords signed
by five Central American presidents and said they could contribute
to the search for peace here.
   The high command of the rebel Farabundo Marti National
Liberation Front, or FMLN, said it ``vigorously applauds'' the
accords.
   The presidents of El Salvador, Guatemala, Honduras, Costa Rica
and Nicaragua on Monday signed an agreement for demobilizing within
120 days the Nicaraguan rebels based in Honduras.
   The presidents also exhorted the Salvadoran government and FMLN
to negotiate a solution to the war, which has killed an estimated
70,000 people.
   In a communique over their clandestine radio station, the
Salvadoran rebels called the accords ``a victory for revolutionary,
progressive, independent and democratic forces of the region.''
   President Alfredo Cristiani, who took office June 1, said he was
pleased with the results of the three-day session in the Honduran
port of Tela.
   ``For the first time the Salvadoran problem has been given this
level of consideration by the presidents, who commit themselves to
contribute to peace in El Salvador,'' he said.
   He underscored what he said was a commitment by Nicaraguan
President Daniel Ortega to halt his leftist government's support
for the FMLN.
   However, unlike sections of the accords dealing with Nicaragua,
no procedure was specified for verifying or enforcing the
Salvadoran provisions.
   Col. Rene Emilio Ponce, chief of the joint chiefs of staff,
nevertheless called the accords ``a big political defeat for the
FMLN.''
   The accords ``vehemently urge'' the FMLN to agree to an
``immediate and effective cease-fire.'' The rebels, in Tuesday's
broadcast, did not respond to that demand.
   Guillermo Ungo, president of the Democratic Revolutionary Front,
said it was positive that El Salvador's conflict was recognized at
the summit.
   Cristiani had indicated he would try to link demobilization of
the Contras to demobilization of the FMLN during the summit. Ungo
and other leftist leaders applauded his decision not to do that.
   Eduardo Colindres, former chief of staff to Christian Democrat
Jose Napoleon Duarte, who preceded Cristiani as president, also
considered the Tela accords positive.
   ``They oblige Cristiani to fulfill commitments to strengthening
democracy,'' he said.
   Both Ungo and Colindres noted the opposition's recent efforts to
get negotiations going between the government and the FMLN.
   Cristiani, of the rightist Arena party, in his inaugural address
offered to talk with the FMLN, but proposed a non-governmental
commission for such talks. The rebels rejected that mechanism as
dilatory and doomed to failure.
   Upon his return from Honduras Monday night the president said he
now is willing to enter into a direct dialogue with the rebels.
</TEXT>
