<FIRST>u i AM-Panama     08-08 0555</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama,0574</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>US Soldiers Detain 29 Panamanians Who Entered Military Zone</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAFAEL CANDANEDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. soldiers detained 29 Panamanians
who entered a restricted military area Tuesday and released them
after confiscating their weapons, a spokeswoman for the U.S.
Southern Command reported.
   She said among those briefly detained were 10 officers and
troopers of the Panamanian Defense Forces, including Maj. Manuel
Sieiro. He is a brother in-law of Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega who
is commander of the Defense Force and controls the government.
   The spokeswoman, Mercedes Morris, said five Panamanian
journalists were among the civilians in the group.
   She said in a telephone interview the Panamanians were detained
because ``they ventured without authorization into a military
zone'' reserved exclusively for American forces.
   Ms. Morris said about 40 U.S. Marines were conducting ``a
reconnaissance exercise on roads'' leading to the Panama Canal when
the Panamanians entered the area in 15 vehicles.
   A number of submachine guns, rifles and pistols were confiscated
and will be returned to the Defense Forces through a
U.S.-Panamanian coordinating commission in charge of handling
problems related to the security and defense of the canal, Ms.
Morris said.
   She said the Panamanians were detained for about 1 hour and 15
minutes.
   Ms. Morris was asked if the Panamanians were held at gunpoint
and she said, ``The necessary security measures required in this
case were taken.'' She refused to give further details.
   Mayor Alberto de Santis of the town of Arraijan, 9 miles west of
Panama City and near the site where the incident occurred, said the
Panamanians were ``stopped at gunpoint'' by the Marines and held
for 2 hours and 45 minutes.
   He told reporters about 100 people demonstrated against the
American troops as they passed through the town in six armored
vehicles. The Panamaninan vehicles then appeared and followed the
Americans, according to the mayor.
   He said that at a jungle area a few miles outside of town the
American vehicles turned around and the Marines surrounded the
Panamanians ``at gunpoint'' and detained them.
   Sieiro is Defense Forces commander for the Chorrera military
area, a few miles west of the capital and in the area where the
incident took place.
   A Defense Forces spokesman declined comment on the indicent.
   The Panamanian journalists asked that they not be identified by
name.
   The incident is the latest in a series of confrontations between
American and Panamanian troops in recent months.
   Noriega was indicted in February 1988 by two federal grand
juries in Florida on drug trafficking and money laundering charges.
The U.S. imposed economic sanctions against Panama last year when
Noriega refused to step down.
   Most of the incidents between Panamanian and U.S. troops
involved the exchange of a few shots at nighttime and the
occasional detention for a brief period of Americans by Panamanian
police for alleged traffic violations. No one has been reported
hurt.
   Noriega has accused the United States of trying to force him to
resign and replace him with a ``docile'' government to avoid
turning the canal over to Panama by the years 2000 as stipulated in
treaties signed in 1977.
   The American Southern Command insists it has the right to
conduct military exercises in defense of the canal under the
treaties.
   The pro-Noriega news media calls the exercises a provocation.
</TEXT>
