<FIRST>r a AM-LynnFire 2ndLd-Writethru a0753 08-08 0695</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lynn Fire, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0753,0713</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rooming House Fire Kills at Least Three; 4 Missing</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 3-4 with 3 grafs to UPDATE with two bodies recovered,
search suspended for night, cause being investigated, clarify that Hogan
is a police lieutenant.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BX5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN GALVIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LYNN, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire raged out of control for three hours
and gutted a dilapidated rooming house Tuesday, forcing tenants to
swing from ropes and leap to neighboring roofs because there were
no exterior fire escapes. Three people were killed, and at least
five remained unaccounted for.
   The city had previously filed a criminal complaint against the
owner of the Ben Crest rooming house for failing to install a
sprinkler system; a lawyer for the owner said installation of
sprinklers was to have begun next week.
   Rescuers aided by a crane brought in to clear rubble from the
four-story brick building recovered two bodies by Tuesday night but
neither had been identified, said police Lt. Richard Hogan.
   The search was suspended shortly before 7 p.m. and was not
expected to resume until late Wednesday morning, he said. The cause
of the blaze was still being investigated.
   Early estimates put the number of registered guests and visitors
at about 37, and initial reports indicated at least five people
were unaccounted for, Hogan said.
   Survivors said an alarm failed to sound.
   ``I pulled on the fire alarm, and it broke right off in my
hand,'' said Dwayne Rogers, 25, a fourth-floor resident who tried
to wake other tenants before escaping to an adjacent roof with Leo
McDonnell, 46.
   ``We saw a couple of people that couldn't reach the roof, and
they got torched,'' Rogers said.
   McDonnell and Rogers said they lost one elderly man they had
awakened on their way out.
   ``I turned around and Scottie wasn't there,'' McDonnell said.
``There wasn't anything more we could do.''
   Thirty-five of the 40 rooms were rented Monday night, officials
said.
   Deputy Fire Chief William Conway said the city encourages
exterior fire escapes, but they are not required. He said if there
is no fire escape outside the window of a room, ropes are an
acceptable alternative.
   Seven tenants and two police officers were injured, said police
Capt. Fred McGovern, and Conway said at least seven firefighters
were injured, three seriously.
   The most seriously injured was a firefighter who broke his hip
in a two-story fall while trying to rescue a woman who froze with
fear at her window.
   Fire Chief Curt Numberg said that when he arrived on the scene
about 12:30 a.m., ``people were jumping out of windows ... climbing
down on ropes that knotted up and never reached bottom.''
   Tenants said screams filled the night.
   ``It wasn't screams of help, it was more like screams of
burning,'' said Bobby Barrett, 19.
   One victim died at the feet of the first officer on the scene
after jumping from a second-story window to escape the flames,
McGovern said. The other two confirmed casualties were visible to
firefighters through upper-story windows.
   Al DiVirgilio, mayor of this decaying city of 80,000 on the
seacoast five miles north of Boston, said two criminal complaints
were pending against the rooming house. One citation involved an
illegal woodshop in the basement of the building, which housed
retail space on the first floor.
   The other, however, involved the owner's failure to install a
sprinkler system required under a 2-year-old city ordinance adopted
after a 1984 rooming house fire in Beverly that killed 15, the
mayor said.
   The Ben Crest's owner, Leo Allard of Nahant, has been battling
the ordinance in court. Allard refused to comment Tuesday on
anything relating to the ordinance or the fire.
   His attorney, James E. Smith, said his client and other rooming
house owners were only seeking reasonable time to install sprinkler
systems, and he said work on a system at the Ben Crest was due to
begin next week.
   Second-floor resident Richard Stokes, 53, nursed his right hand
which was raw and sore from sliding down a rope.
   ``I could only hold on about half-way, so I jumped the rest of
the way,'' Stokes said.
</TEXT>
