<FIRST>r a AM-AtlantaMayoral     08-08 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Atlanta Mayoral,0474</SECOND>
<HEAD>Maynard Jackson Headed for Third Mayoral Term As Main Opponent Bows
Out</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AX4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CURT ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The race for mayor of this glittering,
crime-plagued Southern capital became a one-man show Tuesday when
former Mayor Maynard Jackson's only opponent quit the campaign.
   ``I have decided that my greatest service now is to ensure that
this campaign does not divide our city's families,'' said Michael
Lomax, the Fulton County Commission chairman.
   Lomax told reporters he believed he might have been able to win
by pounding on the crime issue that has been his major campaign
theme.
   But, he said, ``I felt that it would have been too costly a
victory, and that's why I stepped aside.''
   He stopped short of endorsing Jackson, but said he pledged to
work with him. ``I have extended the olive branch,'' he said. ``I
believe he will be generous enough of spirit to receive it.''
   The non-partisan election is Oct. 3 to succeed Mayor Andrew
Young, who cannot serve a third consecutive term.
   Lomax spokesman Jim Gray said earlier Tuesday that Lomax decided
to quit the race because of his poor showing in recent polls.
   ``The decision has been made that Michael just can't win. Even
though the gap has narrowed, it hasn't narrowed enough,'' Gray said.
   Jackson said he was not ready to assume the mayor's job was his.
   ``I don't want to take anything for granted. Never, ever do
that,'' Jackson said after a speech to a business group Tuesday.
   Both Lomax and Jackson are black Democrats, but the key to
Lomax's chances was the white, conservative business community that
is a powerful minority in predominantly black Atlanta.
   Jackson, who became the city's first black mayor in 1974 and
served two four-year terms, was often at odds with the business
establishment. But campaign aides say his support among whites this
year is better than in either of his previous two races.
   Lomax tried and failed to capitalize on Atlanta's crime rate,
ranked worst in the nation in the latest FBI survey. Jackson,
meanwhile, pledged not to let the city's ongoing construction and
business boom overrun neighborhoods.
   Lomax's withdrawal allows him to keep his job as chairman of the
county commission, which he would have been forced to give up next
Wednesday at the mayor's race qualifying deadline.
   Jackson was mayor during Atlanta's string of child slayings and
also endured a police department scandal over cheating on promotion
exams, but he was widely credited with adopting progressive race
relations policies that opened the doors of City Hall to blacks and
women.
   He refused to hold city functions at any organization that
discriminated against minorities and began the city's affirmative
action policies in contracts.
</TEXT>
