<SECOND>AM-People-Nureyev,0226</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rudolf Nureyev To Tour as King of Siam</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ballet dancer Rudolf Nureyev, who defected from
the Soviet Union in 1961, is about to leap into musical theater, it
was announced Tuesday. Starting Aug. 18, Nureyev will tour
nationwide as the King of Siam in the Rodgers and Hammerstein
musical, ``The King and I.'' The tour is scheduled to run for 85
weeks over the next three years.
   ``The King and I'' opened on Broadway in 1951, starring Yul
Brynner and Gertrude Lawrence. Brynner and Deborah Kerr starred in
the film.
   Nureyev says he has never seen the show.
   The tour's Anna will be Liz Robertson, who played Eliza
Doolittle in ``My Fair Lady'' and later married the lyricist of
that show, Alan Jay Lerner, according to the announcement from
Joshua Ellis, a public relations firm.
   The ``King and I'' tour, which will visit 13 cities this year,
will be scheduled around Nureyev's commitments with the Paris Opera
Ballet, where he has been artistic director since 1983, and his
touring dance troupe, ``Nureyev and Friends.''
   Cities to be visited this year are Syracuse, N.Y.; Toronto and
Ottawa, Canada; Boston; Hartford and Stamford, Conn.; Tampa;
Wilmington, Del.; Seattle; Costa Mesa and Los Angeles, Calif., and
two to be announced.
