<SECOND>AM-AIDS Child,0243</SECOND>
<HEAD>Authorities: Young AIDS Patient Victim of Sexual Abuse, Drug Injections</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 9-year-old girl contracted AIDS by being
sexually abused by her mother and was reportedly injected with
drugs as punishment, state social workers said.
   The girl has been taken into custody by the state and placed in
foster care with a family who knows her, said David Reilly,
regional director of the Texas Department of Human Services.
   ``From everything we can determine from the circumstances, it
appears to be she got it (AIDS) from abuse,'' he said Monday.
   ``Everybody just wants to give her the best we can give her in
the time she has,'' Reilly said. ``She is with the person she wants
to be with and if that works out, there is no reason to move her.''
   The girl's mother, a drug abuser, died of acquired immune
deficiency syndrome. Social workers believe she is the person who
sexually abused the girl and gave her drug injections as a form of
punishment.
   Authorities held a closed-door hearing Monday concerning the
girl. District Judge Tom Rickhoff said the hearing was closed
because of a law requiring confidentiality in AIDS cases.
   After her mother's death, the girl was left to live with
relatives. Social workers were concerned those surroundings were
further endangering her life, so they obtained an emergency court
order to remove the girl and place her in foster care.
