<HEAD>Striking Teachers Invade Nicaraguan Embassy in Guatemala City</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GUATEMALA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of striking teachers invaded the
Nicaraguan Embassy Tuesday, remaining there for about an hour, and
other teachers battled police near the National Palace.
   Police spokesman Guillermo Molliendo said the street clash
started when about 20 teachers, demonstrating outside the palace,
insulted police patrols.
   He said police moved in to disperse the strikers and one teacher
was arrested for smashing shop windows with a piece of metal. The
Red Cross reported three of the strikers were injured.
   Strike organizers said some 100 teachers entered the Nicaraguan
Embassy and asked embassy officials to intercede with President
Vinicio Cerezo to grant their demands.
   An estimaed 800 students supporting the teachers' strike blocked
traffic in a town 125 miles north of the capital and occupied a
court building.
   Other students threw nails on the highway between Huehuetenango
and La Mesita near the Mexican border, puncturing tires and
blocking traffic, according to police.
   The nation's 35,000 elementary and high school teachers left
their jobs Monday defying a labor court ruling that declared the
strike illegal.
   The public school teachers began job actions May 1, demanding a
monthly increase of $80 in their salaries.
   They currently make from $136 to $328 a month plus a flat bonus
of $70 monthly.
   The teachers have been joined occasionally by 15,000 other
government employees and there have been almost daily marches and
demonstrations in Guatemala City.
