<FIRST>r a AM-HUDSuit     08-08 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD Suit,0382</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suspended HUD Accountant Named in Justice Department Suit</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-HUD Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HILLIARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Department of Housing and Urban
Development accountant was named Tuesday in a federal lawsuit
seeking to recover more than $1 million in funds allegedly diverted
from the beleaguered agency.
   The lawsuit contends Douglas R. Turner diverted to the bank
account of his company, Green View Developers Inc., $1,006,130 in
federal funds intended to assist low-income facilities in obtaining
housing. The company also is named as a defendant.
   U.S. Attorney Mike Norton and acting Assistant Attorney General
Stuart E. Schiffer said the complaint seeks damages arising from
false statements that Turner allegedly made and for alleged false
record keeping by Green View.
   Turner allegedly used the HUD money in Green View's account to
purchase land in the Denver suburb of Littleton, to pay a
contractor to build a house on the property and to buy a car.
   ``We'll move for a default judgment and seek damages, but we
want equitable transfer of the funds back to the federal
government,'' Norton said.
   The case against Turner began when a Denver-area HUD auditor
discovered the alleged diversions after finding payment requests
for Green View assigned to a project that was off the agency's
rolls.
   Turner was suspended without pay on June 4 and the unfinished
house caught the attention of federal agents. Agents said the house
is located in a neighborhood where lots run between $35,000 and
$45,000, and homes from $170,000 to $750,000.
   The lawsuit is the result of a detailed investigation performed
by the Office of the Inspector General, HUD, Denver and the Federal
Bureau of Investigation.
   Sources said the alleged theft occurred in HUD's Section 8
rent-subsidy program, which gives developers subsidies to build
housing for low-income people.
   The inquiry overlaps a probe by auditor's from HUD's Office of
Finance and Accounting of fraud and embezzlement in the sale of HUD
foreclosed homes.
   Nationwide, about 80 branch offices are being examined.
   Mary Brunette, top aide to HUD Secretary Jack Kemp, reported in
June that the Denver accountant allegedly directed Section 8
payments through an automated cash transfer system, from the U.S.
Treasury into his bank account.
</TEXT>
