<FIRST>r a AM-PrayerServicePanic     08-08 0285</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Prayer Service Panic,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>130 Youths Treated After Storm Hits Open-Air Prayer Service</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MORRISON, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four people remained hospitalized Tuesday
after a hailstorm drenched a Lutheran youth prayer service at an
outdoor amphitheater, sending 130 people to hospitals for
hypothermia and other problems.
   The fast-moving storm unleashed a torrent of rain and hail on
Red Rocks Amphitheater about 10 p.m. Monday _ two hours into the
``Fire Power'' prayer service attended by 9,000 teen-agers from
across the United States, said Gary Lane, Denver's director of
parks and arenas.
   ``When you have youths dressed in T-shirts and shorts and a
storm can kick up and drop temperatures 20 degrees, you get some
borderline hypothermia cases,'' Lane said. Temperatures dropped
from 65 degrees to about 45 in minutes.
   Authorities said some youths also were hyperventilating, some
were hysterical and others may have suffered from altitude sickness
from overexertion. Red Rocks, part of the Denver parks system, is
at 6,400 feet elevation in the mountain foothills 14 miles west of
Denver.
   Four Flight for Life helicopters and 35 ambulances transported
the chilled teen-agers to eight Denver-area hospitals. All but four
of the 130 people who were transported were released after
treatment.
   Officials said David Jones, 40, of Franklin, N.C., was in stable
condition for treatment of chest pains; Phyllis Westerman, 32, of
Blue Springs, Mo., who also complained of chest pains, was in good
condition, and Tammy Dennison, 16, of Lancaster, Texas, and Cynthia
Jennings, 17, of Bonfield, Ill., both were listed in good condition
and were under observation for asthmatic conditions.
   About 17,000 teen-agers from across the country are attending
the five-day youth convocation by the Lutheran Church's Missouri
Synod. The gathering began Saturday.
</TEXT>
