<FIRST>r a AM-AlterationDiscrimination     08-08 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Alteration Discrimination,0450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Saks Fifth Avenue Settles Tailor Made Sex Discrimination Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Saks Fifth Avenue department
store chain said Tuesday it has agreed to change its policy of
charging customers for alterations on skirts and dresses but not
for fixing suits, blazers and slacks.
   The out-of-court action settles a class action discrimination
lawsuit filed by Muriel Mabry of Anaheim Hills and Lori Anderson of
Mission Viejo, who bought dresses and were charged $40 each for
alterations. At the same time, the ritzy department store was
tailoring suits, slacks and blazers for free.
   ``We are now adding several free alterations on dresses and
skirts, and we will continue to review the policy for similar
appropriate revisions,'' said Patricia Fox, spokeswoman for the
Saks Fifth Avenue store in Costa Mesa.
   Mabry and Anderson took their case to feminist attorney Gloria
Allred, who accused Saks of illegal discrimination and asked the
court to issue an injunction that would force the store to charge
equally for alterations.
   The suit also sought $250 for each woman hurt by Saks' bias over
the past three years. Allred said the suit, filed Sept. 8, 1988,
was resolved amicably.
   Bill Acton, a spokesman for Saks, maintained that there had not
been the issue of a double standard involved and that no damages
were paid.
   Saks, he said, ``has never had a double standard so it can't
agree to end one.'' He explained that the store previously charged
for work done on dresses and skirts because of the work involved.
However, he said there was no charge for clothing that was
considered ``unisex.'' Since 1980, he said there has been no charge
for ``courtesy'' work on slacks or blazers done for men or women.
   As a result of the settlement, however, the company decided to
``take a second look'' at its policy of charging for alterations
done on skirts and dresses, Acton said.
   Allred lauded Saks' change in policy at a news conference
Tuesday.
   ``Saks' response to the plaintiffs' suit could serve as a model
for the industry. As a major force in the American fashion
industry, Saks is sensitive to issues that affect women,'' Allred
said outside the Saks store in Beverly Hills.
   Many department stores charge women, but not men, for
alterations. Others sometimes charge men a small fee for major
alterations.
   ``Hopefully, other large retail chains will follow suit, and if
they do not, we expect that other women will file lawsuits as we
did,'' Mabry said, adding the victory ``is especially sweet in that
two women, size 2 and 4, could take such a big issue and prevail.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
