<FIRST>u i AM-SouthAfrica     08-08 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa,0462</SECOND>
<HEAD>Archbishop Tutu Joins Demonstration In Support Of Defiance Campaign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAHM VENTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Archbishop Desmond Tutu and other
anti-apartheid leaders demonstrated Tuesday in support of a
national defiance campaign. Police reported widespread student
unrest in townships near Cape Town.
   Tutu was among several opposition clergymen and academics who
addressed a church service held in solidarity with former detainees
who have begun defying restrictions imposed by police following
their release.
   The black Anglican archbishop, the 1984 Nobel Peace laureate,
joined about 60 people in a demonstration outside St. George's
Cathedral after the service. Outdoor protest demonstrations are
illegal, but police did not intervene.
   Hundreds of activists released from detention this year were
served with restriction orders requiring them to be at home each
night and to report daily to local police stations. Many were
banned from political activities.
   On Sunday, 21 Cape Town area activists said they would defy
their restrictions. Other former detainees are expected to join
them on Aug. 20 as part of a defiance campaign begun this month by
the anti-apartheid movement.
   In mixed-race townships near Cape Town, students supporting the
campaign have been staging protests and erecting street barricades.
Several large rallies were held Tuesday.
   Police headquarters said officers fired tear gas in three
incidents Monday to disperse crowds of students. One delivery van
was firebombed, and other vehicles were stoned, police said.
   Maj. Gen. Herman Stadler, a police spokesman, said, ``We can
expect the unrest will increase toward the elections.''
   Parliamentary elections are scheduled to be held Sept. 6.
   Residents of Oukasie, a ramshackle rural black township,
meanwhile won a potentially decisive court victory in their
long-running struggle against government efforts to relocate them,
their lawyer, Geoff Budlender, said Tuesday.
   Pretoria Supreme Court Justice Kees van Dijkhorst ruled Monday
that the government acted improperly last year when it declared the
55-year-old township an ``emergency camp.''
   Under terms of the declaration, rents in Oukasie were raised by
more than 50 percent, unauthorized visitors were barred, and
permits were required to renovate homes. Civil rights workers said
the declaration was imposed to make life so miserable Oukasie
residents would leave voluntarily.
   Government lawyers said Tuesday they would appeal.
   White authorities have tried for years to coax or coerce the
approximately 6,000 residents of Oukasie into moving to a newer
township 12 miles away.
   The official reason for Oukasie's intended demise is that the
government considers it an unhealthy slum.
   Residents believe the real reason is that Oukasie is a few
hundred yards from the white suburb of Brits. Brits, 30 miles west
of Pretoria, is a stronghold of the far-right Conservative Party
</TEXT>
