<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-89 2336EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-DC-10Crash-Reward     08-08 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-DC-10 Crash-Reward,0420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Engine Manufacturer Offers Parts Reward</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Electric Co. is offering rewards
for pieces of the jet engine from United Airlines Flight 232 that
broke up over western Iowa.
   General Electric spokesman David Lane said Tuesday that
handbills have been distributed in an area of western Iowa where
parts of the engine may have landed to keep up interest in the
search.
   The engine parts are key in discovering why the DC-10
experienced engine trouble and lost almost all of its steering
control when hydraulic lines were cut. The planes crew managed to
guide the jumbo jet to Sioux Gateway Airport at Sioux City and
attempted an emergency landing. The fiery, tumbling crash killed
111 people of the 296 on board.
   Sweeps by military aircraft over the area to try to find engine
fragments ended Friday, said Ted Lopatkiewicz, a spokesman for the
National Transportation Safety Board in Washington D.C.
   Officials said they are not planning a ground search of pastures
and fields in Buena Vista County.
   ``It's a big area out there,'' said Buena Vista County Sheriff
Chuck Eddy. ``It's kind of a sit-and-wait situation right now.''
   GE, the manufacturer of the jet's engine, will offer rewards
through the end of August for rotating parts from the engine, Lane
said in a telephone interview from his office in Evendale, Ohio.
   ``A representative authorized by the NTSB will look at each of
the recovered parts,'' Lane said. ``A representative of GE Aircraft
will determine the level of reward.''
   Eddy said GE distributed the information last week to property
owners and farmers. He said the fliers specify the reward is for
engine parts and offer as much as $1,000 for some of the parts.
   The search has been concentrated 60 miles east of Sioux City.
   Parts have continued to turn up, officials said. On Thursday, a
farmer found fragments of a jet fan blade while working in a hay
field, Eddy said. One fragment measured 10 by 12 inches.
   Lopatkiewicz said a titanium fan disk and a shaft from the
engine have not been located. Investigators have said that finding
the disk and shaft would help them determine what caused the engine
to malfunction.
   Investigators hope harvests in late September will turn up more
engine parts.
   Lopatkiewicz said one NTSB investigator remains in Iowa to wrap
up the federal agency's crash-related work, but probably will
return to Washington in a week.
</TEXT>
