<SECOND>AM-Philippines-Rescue,0198</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Navy Rescues Vietnamese Soldiers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has turned over 10
Vietnamese soldiers to Vietnam's embassy one week after a U.S.
aircraft carrier rescued them from a barge drifting in the South
China Sea, officials said Tuesday.
   Ruben Domingo, chief intelligence officer at the Commission on
Immigration and Deportation, said the 10 are to be flown home
Wednesday.
   The USS Ranger rescued the soldiers with 29 other Vietnamese on
Aug. 2 about 80 miles west of Subic Bay Naval Base. The U.S. base
is 50 miles northwest of Manila.
   Domingo said the soldiers were stationed in the Spratlys, a
chain of islands in the South China Sea claimed by China, Vietnam,
Taiwan, Malaysia and the Philippines.
   The soldiers apparently were on the a barge when it broke loose
from its moorings during a storm, he said, without specifying an
exact date.
   The U.S. 7th Fleet said in announcing the rescue last week that
while the barge drifted, those aboard the barge rescued 29
Vietnamese refugees from a foundering boat. The 39 drifted 10 more
days before a plane from the Ranger spotted the barge, the
statement said.
