<HEAD>Six Bodies Recovered from Wreckage of Sightseeing Plane.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WELLINGTON, New Zealand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Search teams on Wednesday
recovered six bodies from the wreckage of a sightseeing plane that
crashed in the Southern Alps with nine American and Canadian
tourists aboard, police reported.
   They said there were no survivors.
   A New Zealander was piloting the twin-engine Britten Norman
Islander that went down Tuesday near Mount Aspiring on South Island.
   A police spokesman in Dunedin said the bodies had not been
identified and he gave no indication when identities of the victims
would be released.
   An uncomfired report said the Americans were from Wisconsin.
   New Zealand Press Association said the bodies were taken by a
helicopter from the crash site to a mountain base camp and would be
transferred to Glenorchy.
   Two rescue dogs were used to help a team of 27 police and rescue
personnel locate the bodies, according to the press agency.
   It said the wreckage was scattered at an elevation of about
4,000 feet on the mountainside and the dogs were brought because
some of the bodies were buried under snow.
   Police said when the plane crashed it triggered a small
avalanche.
