<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-89 1409EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv09   08-08 0679</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 09,0696</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv09</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Wednesday, Aug. 9</HEAD>
<HEAD>One Shock After Another</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American economic history in recent years is
recorded in a series of shocks, but the encouraging lesson that
might be drawn from them is that somehow the country has survived
them all.
   More are coming, accompanied by alarming predictions about the
decline of America. There is, for instance, the coming of a united
Europe in 1992, viewed by alarmists as a fortress Europe that will
exclude American goods.
   Before that time arrives, however, we must contend with the
alarming report issued after the big stock market bust of 1987, in
which 33 economists from 13 countries said the world economy was in
the worst mess since the 1930s.
   The crash, the esteemed economists said, was attributable to the
existence of major and unsustainable imbalances in the world
economy, the most glaring of which was the growing indebtedness of
the United States.
   ``Unless more decisive action is taken to correct existing
imbalances at their roots, the next few years could be the most
troubled since the 1930s,'' they stated in their report, ``The
Global Economic Crisis: After Wall Street.''
   Theirs was not the first warning about imbalances.
   Throughout the 1980s publications flapped the storm flags about
ruinous inflation, soaring interest rates, energy shortages and
credit crunches. The common theme was America living beyond its
means. The forecast: Collapse.
   Before that, in 1979, President Carter delivered his malaise
speech. Americans suffered a crisis of confidence, he said. They
doubted the purpose and meaning of their own lives. They had lost
their sense of national unity.
   Delivered from the heights of the presidency itself, from a
leader expected to correct such defects of spirit, the speech was
demoralizing. Some who didn't feel dispirited before the speech
might have felt that way afterwards.
   It was a time of other crises too, especially that produced by
the high price of imported oil. Can anybody forget the grim
warnings of disaster, of an America unable to compete in the world
because it had been outfoxed by Arabs?
   If problems with oil wouldn't do America in, then the Japanese
would. Why it was demonstrated in showrooms all over America: The
Japanese produced better cars and lower prices and beat Detroit in
Detroit's own territory.
   Americans did everything wrong. They consumed instead of
produced, spent instead of saved, wasted time instead of putting
their noses to the grindstone, indulged themselves in the present
instead of planning for the future.
   Considering the pace at which this transition was occurring, it
was said, America would become a second-rate power by the turn of
the century. The future belonged to Japan, if not to the Soviet
Union, which would bury us economically if it didn't destroy us,
and probably the world, in an atomic battle.
   Edward Yardeni, never one to join in the ecofadish (economic
fad) thinking, which generally is pessimistic and always alarming,
declares that things are not nearly what they might seem.
   Yardeni, director of economics at Prudential-Bache Securities,
talks instead about the triumph of capitalism, the collapse of
communism, free-market spirit, global markets, cost-reducing
competition, free trade, economic reform, technological innovation,
communications, de-emphasis of military.
   The entire world, he indicates, may be reaching for another
level of achievement. It is a dynamic one in which problems are
more transitory than permanent, and become resolved eventually
rather than allowed to destroy.
   Americans haven't saved? Yes, he concedes. Americans were young
and in a consuming mood. Now that they are growing a bit older they
will save. Emerging economies in contrast will take to spending
like Americans used to.
   In a dynamic world problems aren't necessarily permanent or
reflective of national weaknesses. ``The pessimists aren't seeing
the big global picture,'' he says.
   ``Communism has failed. Capitalism has triumphed. By 1993, U.S.
government bonds should yield 5 percent and the Dow Jones
industrial average should be at 5000,'' which is a way of saying
America will prevail.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Wed., Aug. 9.</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890808-0184 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-89 1402EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a AM-Right-to-Die Adv14   08-08 1089</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Right-to-Die, Adv 14,1121</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv14</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Mon AMs, Aug. 14, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Family In Right-to-Die Case, the Pain `Is Always There.'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL MANNING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOUNT VERNON, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Joe and Joyce Cruzan visit their
32-year-old daughter in her bright, private room at the Missouri
Rehabilitation Center, they can't help wonder what she would tell
them if she could speak.
   ``She would say, `Pull the plug, stop it. I don't want to live
like this. I have no dignity,''' Joe said during a visit to the
hospital where Nancy Cruzan has lain comatose for six years. ``I
think that probably would be the key word, no dignity.
   ``She used to come to me and say, `Dad, my car is not running
very well,' and I would fix it for her. Now, it's `Dad, I'm in a
situation that I can't help. Can you do something for me?'''
   So far, the answer has been no.
   The Cruzans hope that will change this fall when the U.S.
Supreme Court rules on their request to remove feeding tubes that
sustain Nancy's life. The case is the first time the court has
agreed to consider the troubling issue of when it is appropriate to
stop medical treatment _ to pull the plug on a life.
   The Cruzans' world changed forever on Jan. 11, 1983. Nancy,
driving home from work, lost control of her car and it overturned.
At first she was presumed dead; by the time paramedics revived her,
she had irreparable brain damage.
   Ever since, Nancy Cruzan has been in what doctors call a
``persistent vegetative state.''
   Lying in bed in a small, fourth-floor room, she breathes on her
own but by all accounts is unaware of her surroundings. Birthday
and greeting cards are taped to a window; a wide-brimmed straw hat
with ribbons hangs near the door.
   Nancy's body is stiff and her hands so contracted that her
fingernails cut into her wrist if not trimmed. Her eyes are
sometimes open, roaming aimlessly, but she does not respond to
voices or gestures.
   The Cruzans visit weekly. Joyce makes colorful gowns for her
daughter to wear instead of drab, hospital-issued clothing. She
used to talk to her daughter during those visits, but not so much
anymore.
   ``It's always been an exercise in futility. It's always been
more for me. I used to come in and tell her everything and now
sometimes I tell her stuff. Sometimes, I just brush her hair and
sit and touch her.''
   Medical experts say Nancy Cruzan could live another 30 or 40
years, as long as she is given food and water through a feeding
tube implanted in her stomach.
   The Cruzans, who live in Carterville in southwest Missouri, have
fought for approval to remove the tube.
   A state court judge said a year ago they could ask the hospital
to remove the feeding tube. But the Missouri Supreme Court
overturned that decision in a 5-4 ruling last fall. Acting as her
guardians, the Cruzans appealed to the U.S. Supreme Court, which is
expected to hear the case in November or December.
   No federal appellate court has ruled directly on the issue and
opinions are split at the state level. Arizona and Massachusetts
high courts have ruled that such patients retain a federal
constitutional right to refuse such treatment, including feeding,
while Missouri and Washington ruled to the contrary, said Bill
Colby of Kansas City, the Cruzans' attorney.
   In the most famous right-to-die case, the New Jersey Supreme
Court ruled in 1976 that Joseph and Julia Quinlan had a right to
take their comatose daughter, Karen Ann, off a respirator. The U.S.
Supreme Court declined to review the case and Karen died at age 31
in 1985, nine years after her respirator was removed.
   The Cruzans, like the Quinlans, want to remember their daughter
as she was before her accident _ an independent young woman who
enjoyed life.
   ``If she had her way, she'd like to come back like she was,''
said Cruzan, 55, a sheet metal worker. ``That's what I wish, but
it's not going to happen.''
   The crux of the Cruzan case is the lack of a state law allowing
removal of food and water in such cases. In fact, the Missouri high
court noted the state living will statute prohibits such removal
from terminaly ill patients.
   While the statute never was an issue in the case and Nancy
Cruzan is not terminally ill, it is important because it reflects
the state's policy of not including food and water as medical
treatment that can be withdrawn.
   Colby is optimistic the Supreme Court will rule in favor of the
Cruzans.
   ``It's an important part of our country's traditions that
recognizes the sanctity of the family,'' he said. ``I think the
U.S. Supreme Court will continue to recognize the importance of the
family in our case.''
   The state Supreme Court ``improperly discounted the rights of
the individual'' in the 14th Amendment, he said. That amendment
says no state shall deprive any person of life, liberty or property
without due process.
   ``Within this concept of individual liberty is the right for
that person to accept or reject invasive medical treatment,'' Colby
said.
   Missouri Attorney General William Webster, while sympathetic to
the family, disagreed with Colby's interpretation. ``We don't
believe the 14th Amendment extends the right to privacy to remove
food and water in this case.''
   The issue, he said, is ``whether the constitutional right of
privacy extends to the right of a third party, when the patient is
not terminally ill, to withdraw nutrition and hydration from an
incompetent ward of the state.''
   The Legislature could pass a statute allowing the removal of
food and water from patients like Ms. Cruzan, although lawmakers
this year refused to act on such a measure, he said. ``I can't
project how I would feel if I was in their circumstances. I don't
know if anybody can.
   ``But I'm not sure if the tragic nature of the circumstances
gives rise to argue a constitutional right of privacy where the
Supreme Court has been silent on the issue and the words don't
appear in the Constitution.''
   The ordeal has taken its toll on the family. Cruzan has trouble
sleeping and his wife has taken medication to fight depression.
   ``It's always there, just below the surface,'' Cruzan said.
``When you go to bed at night and the first thing usually when you
wake up in the morning.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, Aug. 14</NOTE>
