<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     08-08 0794</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0831</SECOND>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock in UAL Corp. rocketed higher after the
parent of United Airlines disclosed that investor Marvin Davis had
made an unsolicited offer to buy the company, which for months had
been rumored a takeover target.
   The conditional offer by Davis reportedly values UAL at $200 a
share or $4.32 billion. UAL said its board will consider Davis'
proposal on Wednesday.
   UAL shares jumped $46.25 to close at $210.75 Monday on the New
York Stock Exchange.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Management employees at three ``Baby Bell'' telephone companies
struggled to cover posts left vacant by the walkout of more than
150,000 union workers in 15 states and the District of Columbia.
   Officials said direct-dial customers were not appreciably
affected on Monday but some other services were delayed on the
first business day since members of two unions, the Communications
Workers of America and the International Brotherhood of Electrical
Workers, walked out beginning at midnight Saturday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A call by Eastern Airlines pilots union leaders to
continue the 5-month-old strike has been swiftly backed by
rank-and-file members and should be reinforced in caucuses held
around the nation this week, union officials said.
   Straw polls or voice votes in more than a dozen cities are
expected to underscore the pro-strike sentiments of Air Line Pilots
Association members, ALPA spokesman Hank Weber said Monday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two former Merrill Lynch &amp; Co. stockbrokers and
a New York lawyer were charged in connection with the Dennis Levine
insider trading ring, whose exposure triggered a crackdown on Wall
Street corruption in 1986.
   In a civil lawsuit, the Securities and Exchange Commission on
Monday accused the three men and an investment company formed by
two of them of unlawful trading in 15 stocks in an international
scheme from March 1984 through June 1985.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government prosecutor said a new indictment
would be filed by October against junk bond pioneer Michael Milken,
who already has been charged with 98 counts of racketeering and
securities fraud.
   At a hearing Monday in federal court in Manhattan, Assistant
U.S. Attorney John K. Carroll told Judge Kimba Wood the government
was targeting Oct. 1 to file a superseding indictment against
Milken that is widely expected to contain further allegations of
securities law violations.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Con artists invoking God's name as endorsement
for investment schemes are working religiously to cheat thousands
of Americans out of hundreds of millions of dollars, state
securities regulators warned.
   Officials said Monday that quick-buck artists have cheated
15,000 believers out of $450 million since 1985 in scams ranging
from bogus investment funds offered by self-proclaimed ``born
again'' financial planners to givers of ``divinely inspired''
investment advice about coins and real estate programs.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush intends to sign historic
savings and loan legislation Wednesday and the Treasury will borrow
the first $5 billion installment for the bailout a day later.
   Bush will sign the bill at a White House ceremony, almost
exactly two years after the last bailout of the S&amp;L insurance fund,
congressional and administration sources, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said Monday.
   Congress broke a two-day standoff early Saturday morning by
passing the S&amp;L bill, six months after Bush called for emergency
action to close or merge 500 insolvent thrift associations.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. and Soviet officials will begin
negotiations toward a new, long-term grain agreement in December,
agriculture and trade officials say.
   Secretary of Agriculture Clayton K. Yeutter said in remarks
prepared for delivery Monday at a meeting of the U.S. Feed Grains
Council in Chicago that a new long-term grain agreement would
``help stabilize our trading relationship and hopefully serve as a
mechanism for additional sales.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Buyers of Acuras are the most satisfied with
their cars and their dealers, according to a new survey.
   It was the third straight year that the nameplate from Japan's
Honda Motor Co. luxury division topped the survey by J.D. Power and
Associates.
   Buyers of cars made by West Germany's Mercedes-Benz and Japan's
Honda and Toyota Motor Corp. followed Acura, according to the
survey released Monday. The U.S.-made Cadillac from General Motors
Corp. placed fifth.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market rolled up a strong advance Monday, as the Dow
Jones average of 30 industrials jumped 41.54 points to 2,694.99,
just 27.43 points shy of the record closing high of 2,722.42 it
reached on Aug. 25, 1987.
   Bond prices were unchanged to slightly lower.
   The dollar edged higher against most key currencies in thin
trading.
   Crude oil and sugar futures prices fell; cotton futures slipped
the daily trading limit; soybean futures rose and livestock and
pork futures were mixed.
</TEXT>
