<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-89 0237EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-UALOffer Bjt   08-08 0748</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UAL Offer, Bjt,0772</SECOND>
<HEAD>UAL Board To Consider Davis Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials of UAL Corp. say they will give
``careful consideration'' to an unsolicited takeover offer from
investor Marvin Davis, which sent shares of United Airlines' parent
company soaring 28 percent.
   The offer from Davis, who unsuccessfully bid to acquire the
parent of Northwest Airlines earlier this year, reportedly values
UAL at $200 a share or $4.32 billion, although analysts say the
price could rise if others make offers.
   UAL shares jumped $46.25 to close at $210.75 a share Monday in
heavy trading on the New York Stock Exchange.
   UAL described the offer Monday as ``highly conditional'' but
declined to give further information. The UAL board will consider
it at a Wednesday meeting, officials said.
   ``While the board of directors has not decided whether a sale of
the company is in the best interest of the company's shareholders
and other constituencies, in keeping with its fiduciary duty, the
board will give careful consideration to Mr. Davis' proposal,''
Stephen M. Wolf, UAL chairman and president, said in a statement.
   Jim Fingeroth, a spokesman for Davis, said the Los Angeles
investor would not make any comment on his offer, which was
disclosed Monday.
   United is the nation's second-largest airline after American
Airlines in terms of paid passenger miles.
   The carrier owns 80 percent of its 408-jet fleet, the highest
percentage of ownership among the major carriers and a factor seen
as enhancing its value to suitors. Its other planes are leased, a
practice common with airlines.
   Earlier this year, United announced orders for as many as 370
new Boeing Co. aircraft valued at $15.74 billion.
   United also has a large route network in the Pacific, the
world's fastest-growing air-travel region. And last month _ one day
before the deadly crash of a United DC-10 near Sioux City, Iowa _
the carrier filed petitions with the Department of Transportation
for several new European routes.
   Louis Marckesano, an airline analyst for the Philadelphia-based
investment firm Janney Montgomery Scott Inc., said Davis' bid is
reasonable.
   ``What I expect is that it will trigger interest in the
airline,'' he said. ``The key is who will be new bidders, which
could include other airlines.''
   In 1987, members of the union representing United's pilots
proposed an employee takeover of UAL for $4.5 billion, which was
rejected as inadequate.
   Capt. Jim Damron of the Air Line Pilots Association said Monday
the union has not seen Davis' proposal, but that the union's
financial and legal advisers would study it.
   ``The pilots have a long-time interest in employee ownership in
whatever form that would take,'' Damron said.
   Davis, a former oil wildcatter who once owned moviemaker 20th
Century-Fox Film Corp., prompted a takeover battle for NWA Inc.
when he announced March 28 he had offered to purchase the Eagan,
Minn.-based parent of Northwest Airlines for $90 a share.
   The NWA board of directors rejected the offer, and Davis
appealed directly to shareholders with a tender offer. The board
then put the airline on the market, eventually selling it to a
group headed by Los Angeles investor Alfred Checchi for $3.65
billion, or $121 a share.
   UAL stock rose sharply as a result of the NWA bidding, going
from $117.50 in mid-June to $190 in late July amid speculation that
investors such as Robert Bass and Davis had purchased stakes in UAL.
   The stock settled in recent trading, closing Friday at $164.50.
But it soared Monday as word spread about the Davis bid, opening at
$196 and climbing to $210.75 at the close.
   The U.S. Transportation Department has indicated recently it
would no longer look kindly on leveraged takeovers of major U.S.
airlines, and Marckesano said a high-debt bid for United could draw
opposition.
   ``It would weaken the company to such an extent it would not be
a viable carrier,'' he said.
   But, he said, ``If someone with ample new equity like Checchi
makes an offer, I don't see that much room for Transportation
Department objection.''
   In reaction to Davis' bid, Standard &amp; Poor's Corp. put United's
$215 million in BBB-rated industrial revenue bonds on review for
possible downgrading. Such a move would increase borrowing costs
for the airline.
   United reported a 14 percent increase in its second-quarter
profit from a year earlier. For the quarter ended June 30, the
airline reported net income of $141 million, or $6.52 per share, on
revenue of $2.5 billion. The company had revenue of $8.98 billion
in all of 1988.
</TEXT>
