<FIRST>r f PM-Hewlett-Packard-Samsung     08-08 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hewlett-Packard-Samsung,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>HP Will Share Technology, Resell Samsung Workstations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALO ALTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. computer manufacturer
Hewlett-Packard Co. has signed a technology-sharing agreement with
Samsung Electronics Co. and intends to resell low-end workstations
built by the South Korean company.
   The move was seen as an effort by Hewlett-Packard to capture
more of the burgeoning worldwide market for workstations,
high-performance desktop computers priced from $5,000 to $100,000.
   By sharing technology on development of so-called reduced
instruction set computer semiconductor chips, Hewlett-Packard could
gain a competitive edge over rival manufacturers who are trying to
win acceptance for their own RISC-based chips.
   Hewlett-Packard is expected to devote it own manufacturing
resources to ``high-margin'' workstations and other products, said
Andrew Allison, a writer who follows the workstation market,
expected to reach $20 billion annually by 1992.
   ``Samsung is a very credible low-cost alternative for HP,'' he
said.
   Hewlett-Packard rarely has resold computers built for it by
others, and the move indicates how serious HP is in fighting for a
share of the workstation market, Allison said.
   Two weeks ago, Hewlett-Packard announced its first agreement to
share its computer technology in a deal with Hitachi Ltd. of Japan.
The two will develop super-fast computer chips to be used in
computers manufactured by both companies.
   Hewlett-Packard last year bought Apollo Computer, at the time
the second-largest maker of technical workstations.
   Samsung Electronics, a division of South Korea's Samsung Group,
manufacturers both semiconductor chips and computers. Samsung's
computers are expected to be in the $12,000 range.
   Sun Microsystems of Mountain View is among the major competitor
to Hewlett-Packard over the RISC chip and computer market.
   Hewlett-Packard plans to also share some advanced chip-making
techniques with Samsung, as well as a version of the its Unix
operating system. Samsung has the right to independently market
products based on the technologies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
