<FIRST>r f PM-JerricoSale     08-08 0430</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Jerrico Sale,0447</SECOND>
<HEAD>Long John Silver's Parent Will Sell to Investment Groups</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A relatively low stock price and stable
cash flow has prompted directors of the parent company of the Long
John Silver's Seafood Shoppes chain to agree to be acquired for
$620 million.
   Warren W. Rosenthal, chairman of the Lexington-based Jerrico
Inc., said the stock price, recently about $20 a share, and cash
flow, $70 million a year, could attract unfriendly offers, a prime
factor in the decision to sell.
   ``Once in play, you're gone,'' Rosenthal said.
   Rather than leave the company open for that possibility,
Rosenthal said when he was approached with what seemed like a good
offer from the DJS-Inverness &amp; Co. and Castle Harlan Inc.
investment groups a couple of months ago, he decided to explore it.
   Jerrico's directors agreed to sell to the two New York-based
investment groups for $24.25 in cash per share of common stock.
   Rosenthal and David S. Weil, vice chairman, will retire when the
transaction is completed. Other executives are to receive an
ownership position in the company, which also operates Jerry's,
Florenz and Fazoli's restaurants.
   Jerrico got its start as the White Tavern Shoppes, a small chain
of hamburger stands begun by Jerome Lederer in Shelbyville, Ky., in
1929.
   It soon moved to Lexington and in 1946 started a Jerry's
restaurant. In 1957, under Rosenthal, it began franchising the
family-style restaurant.
   Its first Long John Silver's Seafood Shoppe opened in 1969. The
company, the nation's largest seafood chain, now employs about
18,000 people nationwide.
   But a mature restaurant business has slowed the company's growth
and price increases in fish in recent years cut profit below
anticipated levels. That prompted a slowdown in construction plans,
the layoff of about 60 employees earlier in the year and general
belt tightening.
   Such factors also have prompted speculation in recent months
that the company was a takeover candidate.
   In the past few months, though, Jerrico's fish prices have
declined, and cost cuts have improved its financial picture, said
Leonard Harlan, president of Castle Harlan.
   He and his fellow investors were attracted to Jerrico for those
reasons and because they believe that people, as they become more
health conscious, are eating more fish.
   Harlan's company owns the Peasant Restaurants, a medium- to
higher-priced chain based in Atlanta, and the high-priced Morton's
Restaurants of Chicago.
   DJS-Inverness recently has acquired the S&amp;A Restaurant Corp.,
which operates the Steak &amp; Ale and Bennigan's chains.
   The acquisition is contingent on the investment groups receiving
at least 51 percent of Jerrico's stock under their offer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
