<HEAD>Grant Met Buying United Biscuits Restaurant Business</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grand Metropolitan PLC is to buy United Biscuits
PLC's entire restaurant operation for the equivalent of about $290
million, United Biscuits said Tuesday.
   United Biscuits' restaurant business is made up of 858
restaurants, including the Wimpy hamburger, Pizzaland and Perfect
Pizza chains. It had revenue of about $237 million last year.
   Grand Met, a British liquor, food and leisure company, bought
U.S.-based Pillsbury Co., including the Burger King chain of
fast-food restaurants, for $5.75 billion last year.
   The latest sale is intended to allow United Biscuits, a British
maker of snack foods, to concentrate on its core manufacturing
operations, the company said.
   United Biscuits Chairman Sir Hector Laing said the restaurants
``have found a very good home'' with Grand Met.
   ``By joining Grand Metropolitan's restaurant chain, the
businesses will be participating in the creation of a major
international restaurant chain with a very exciting future,'' he
said.
