<FIRST>r f BC-Reebok-Whaler     08-08 0335</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Reebok-Whaler,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reebok Decides to Buy Boston Whaler for $42 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CANTON, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reebok International Ltd., maker of
athletic shoes and clothing, is branching out in a new direction
with an agreement to buy boat maker Boston Whaler Inc. for about
$42 million.
   Paul Duncan, Reebok chief financial officer, said Monday, ``We
have stated that we were looking to diversify and particularly to
diversify out of footwear. Granted it's a long way from a boat to a
shoe, but we never wanted to be tied to a shoe.''
   Reebok's ambition tied in with plans of CML Group Inc. which
announced last week that it would sell off its Boston Whaler,
Carroll Reed and Sybervision divisions.
   Reebok said that under the agreement, to be completed in 60
days, it will also receive warrants to buy 400,000 shares, or 6
percent, of CML stock for $31.25 per share in the next eight years.
   In composite trading on the New York Stock Exchange Monday, CML
stock closed at $26 a share, down $1. Reebok stock closed at
$14.37{ a share, down 25 cents.
   Boston Whaler, which will give Reebok a foot in the recreational
boating door, has about 500 employees at facilities in Rockland and
at Edgewater, Fla. It reported sales of $66 million in 1988.
   Reebok, a major force in sports and leisure wear, had sales last
year of about $1.8 billion.
   Duncan said Boston Whaler has an easily recognized name in the
boating industry with its ``unsinkable'' hulls, constructed with a
proprietary foam-core material.
   He said the boat company can do better than the 5 percent of the
power boat market it has now. Duncan declined to say what Reebok
plans for the acquisition, except to say there are no plans for
staff or management changes.
   Boston Whalers range in length from nine to 31 feet and sell for
$2,300 to $126,000. The company has had problems this year. It
announced plans to close a leased production plant and layoffs of
170 employees.
</TEXT>
