<DOCNO> AP890808-0200 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-89 1058EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-NewspaperMerger 1stLd-Writethru f0039 08-08 0434</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Newspaper Merger, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0039,0441</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Las Vegas Newspapers File Joint Operating Agreement</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `The agreement...' and 8th graf, `Like many...'
with one graf each to CORRECT that Sun would change from morning to afternoon
publication. This also moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MACY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Las Vegas Review-Journal and Las Vegas Sun,
journalistic rivals for 39 years, have announced plans to merge
their business, circulation and production operations.
   The proposal is a move to save the Sun, which is losing about $3
million a year, has a debt of $10.7 million and has not been
profitable since 1981, according to the proposal for a joint
operating agreement.
   The Sun's founder and feisty editor, Hank Greenspun, who died
July 22, for years sought a JOA with the more powerful
Review-Journal. An agreement was signed by the two papers July 12,
and the plan was announced onday.
   If approved by the U.S. Justice Department, the plan will make
Las Vegas at least the 19th U.S. city to have a JOA.
   The agreement calls for both newspapers to maintain separate
newsrooms and separate weekday editions. The Review-Journal would
remain a morning paper and the Sun would become an afternoon
publication, but combined morning editions, labeled the Las Vegas
Review-Journal-Sun, would be published on Saturdays, Sundays and
holidays.
   ``Without this move we believe the Sun is in probable danger of
financial failure,'' Sun President Brian Greenspun said in a
statement. ``With this move, there will be no displacement of Sun
newsroom personnel and there will be the continuation of an
important newspaper.''
   The Review-Journal is Nevada's largest newspaper and the
flagship for Donrey Media Group, which owns 59 U.S. daily papers.
The Sun is the state's third-largest paper.
   Like many papers in a city with a dominant competitor, the Sun
has been losing circulation. It dropped 8 percent daily and 11
percent Sunday between 1980 and 1988, while the Review-Journal's
circulation increased 50 percent daily and 60 percent on Sunday.
   The Review-Journal's daily circulation at the end of 1988 was
121,321 compared with 50,515 for the Sun. Sunday circulation was
142,923 for the Review-Journal, 54,669 for the Sun.
   Under the JOA, the Sun would receive 10 percent of the operating
profits of the two newspapers and the Review-Journal would receive
90 percent, based on its stronger financial position.
   The Sun will give Donrey Media Group 10 percent of the
outstanding stock in Community Cable TV worth an estimated $20
million and an option to purchase an additional 35 percent of the
stock.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
