<DOCNO> AP890808-0202 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-89 1126EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-CustomerSatisfaction 1stLd-Writethru f0004 08-08 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Customer Satisfaction, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0004,0335</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survey: Acura Buyers Most Satisfied</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Recasts lead to CORRECT, deleting reference to European cars.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Buyers of American cars may be getting happier
with their purchases, but the Japanese-made Acura once again
provides the most customer satisfaction, a new survey says.
   It was the third straight year that the luxury division of
Japan's Honda Motor Co. topped the survey by J.D. Power and
Associates.
   More than 24,000 owners of 1988 model cars were surveyed after
owning their vehicles for a year.
   Buyers of other Honda models and cars made by West Germany's
Mercedes-Benz and Japan's Toyota Motor Corp. followed Acura in
satisfaction. The top-ranked U.S.-produced nameplate was General
Motors Corp.'s Cadillac division, in fifth place.
   Owners of U.S.-made automobiles gave higher marks to their cars
and dealers this year than they had in the past, surpassing
European makes for the first time since the survey began in 1986
and closing the gap between domestics and Asian imports.
   Overall customer satisfaction increased this year as it had
during the three previous years, the survey said.
   The survey covered owners of 35 different nameplates. It
measured satisfaction in 23 areas, including courtesy and interest
of dealership personnel, convenience of service appointment times
and specific questions about vehicle performance.
   The survey was outlined in a news release from J.D. Power
headquarters in Agoura Hills, Calif. The full survey is published
in the August issue of the organization's newsletter.
   Acura, Mercedes-Benz and Honda were ranked Nos. 1-3 in this
year's and last year's surveys. Toyota and Cadillac swapped places
this year from last year's survey.
   The next five, in order of customer satisfaction, were Nissan,
Subaru, a tie between Mazda and BMW, and Buick, the survey said.
   According to the survey's point system, there was a smaller gap
between the top-ranked cars and the bottom-ranked ones, indicating
an increasing level of customer satisfaction among owners of all of
the cars surveyed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
