<HEAD>Grain and Soybean Futures Mixed as Traders Await First of Two Key
Reports</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices opened mixed
today on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Corn lost some support because export business was less than
expected overnight, while wheat gained some strength because
business exceeded expectations.
   But the markets generally held to a narrow range ahead of the
release of the first of two important crop production estimates.
   The first, due out after the close of trading today, will come
from influential private forecaster Conrad Leslie. The second, due
out Thursday, is from the U.S. Department of Agriculture.
   At the opening, wheat was { cent lower to } cent higher, with
the contract for delivery in September at $3.92\ a bushel; corn was
1 cent lower to \ cent higher, with September at $2.25 a bushel;
oats were \ cent to 1 cent higher, with September at $1.39\ a
bushel; and soybeans were { cent lower to 2 cents higher, with
August at $6.03{ a bushel.
   Livestock and pork futures were higher on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange.
   Live cattle were unchanged to .58 cent higher, with August at
74.03 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .27 cent
higher, with August at 84.75 cents a pound; live hogs were
unchanged to .40 cent higher, with August at 47.05 cents a pound;
and frozen pork bellies were .32 cent to .65 cent higher, with
August at 26.62 cents a pound.
