<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-89 1327EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Hewlett-Packard-Samsung     08-08 0183</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hewlett-Packard-Samsung,0191</SECOND>
<HEAD>Korea's Samsung to Make Computers Based on H-P Chip Design</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Korea's Samsung Electronics Co. Ltd. will
make chips and computers based on technology from Hewlett-Packard
Co., the companies said Tuesday.
   The alliance will heat up competition in the low-priced segment
of the market for workstations, which are souped-up personal
computers for scientists, engineers and other power users.
   Hewlett-Packard is hoping to use Samsung's manufacturing
expertise to expand sales of computers based on Hewlett-Packard's
design for streamlined, speedier computers. The design is known as
RISC, for reduced instruction set computing.
   Palo Alto, Calif.-based Hewlett-Packard also manufactures its
own computers but focuses on bigger machines with higher profit
margins. The new computers, which will be sold under the Samsung
and Hewlett-Packard labels, will be priced to compete with
top-of-the-line personal computers as well as low-end workstations
from companies such as Sun Microsystems Inc.
   Last month Hewlett-Packard announced a similar deal with Hitachi
Ltd. That one was for bigger, more expensive workstations.
   Hewlett-Packard became the world's biggest manufacturer of
workstations last year when it acquired Apollo Computer Inc.
</TEXT>
