<FIRST>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     08-08 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dollar-Gold,0366</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Eases, Gold Up</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: An AMs version planned by 5:30 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar finished lower in quiet European
trading Tuesday. Gold prices were little changed.
   Currency dealers said the market's exaggerated reaction to
Friday's better-than-expected U.S. unemployment data left the
dollar ripe for profit-taking.
   However, many traders said they were prepared to move to the
sidelines until Friday when the July U.S. producer price index and
July retail sales data are released, shedding more light on the
state of the American economy and inflation level.
   ``There was a lot of speculation that people in the Far East
were selling a lot of dollars earlier,'' said Manfred Totzauer, a
vice president at Citibank in Frankfurt.
   Alfred Zapfel, chief trader at Bank of Boston in Frankfurt, said
the dollar remained stuck in a range between 1.8800 marks and
1.9200 marks and that he doesn't expect it to break out soon.
   ``I think the dollar wants to go down, but I'm really just not
sure any more,'' Zapfel said. ``There's just not a lot of desire or
ideas in Europe right now.''
   In London, the dollar fell nearly 2 cents against the British
pound. It cost $1.6250 to buy one pound, compared with $1.6075 late
Monday.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell 0.53 yen to a closing 139.25 yen. Later, in
London, it was down to 138.75 yen.
   Other dollar rates at mid morning compared with late Monday:
1.8900 West German marks, down from 1.9055; 1.6270 Swiss francs,
down from 1.6380; 6.3995 French francs, down from 6.4470; 2.1398
Dutch guilders, down from 2.1502; 1,362.50 Italian lire, down from
1,373.50; and 1.1720 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1745.
   Gold traded in London at $365.45 a troy ounce late Tuesday, down
30 cents from late Monday's price. In Zurich the bid price was
$365.85 an ounce, up from $365.40 late Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $1.18 to close at a bid $367.28
an ounce.
   Silver was quoted at a late bid price of $5.16 a troye, down
from Monday's $5.18.
</TEXT>
