<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-89 1453EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-GEClearance     08-08 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-GE Clearance,0315</SECOND>
<HEAD>GE Worker Sues Because Of Allegation of Homosexuality</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KING OF PRUSSIA, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Electric Co. fired an
engineer after a security investigation alleged he was homosexual,
then rehired him 17 days after he filed a federal lawsuit against
the company, the employee claims.
   James M. Wood claims in the lawsuit, which also names the
Department of Defense as a defendant, that his right to due process
was violated when he was laid off in June from his job as an
information systems engineer for GE Aerospace. The job required
government security clearance.
   On July 31, 17 days after he filed the suit, GE rehired him,
giving Wood a similar job in another laboratory and back pay,
Wood's attorney, Cletus Lyman, told The Philadelphia Inquirer.
   Wood called the new job ``a step in the right direction, toward
making decisions based only on my qualifications.''
   Wood and his attorney declined to say whether Wood is a
homosexual, contending that only the perception of homosexuality
caused his application to be derailed.
   In his suit, filed in U.S. District Court, Wood said one of his
bosses told him in May that GE had withdrawn the application for
security clearance. A spokeswoman for the Department of Defense
declined to comment on the lawsuit.
   GE spokesman Don Norton declined comment but said that the
security clearance ``is not a problem because this job does not
require the level of security clearance that was needed for the job
before.''
   In the suit, Wood, 26, of Philadelphia, said the defendants
violated government procedures by never giving him an acceptance or
denial of his clearance application or holding a hearing where he
could confront witnesses or examine the evidence against him.
   The suit, which does not ask for monetary damages, asks that his
application be processed without discrimination.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
