<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-89 1442EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-Norden-UTC     08-08 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Norden-UTC,0320</SECOND>
<HEAD>UTC Division Taken Off the Market</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Longer version planned for AMs.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORWALK, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Technologies Corp. has taken its
Norden Systems subsidiary off the market after more than a year of
looking unsuccessfully for a buyer willing to pay what UTC thought
the radar-systems maker was worth, according to a letter to
employees made public today.
   The letter, from division President Edwin D. Decker, was
distributed to Norden's 3,500 employees Monday.
   Hartford-based UTC announced in April 1988 that it planned to
sell Norden because it didn't feel Norden fit into its overall
plans and would fare better as part of a large defense electronics
company.
   Norden, a $400 million-a-year company, makes radar systems for
aircraft and ships. It also has a contract to make radar systems
for the Federal Aviation Administration.
   UTC had discussions with several companies but ``had but unable
to conclude a sale on terms reflecting the true value of Norden,''
Decker said.
   Decker said Norden management had supported UTC's decision to
solicit bids for the Norwalk-based subsidiary.
   But he said the past year ``has been a frustrating and uncertain
period for all of us,'' noting the company had undergone many
changes, including an ongoing restructuring.
   Although Norden sales had fallen in recent years, the company is
now on the rebound and Decker predicted that Norden would
``complete its turnaround to again contribute to the success of the
corporation.''
   UTC's other divisions include Sikorsky helicopters and Pratt and
Whitney aircraft.
   Norden, founded 60 years ago by Carl Norden, developed the
Norden bombsite used in American bombers at the end of World War II.
   Norden spokesman Scott Brinckerhoff attributed the subsidiary's
recent problems on the fact that there are ``a lot of pitfalls in
building state of the art radar systems.''
   ``Ours is very high risk business,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
