<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-89 2134EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>d f AM-Greece-Boeing     08-08 0224</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greece-Boeing,0232</SECOND>
<HEAD>Purchase of Three Boeing 767's to be Investigated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government Tuesday said an
investigation was being conducted into the ordering by the former
Socialist administration of three Boeing 767 aircraft for Olympic
Airways, Greece's national carrier.
   Transport and Communications Minister Nikos Gelestathis said the
probe was being carried out by the new Olympic Airways board to
determine whether the contract was detrimental to the state and
whether its revision should be sought.
   The contract was signed last September by the Panhellenic
Socialist Movement (PASOK) of Andreas Papandreou. The party was
defeated in national elections in June amid allegations of senior
government members' involvement in a series of financial and arms
scandals.
   The government formed by the conservative New Democracy party
and the Communist-dominated Coalition of the Left and Progress has
pledged to perform a cleanup before holding elections in October.
   The 120- to 150-seat Boeing 767's were bought for $60.8 million
each and two installments have already been paid. Several press
reports have alleged that people close to former Premier Papandreou
took commissions from the sale, but no evidence has been presented
so far.
   Papandreou's new wife, former Olympic Airways stewardess Dimitra
Liani, sent a letter to newspapers on Monday denying a report which
claimed that she was involved in the purchase of the three Boeing
767's.
</TEXT>
