<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Retail     08-08 0218</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Retail,0226</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wal-Mart Posts 22 Percent Profit Rise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Wal-Mart Stores Inc. Tuesday reported a 22 percent gain in its
second-quarter profit, reflecting strong sales growth and inventory
control.
   Wal-Mart, a discounter that is the country's third biggest
retailer, said its income rose to $219 million, or 39 cents a
share, in the quarter ended July 31 from $179.6 million, or 32
cents a share, a year earlier. Sales grew 25 percent to $6.05
billion from $4.85 billion.
   Commenting on the performance, David Glass, Wal-Mart's president
and chief executive officer, said: ``Well-managed inventory levels,
better customer service, and solid sales momentum position us to
meet our sales and earnings objectives for the remaining six months
of this year.''
   In the first six months, Wal-Mart earned $417.3 million, or 74
cents a share, up 25 percent from $333.2 million, or 59 cents a
share, in the first half of 1988. Sales totaled $11.42 billion, up
25 percent from $9.13 bllion.
   Wal-Mart, which ranks after Sears, Roebuck and Co. and K mart
Corp., said it opened 28 new Wal-Mart stores and 3 Sam's Wholesale
clubs during the second quarter.
   The company, based in Bentonville, Ark., operates a total of
1,307 Wal-Mart stores, 109 Sam's Wholesale clubs, 14 Dot Discount
Drug stores and 3 Hypermart USA units.
</TEXT>
