<HEAD>Grain Lower, Soybeans Suffer Double-Digit Loss</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: DELETES description of crop production figures as bullish in
2nd graf.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain futures prices were moderately lower, but
soybeans suffered double-digit losses Tuesday on the Chicago Board
of Trade.
   A wave of selling by several large brokerage houses near the
close forced the November soybean contract to yet another low. One
analyst suggested the late selloff may have been triggered by the
leak of crop production figures from influential private forecaster
Conrad Leslie.
   Leslie's report estimated this year's soybean crop at 1.98
billion bushels and corn at 7.59 billion bushels. Leslie's figures,
above the averages of 1.95 billion for soybeans and 7.53 billion
for corn that had been widely anticipated by the trade, were
supposed to have been embargoed until after the close of trading
Tuesday.
   ``There wasn't any rhyme or reason to it,'' said Vic Lespinasse,
a trader with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc., Chicago. ``The market was
on the defensive all day, but there wasn't any fresh news at the
close.''
   On the close, wheat was 3{ cents lower to unchanged, with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.91{ a bushel; corn was 1{
cents lower to { cent higher, with September at $2.24{ a bushel;
oats were 4 cents to 1{ cents lower, with September at $1.36 a
bushel; and soybeans were 9{ cents to 18{ cents lower, with August
at $5.92 a bushel.
