<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     08-08 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Down, Gold Up</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Precedes LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar drifted lower Tuesday against all
major foreign currencies in listless summer trading.
   Gold prices firmed. On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold
bullion for current delivery rose to $366.20 a troy ounce from
$365.90 late Monday. Republic National Bank of New York said the
late bid for gold was $365.70, up 50 cents.
   Currency dealers said profit-taking following a moderate advance
on Monday helped push the dollar lower, but trading was light in
the absence of any market-moving news and because many traders were
on vacation.
   ``There's really nothing happening. We're sort of in no-man's
land,'' said Robert Ryan, a senior trader with Irving Trust Co.
``The market is just moving on whatever customer orders come in.''
   The dollar moved sharply higher on Friday and continued to
advance at the start of this week on speculation that U.S. interest
rates aren't likely to decline soon. That sentiment followed the
release of better-than-expected employment figures for July, which
showed nonfarm payrolls risng by 169,000 and the jobless rate
falling to 5.2 percent from 5.3 percent in June.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell 0.53 yen to a closing 139.25 yen. It fell
to 138.75 yen in London, and to 138.86 yen in New York, down from
140.05.
   In London, it cost $1.6250 to buy one British pound, compared
with $1.6075 late Monday. Sterling fetched $1.6255 in New York, up
from $1.5980.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Monday's
rates, included: 1.8935 West German marks, down from 1.9160; 1.6288
Swiss francs, down from 1.6475; 1.17195 Canadian dollars, down from
1.17355; 6.4040 French francs, down from 6.4830; and 1,361.00
Italian lire, down from 1,377.50.
   Late dollar rates in Europe compared with Monday: 1.8900 West
German marks, down from 1.9055; 1.6270 Swiss francs, down from
1.6380; 6.3995 French francs, down from 6.4470; 2.1398 Dutch
guilders, down from 2.1502; 1.1720 Canadian dollars, down from
1.1745; and 1,362.50 Italian lire, down from 1,373.50.
   Gold traded late in London at $365.45 an ounce, down 30 cents
from Monday's price. In Zurich the late bid price was $365.85 an
ounce, up from $365.40 Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $1.18 to close at a bid $367.28
an ounce.
   Silver prices were mixed. On New York's Comex, silver bullion
for current delivery rose to $5.156 a troy ounce from $5.128. But
silver fell in London to $5.16 an ounce from $5.18.
</TEXT>
