<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-89 2019EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Earns-Commodore     08-08 0250</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Commodore,0260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Commodore Loses $8.9 Million In Fourth Fiscal Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST CHESTER, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Commodore International Ltd. lost $8.9
million in its fourth fiscal quarter, blaming a strong dollar in
Europe and high interest rates in Australia for a 16 percent drop
in sales, the computer maker announced Tuesday.
   Commodore for months had been warning investors it would lose
money in the quarter that ended June 30. Its stock rose 50 cents a
share to $10.50 on the New York Stock Exchange.
   A strong U.S. dollar has cut into sales and decreased earnings
when exchanging foreign currency for U.S. dollars, the company said.
   The company plans to compensate for the strong dollar in Europe
by keeping price reductions to a minimum and warily increasing
prices on selected products in selected areas, Commodore treasurer
Carden Welsh said.
   High interest rates in Australia, another important market for
Commodore, hurt consumer spending there, Welsh said.
   The loss came on sales of $180.3 million. For the same period
last year, the company earned $12.2 million, or 38 cents per share,
on sales of $215.2 million.
   For the fiscal year, Commodore's earnings dropped 8 percent to
$51.3 million, or $1.59 per share, on sales of $939.7 million. In
the last fiscal year, the company earned $55.8 million, or $1.75
per share, on sales of $871.1 million.
   The company received a $1.2 million tax benefit in 1989 by
carrying forward losses from previous years. In 1988 the tax carry
forward was worth $7.6 million.
</TEXT>
