<FIRST>u f AM-MidwayOffer Bjt   08-08 0472</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Midway Offer, Bjt,0490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ampco-Pittsburgh Announces 6.6 Percent Stake in Airline</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ampco-Pittsburgh Corp., a low-profile metal
manufacturer, announced Tuesday it has acquired a 6.6 percent
interest in Midway Airlines Inc. and may someday attempt to take
control of the mid-sized airline.
   Midway ``has no interest in being acquired'' and has not had
discussions with Ampco-Pittsburgh Corp., said David R. Hinson, the
airline chairman and chief executive.
   Midway is a 10-year-old airline that ranks 16th in size in the
United States, with 0.8 percent of the nation's air traffic. Its
hub at Midway Airport appeals to business travelers because it is
closer to downtown Chicago.
   Ampco-Pittsburgh and its subsidiaries _ which include Buffalo
Forge Co. and Union Electric Steel Corp. _ make and sell engineered
products such as fans and pumps.
   The company is a mystery to some airline analysts.
   ``They aren't a big player. I've never heard of them,'' said Bob
Joedicke, an analyst for Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York.
   In a filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission in
Washington, Ampco-Pittsburgh said it had acquired 662,000 shares of
Midway common stock through a Delaware subsidiary, Ampco-Pittsburgh
Securities III Corp.
   In a statement issued in Chicago, Midway Airlines confirmed that
Ampco-Pittsburgh holds 6.6 percent of its outstanding stock.
   Ampco-Pittsburgh said it bought the Midway shares ``for
investment and to acquire a significant equity interest'' in the
Chicago-based airline.
   The SEC disclosure document also said Ampco and its subsidiaries
``may also consider seeking to acquire control'' of Midway ``in the
future, although they have no plans or proposals to do so at
present.''
   Midway was founded 10 years ago at the start of airline
deregulation, when it served three Midwest cities from Chicago _
Cleveland, Detroit and Kansas City, said spokeswoman Sandra Allen.
   The airline now serves 51 U.S. cities, from Los Angeles to
Boston, and from Chicago to Miami, she said.
   Midway recently announced it had ordered for 74 new jets from
McDonnell-Douglas Corp. worth about $2 billion.
   According to the filing, Ampco-Pittsburgh Securities III bought
the Midway shares at prices ranging from $14.75 to $18 between July
25 and last Thursday for a total of $10.3 million.
   Last week, Midway announced it had reached an agreement with
Miami-based Eastern Airlines to purchase routes, gates and aircraft
from the strike-plagued carrier for $210 million.
   The proposed sale covers gates at Philadelphia International
Airport and Eastern routes from Philadelphia to Montreal and
Toronto. It also includes operating slots at Washington's National
Airport and New York's LaGuardia Airport, 16 DC-9 jetliners and
spare engine and parts.
   The Canadian routes would represent Midway's first international
flights, Ms. Allen said.
   The agreement must be approved by a federal bankruptcy court
judge as part of Eastern's strike-recovery plan to restructure into
a smaller airline.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
