<DOCNO> AP890808-0225 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-89 1805EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     08-08 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0338</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Prices Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices rose Tuesday in light
trading, pushed up by buyers hoping for a drop in oil inventories.
   The American Petroleum Institute's weekly statistics on oil
stocks were due out after the close of trading.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, West Texas Intermediate
crude for delivery in Septemer rose 21 cents to close at $18.12.
WTI, the benchmark grade of light U.S. crude, fell 12 cents on
Monday in another quiet session.
   Contracts for delivery later in the year also showed gains but
closed below $18 a barrel.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, unleaded gasoline
for September rose 0.69 cent to finish at 50.44 a gallon, while
September heating oil gained 0.12 cent to a settlement price of
48.56 cents a gallon.
   Except for a few upward blips, crude prices have been falling
since late July. The September contract has lost 42 cents since
July 25, when it traded at $18.54.
   Analysts said the latest gains came on expectations that last
week's hurricane in the Gulf of Mexico would reduce some of the
inventories that have been building lately. Sluggish demand and
excess production by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries have increased the supplies of crude and gasoline in
storage.
   ``People were buying ahead of the APIs,'' said John Hill, energy
broker for Merrill Lynch Energy Futures. ``Because of the hurricane
last week people think there will be a drawdown in inventories.''
   The storm forced the shutdown of some refineries, delaying the
production of gasoline and other refined products.
   Despite the advance, some traders said the underlying weakness
in the market remains and prices could fall further.
   ``We expect prices to continue on a downtrend,'' said Randall
Rothenberg, trader with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. ``It might not be
tomorrow or the next day but we expect the market to go down before
it comes out of this doldrum.''
</TEXT>
