<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     08-08 0614</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0637</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cotton Futures Prices Rise Sharply; Soybeans Fall</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Cotton futures prices made an abrupt about-face Tuesday, surging
to the upper reaches of the daily trading limit after falling
nearly their daily limit in the previous session.
   On other markets, soybeans suffered big losses after a wave of
selling near the close, and crude oil futures broke back above the
$18-a-barrel plateau.
   The sharp price swings in cotton appeared to reflect uncertainty
over the size and quality of the crop in advance of a U.S.
Department of Agriculture crop production report due out Thursday.
   ``It seems the market at some point (Wednesday) discovered the
rains Tuesday in Texas weren't as beneficial as originally
thought,'' said Sandra Kaul of Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc., New
York.
   Traders speculated that extremely dry conditions in Texas may
have lowered the yield there, while unusually wet weather
throughout the growing areas of the Delta during the spring and
summer is believed to have adversely affected much of the crop
there.
   Many fields in both regions apparently have been so devastated
that growers with marginal crops are considering abandoning the
acreage or trying to plant another crop.
   Cotton settled 1.86 cents to the limit-up 2 cents higher on the
New York Cotton Exchange, with the contract for delivery in October
at 74.80 cents a pound.
   Grain futures prices eased slightly, but soybean prices absorbed
a more direct hit on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   ``There wasn't any rhyme or reason to it,'' said Vic Lespinasse,
a trader with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc., Chicago. ``The market was
on the defensive all day, but there wasn't any fresh news at the
close.''
   The USDA's influential crop production report is set for release
Thursday.
   Wheat settled 3{ cents lower to unchanged, with September at
$3.91{ a bushel; corn was 1\ cents lower to { cent higher, with
September at $2.24\ a bushel; oats were 3 cents to 1{ cents lower,
with September at $1.36 a bushel; and soybeans were 9 cents to 18
cents lower, with August at $5.92{ a bushel.
   Crude oil futures, at $20 a barrel three weeks ago, had been
tending downward since. But the price climbed above $18 and held
the line Tuesday at the New York Mercantile Exchange, pulling the
products along.
   ``I'd call $18 more a psychological support level than anything
else, but the trade tends to rally on round numbers,'' said Jim
Ritterbusch of Carson Petroleum Co., Chicago.
   Crude oil climbed 3 cents to 21 cents higher, with September at
$18.12 a barrel; heating oil settled .12 cent to .49 cent higher,
with September at 48.56 cents a gallon; and unleaded gasoline was
.20 cent to .85 cent higher, with September at 50.44 cents a gallon.
   Livestock futures were mixed, but pork futures mostly lower on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .60 cent lower to .48 cent higher, with August
at 74.30 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .03 cent lower to .15
cent higher, with August at 84.57 cents a pound; live hogs were .20
cent lower to .45 cent higher, with August at 47.10 cents a pound;
and frozen pork bellies were .98 cent lower to .02 cent higher,
with August at 25.37 cents a pound.
   Precious metal futures finished mostly higher in the wake of a
weakening U.S. dollar.
   Gold was 40 cents lower to 30 cents higher on the Comex, with
September at $366.20 a troy ounce; silver was 2.8 cents to 3.5
cents higher, with September at 515.6 cents a troy ounce. Platinum,
traded on the New York Merc, settled $4.10 to $5.50 higher, with
September at $485.70 a troy ounce.
</TEXT>
