<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-89 1843EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Norden-UTC     08-08 0589</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Norden-UTC,0609</SECOND>
<HEAD>UTC Takes Norden Off Market</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEAN GOLEMBESKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORWALK, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A year in corporate limbo ended for Norden
Systems Inc. with the announcement Tuesday that the subsidiary of
United Technologies Corp. is no longer for sale.
   The Norwalk-based manufacturer of radar systems and other
electronic military equipment was put up for sale in April 1988,
but UTC decided to keep it after receiving offers it said were
inadequate.
   Norden's 3,460 employees learned of the decision Monday in a
letter from division President Edwin D. Decker. The letter was made
public Tuesday.
   ``It wasn't a grudging kind of decision. It really wasn't. I'm
pleased to be able to say that, because if it was I'd really be
feeling bad and I'm not,'' Decker, who participated in the
decision, said during an interview at his office.
   ``They would be delighted to have us return to profitability,
and that's what we're going to do,'' Decker said, predicting Norden
would begin to improve its bottom line after 1990.
   Security analyst Michael Bunyaner, vice president of research
with Oppenheimer &amp; Co. in New York, said Norden was pulled off the
auction block because ``the market is glutted with defense-related
businesses.''
   ``It's not as an attractive property as it was a year ago,'' he
said.
   Norden has been part of Hartford-based UTC since 1958.
   Decker said UTC came close to selling the company on more than
one occasion. But he said no offers were made that came close to
what UTC executives and Decker thought was a fair price for the
$400 million-a-year company. Decker declined to name the suitors.
   ``There was a lot of good interest by a couple of substantial
companies that were intrigued with our technological
capabilities,'' he said.
   Since 1988, Norden has eliminated nearly 700 jobs, including 400
that were announced in late May when a restructuring plan was
revealed. Decker said more jobs might be cut after this year.
   Norden has been posting losses since 1986. Those losses resulted
in part from cost overruns and demands for additional investments
in four new radar systems that were being developed simultaneously
by Norden for the military. Decker said the company spent
``hundreds of millions of dollars'' in development costs over the
past four years.
   In April Norden was eliminated in April as a subcontractor to
General Dynamics Corp. for the Navy's Advanced Tactical Aircraft,
or A-12. Norden had spent $114 million to design and develop the
radar system for the A-12.
   Norden has filed suit in Stamford Superior Court seeking
unspecified damages from General Dynamics. General Dynamics, which
canceled the contract because it was reportedly dissatisfied with
Norden's performance, has sought to have the suit dismissed because
of the top-secret nature of the project.
   Decker declined comment on the lawsuit, but said work on the two
remaining radar systems is progressing. He said Norden is in the
flight-test stage for both radar systems, the final step before
they are put in operation.
   Norden, founded 60 years ago by Carl Norden, developed the
Norden bombsite used in American bombers at the end of World War
II. Since that time, virtually all of Norden's business has been
for the military.
   Decker said the company has no plans to expand into
non-defense-related areas and soon will announce details of two
contracts signed in the past two weeks. He revealed that the
contracts are worth a total of $60 million.
   UTC's other divisions include Sikorsky helicopters, Pratt &amp;
Whitney aircraft, Otis elevators, and Carrier air conditioners.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
