<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-89 2035EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-China-FeedGrains     08-08 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Feed Grains,0448</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Still Potential Customers for U.S. Grain; Timetable Unclear</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT LEE ZIMMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China still could be a big customer for U.S.
grain but recent internal turmoil could delay progress developing
that market, an official of the U.S. Feed Grains Council said
Tuesday.
   Wuu Hao, director of the council's operation in China, said the
country is short on cash to buy feed grain.
   But, with more than a billion people to feed, China needs to
have more grain _ both for feeding to livestock for meat production
and for making consumer products from corn flakes to beer.
   ``They have to improve the diets,'' said Hao. ``Without happy
citizens, nothing will work.''
   The Feed Grains Council will continue to focus on improving
livestock feed production in China and on teaching the Chinese
modern livestock production techniques, he said.
   The poultry industry holds the greatest potential for growth in
China because it offers faster profits and, as a relatively new
industry, faces fewer government restrictions, he said.
   But pork remains the main meat in the Chinese diet. Hao said 80
percent of the total meat consumption is pork, but production
techniques are very primitive _ usually a couple of pigs in the
yard eating crop waste.
   Only 10 percent of China's 300 million hogs are fed a modern,
blended feed ration, Hao said, adding that U.S. Feed Grains Council
representatives are working with the Chinese to change that.
   In addition, the Chinese have started buying better swine
breeding stock.
   Eventually, Hao said that will mean a demand for more feed
grain. But the Chinese currently can afford to import only ``wheat
flour to fill stomachs'' of the people, he said.
   ``The market right now is not very much because they just don't
have the foreign exchange,'' said Hao.
   ``It's still too early to assess'' the impact of this summer's
violence on trade with the United States, he said.
   Hao said he and the four people on his staff left China during
the fighting because they did not know what to expect, but have
since returned to resume work in China.
   Among their projects are sending 4,000 technical brochures on
livestock feeding quarterly to government officials, schools and
others who could spread the information; working with Chinese
producers on feed quality control to make sure animals are getting
the nutrition they need; and teaching feed management to producers.
   The U.S. Feed Grains Council, a private organization of farm and
agribusiness groups, was formed in 1960 to promote export markets
for U.S. corn, barley and sorghum.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
