<FIRST>r f AM-AFL-CIO     08-08 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AFL-CIO,0398</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kirkland Says Union Movement Strong Despite Nissan Defeat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   AFL-CIO President Lane Kirkland said Tuesday that
organized labor is at odds with the Bush administration on a number
of issues.
   But Kirkland, speaking at a news conference during the summer
meeting of the AFL-CIO Executive Council, the union federation's
governing board, said he didn't want to pass judgment on President
Bush after just seven months in office.
   He said the labor movement's disagreements with Bush are on
issues such as the minimum wage, child care and the Eastern
Airlines strike.
   ``That's not a very good beginning of a presidential term from
my point of view,'' Kirkland said.
   He said the federation supports the formation of a federal
emergency board that would resolve the dispute between Eastern, its
pilots, flight attendants and Machinists union members.
   Kirkland said the executive council will meet with leaders of
the Air Line Pilots Association about organized labor's efforts on
behalf of striking Eastern workers.
   Kirkland also said the labor movement remains viable despite the
defeat two weeks ago of efforts by the United Auto Workers union to
organize workers at a Japanese auto plant in Tennessee.
   Kirkland said the organizing efforts at the Nissan Motor Co.
plant in Smyrna, Tenn., have been deferred, not defeated.
   ``We have a long history of many years of efforts to organize
some of the firms we have succeeded in organizing in this country,
including the automobile industry, where our initial efforts were
defeated time and again,'' he said. ``But we persevered. We're not
defeated as long as we stay in the game.''
   In what was expected to be a close vote, Nissan workers on July
26 and 27 voted by more than 2-1 against unionizing the plant.
   Kirkland also said the federation is engaged in an experimental
effort to attract new members at plants that have yet to be
organized.
   He said the effort involves giving workers at plants targeted
for organization associate membership, with full membership granted
once a collective bargaining agreement is reached with the employer.
   The executive council passed resolutions Tuesday opposing
reductions in the capital gains tax, advocating the strengthening
of the Clean Air Act and criticizing recent U.S. Supreme Court
rulings on affirmative action.
</TEXT>
