<FIRST>u f AM-USAir-Buffett     08-08 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-USAir-Buffett,0449</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Oracle of Omaha' Turns Sights on USAir</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Midway Offer, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nebraska investor Warren E. Buffett, often
perceived as a ``white squire'' riding to the aid of besieged
companies, has turned his sights on USAir Group Inc.
   Buffett has agreed to buy 12 percent to 14 percent of the
airline holding company's stock through a new issue valued at $358
million, a move that could block a hostile takeover.
   USAir stock closed Monday at $53 a share, up $1, on the New York
Stock Exchange. The announcement of Buffet's move Monday came after
the market's close. On Tuesday, the stock hit a high of $53 but
then slipped to end at $51.12{.
   The news of Buffett's purchase was both preceded and followed by
more takeover frenzy in the airline industry. Earlier Monday, an
unsolicited offer for UAL Corp. from investor Marvin Davis sent
shares of United Airlines' parent soaring.
   On Tuesday, a Pittsburgh-based manufacturing company said it has
acquired a 6.6 percent stake in Midway Airlines and indicated it
might seek to take over the carrier.
   The billionaire Buffett, known as the ``Oracle of Omaha'' for
his canny investments and forthright business advice, has a
reputation for taking sizable stakes in a limited number of
companies and holding them, sometimes for years.
   Buffett, who made a fortune buying little-known stocks, also
owns bi He owns the Buffalo News
newspaper.
   He played the role of friendly squire to razor maker Gillette,
the object of two hostile takeover bids in three years.
   Under the USAir deal, Buffet would agree not to sell the stock
to a bidder for 10 years without the approval of the airline's
board of directors, except under limited conditions.
   USAir, which has its headquarters in Arlington, Va., is
incorporated in Delaware. That state's laws make it difficult to
acquire a company without obtaining 85 percent of its shares.
   USAir stock has risen steadily in the past three weeks as
takeover speculation has swept the airline industry. Last month,
New York money manager Michael Steinhardt sent the stock soaring
when he told federal regulators he might try to take over the
airline.
   In a press release, Buffett said it was unusual for him to
invest in a capital- and labor-intensive industry. The USAir stock
purchase, he said, showed his ``high regard for (Chairman) Ed
Colodny's management.''
   Buffett is buying preferred shares that will yield a 9.25
percent annual dividend and can be converted to common shares at
$60 a share.
</TEXT>
