<FIRST>u f BC-DartDrug-Chapter11     08-08 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dart Drug-Chapter 11,0383</SECOND>
<HEAD>Washington-Area Drug Chain Seeks Chapter 11</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LANDOVER, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dart Drug Stores Inc., one of Washington's
best-known retailing names which now operates under the name of
Fantle's Drugstores, filed Tuesday for bankruptcy court protection
from creditors.
   ``We ... deeply regret having to take the step of filing for
bankruptcy relief,'' Sheldon Fantle, Dart's chairman, said in a
statement. ``Our board determined that it was far better to take
this step now, while our company has substantial resources to
implement a plan of reorganization.''
   Fantle led a group of investors that took over management of the
company in November 1987. At that time, Dart owed more than $164
million to bondholders and to its bank lenders. It has paid more
than $26 million in principal and interest payments on that debt.
   ``We came to the conclusion that the company simply could not
afford to continue to make payments on that amount of debt,'' said
Fantle.
   Dart operates 69 retail drug stores in the Washington, D.C.,
area, of which Landover is a suburb, and five Total-Plus discount
stores in the Richmond, Va., area. Dart has more than 2,000
employees.
   In the quarter ended April 29, it lost $7.3 million on revenue
of $39.2 million against a loss of $9.6 million on revenue of $54.1
million in the corresponding quarter a year earlier.
   In the nine months ended April 29, the company lost $16.6
million on sales of $128.8 million compared with a loss of $13.3
million on sales of $174.9 million in the corresponding
year-earlier period.
   Dart Drug Stores was founded in 1954 by Herbert Haft, who sold
the company to a management group in 1984 before going on to make a
series of unsuccessful corporate takeover attempts under the mantle
of his Dart Group Corp., which is unrelated to the drugstore chain.
   Fantle attempted to revamp the company by remodeling stores,
placing new emphasis on customer service, restructuring the
company's finances and starting an unusual plan to donate 5 percent
of the company's gross receipts to charity.
   The company filed its bankruptcy petition in U.S. Bankruptcy
Court in Rockville. Under Chapter 11, management may be permitted
to operate the company while developing a reorganization plan.
</TEXT>
