<FIRST>u f AM-Japan-Markets     08-08 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Opens Lower, Share Prices Edge Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar opened lower against the Japanese
yen Wednesday morning, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange edged up.
   The dollar opened at 138.72 yen, down 0.53 yen from Tuesday's
close of 139.25 yen. In New York, it ended at 138.88 yen overnight.
   Traders said the dollar's lower opening in Tokyo, following its
losses in New York, was mainly due to concern over the U.S. Federal
Reserve Board's monetary policy, which investors think might move
further toward relaxation.
   Toru Kanai, a foreign exchange analyst with the New Japan
Securities Co., said the dollar is in a downward trend.
   Market players were also reluctant to increase their dollar
positions ahead of the release of the U.S. wholesale price index
for July, scheduled for Friday.
   ``To see whether the U.S. economy is really slowing down or not,
market players are very much concerned about the figure as an
important indicator,'' Kanai said.
   ``The dollar edged up following last Friday's jobless rate
report, but the rate is going back to where it was before,'' he
said.
   Early last week, the dollar was trading in a range around 136
yen. But following the release of a lower-than-expected July U.S.
unemployment figure of 5.2 percent, indicating continuing strength
in the economy, the dollar moved up.
   He said trading Wednesday was light in the absence of
market-affecting incentives.
   On the stock exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected
issues gained 63.23 points to move to 34,822.71 within the first 15
minutes of trading. It had gained 129.10 points Wednesday, its
first gain in the last four trading days.
   Dealers said the Nikkei rose following the yen's strength
against the dollar, as well as overnight gains in the Dow Jones
industrial average of 30 major issues in New York. The Dow Jones
index rose by 4.18 points.
   Participants were mainly buying chemical, paper and finance
issues.
</TEXT>
