<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-QuakerOats     08-08 0214</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Quaker Oats,0222</SECOND>
<HEAD>Earnings Offset by Non-Recurring Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Quaker Oats Co. said Tuesday that non-recurring
charges cut into the food giant's quarterly profit.
   For the quarter ended June 30, Chicago-based Quaker reported a
profit of $87.2 million, or 71 cents a share, compared with
earnings of $159.1 million, or $1.18 a share, in the same quarter
of 1988.
   Quaker reported revenues of $1.56 billion for the period, which
is the fourth quarter in the company's fiscal year, compared with
revenues of $1.49 billion for the same period in fiscal 1988.
   For the fiscal year ended June 30, Quaker reported a profit of
$328.7 million, or $2.56 a share, compared with a profit of $413.6
million, or $3.20 a share, in its fiscal 1988.
   Revenue for the 12 months totaled $5.72 billion, compared with
$5.33 billion in fiscal 1988.
   The fiscal 1989 results were offest by charges of $124 million
due to plant consolidations and overhead reduction, officials said.
In addition, a charge of about $26 million was taken for a change
in accounting proceedures.
   ``Excluding the various restructuring charges associated with
our steps to keep Quaker a low-cost producer of premier brands, our
overall performance was again at a record level,'' said William D.
Smithburg, chairman and chief operating officer.
